<FIRST>u a AM-MissAmerica-Preliminaries 2ndLd-Writethru a0824 09-12
0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miss America-Preliminaries, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0824,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miss Missouri, Miss Ohio Win Preliminary Miss America Competitions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 15 grafs to UPDATE with quotes from winners; picks
up 7th graf pvs: `Tuesday's competition ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XCC4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miss Ohio won the talent competition
and Miss Missouri won the swimsuit contest in the first preliminary
competition of the Miss America Pageant on Tuesday.
   Kristin Huffman, 24, sang a classical vocal piece titled
``Csardas'' to win the talent contest. She performed in a tomato-red
sheath trimmed in gold sequins and a flowing red train, and carried
a sequined mask trimmed in red ostrich feathers.
   Miss Huffman, a olive-eyed blonde from Canal Winchester, Ohio,
hopes to perform at the concert level and teach voice at a college.
   She said her performance was magnified because her parents _ both
singers _ were in the audience.
   ``I felt good vibes from them,'' she said.
   Miss Huffman said she knew she performed well because ``the heat
was coming off me.''
   She graduated from Northwestern University with a masters in
music. For 21 years, she has performed with her family's
professional singing group for community, business and church groups.
   She has also assisted in special musical educational programs for
the mentally handicapped and founded a singing group called
``Friends &amp; Neighbors.''
   Miss Huffman, however, said the preliminary win does not
guarantee her the crown. ``I don't plan on relaxing,'' she said.
``This is only the beginning.''
   In the swimsuit competition, Debbye Turner, a 5-foot-7{,
118-pound University of Missouri senior, won in a canary yellow
swimsuit.
   Miss Turner, 23, from Mexico, Mo., hopes to become a veterinarian
specializing in small animal internal medicine. She works out by
swimming and weight lifting.
   After winning, she said all she could think about while walking
down the runway were the five cookies she had for dinner. ``I was
hungry,'' she said. ``I don't believe in starving.''
   Miss Turner said she was probably ``a little smaller'' three
months ago when she won her state pageant, but had still worked hard
to maintain her shape for the national competition.
   ``Being on stage in a swimsuit does motivate one not to have a
tummy,'' she said.
   Tuesday's competition was the first of three nights of swimsuit,
talent and evening gown rounds. The winners of the preliminary
evening gown competitions are kept secret to heighten the suspense
for the finals.
   The three preliminary competitions for the 51 contestants are the
first steps to the live televised Miss America Pageant on Saturday.
On Friday night, the contestants participate in the famous Miss
America Parade on the resort's Boardwalk.
   The 10 women who have accumulated the most points in preliminary
competitions and interviews with the judges will compete to succeed
Miss America 1989 Gretchen Elizabeth Carlson.
   After the three preliminary nights, the total scores will
determine the finalists, and those 10 then start over again Saturday
night.
   In the final night's judging before a new panel of celebrity
judges, talent counts for 40 percent, evening gown for 15 percent
and swimsuit for 15 percent. The interview with the preliminary
judges is carried over from earlier in the week to count for 30
percent of the score.
   The 63rd annual pageant will be broadcast live on NBC at 10 p.m.
EDT Saturday. Gary Collins and Miss America 1971 Phyllis George
Brown will host.
</TEXT>
