<FIRST>r a AM-PSNHBankruptcy 1stLd-Writethru a0657 09-12 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PSNH Bankruptcy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0657,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede MANCHESTER, N.H.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Public Service Reaches Agreement On Bankruptcy Reorganization Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: NEW THROUGHOUT to UPDATE with details of New England Electric
System plan, reax; tightens; no pickup. ADDS byline. Also moved on financial
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE RECHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public Service Company of New Hampshire said
Tuesday it has agreed with creditors and shareholders on major
points of a bankruptcy reorganization plan, but Gov. Judd Gregg said
the state had found a better deal.
   The agreement was reached three days ahead of a deadline set by
the federal bankruptcy court in Manchester for reorganization plans
and for buyout offers from other utilities.
   But Gregg told reporters at a news conference that a deal by
Massachusetts-based New England Electric System was ``a dramatic
improvement'' over proposals by Public Service and Connecticut-based
Northeast Utilities.
   Gregg, who earlier backed the Northeast Utilities plan, said the
New England Electric proposal has the state's ``primary
endorsement.''
   New England Electric said that under its plan, electricity rates
for New Hampshire customers would increase 4.8 percent for each of
the next seven years, regardless of whether the Seabrook nuclear
plant operates.
   The $6.2 billion plant, finished three years ago, is idle for
lack of a federal operating license. Public Service is the plant's
lead owner.
   The Public Service and Northeast Utilities plans call for 5.5
percent increases for seven years, and additional 1.1 percent hikes
for five of those years if Seabrook never operates.
   Northeast Utilities is offering about $1.9 billion for Public
Service, whether or not Seabrook runs; New England Electric's offer
is $2 billion if Seabrook runs, $1.9 billion if it is canceled; and
Public Service valued its new proposal at $2.2 billion.
   Public Service said creditors and investors already accepted the
major points of its proposal, which means its plan could be
implemented much sooner than the other two, which don't have such
approval.
   Wilbur Ross of Rothschild Inc., financial advisers to the
committee that represents Public Service stockholders, said they
agreed to the Public Service plan ``very reluctantly because it's
very painful.'' He said it represented losses of $1 billion to
stockholders and $300 million to bondholders.
   He said the New England Electric plan would inflict another $200
million in losses on investors.
   Northeast spokesman Jeffrey Kotkin declined to compare plans
without seeing details of his competitors' proposals.
   Details of all plans must be submitted to bankruptcy Judge James
Yacos by Friday. Yacos plans hearings on the proposals into
mid-November, and then shareholders and creditors will vote on the
plans.
   Public Service, the state's largest electric utility, filed for
bankruptcy protection in January 1988 under the burden of its 36
percent share of the Seabrook plant.
   Public Service had been unable to agree with creditors,
shareholders and the state on a reorganization plan, and the state
still is holding out.
</TEXT>
