<FIRST>r a AM-RockyFlatsPond     09-12 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rocky Flats Pond,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rocky Flats Alert Called Off; Dam Called Safe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to CORRECT category code.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant was
put on alert Tuesday because state officials feared that an earthen
dam might fail, sending herbicide-contaminated water from a holding
pond into suburban water supplies.
   State health officials said they were concerned more that the
runoff water holding pond contains herbicides than its radiation,
which is ``low but measurable'' and comparable with other water
sources around the state.
   Holding Pond C2 empties into Woman's Creek and from there into
Standley Lake, which provides drinking water for the suburban Denver
communites of Westminster, Thornton and Northglenn.
   Rocky Flats, which manufactures plutonium triggers for nuclear
weapons, is 16 miles northwest of Denver and is operated for the
Department of Energy by Rockwell International Corp.
   DOE officials had expressed concern about the earthen dam when
heavy rainfall filled the pond to 75 percent of capacity. They asked
the state Department of Health for permission to release some water
without treating it.
   The state Office of Emergency Preparedness, which coincidentally
was holding a drill at Rocky Flats on Tuesday morning, at 10 a.m.
issued an alert, the third-highest level of preparedness for the
facility.
   In a 2:30 p.m. news conference, Colorado dropped its alert after
an inspector for the state engineer's office declared the dam was
sound.
   Health officials denied DOE's request to release the water
without treating it, saying the pond contains the herbicide
atrazine, a possible carcinogen, as well as manganese and sulfide.
   FBI agents and EPA investigators raided the plant earlier this
summer for evidence of illegal dumping of hazardous materials. A
federal grand jury is investigating the matter.
</TEXT>
