<SECOND>PM-BRF--Hopkinton Gag Order, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0410,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Town Agrees to Settle Gag-Order Case for $1,500</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st three grafs to clarify</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three former Hopkinton police dispatchers
will share $1,500 from the town for being told they couldn't write
letters to the editor.
   Lynette Labinger, the American Civil Liberties Union attorney who
handled the case, said the town agreed Monday to pay each of the
former dispatchers $500 to settle their U.S. District Court lawsuit.
The town also accepted an injunction against barring future letter
writing by police dispatchers, Labinger said.
   The three had drafted a letter to The Westerly Sun last year
complaining about the Town Council's decision to lower their salary
increases.
   They argued they were ``grossly underpaid'' and should earn more
than clerical employees because dispatchers made life-and-death
decisions.
   After a reporter made inquiries about doing an article on the
dispute, Police Chief George Weeden barred the dispatchers from
sending the letter. The ACLU claimed that was a violation of their
free-speech rights.
   ``We're confident we would have prevailed at trial, but this was
a good and easy way to settle it,'' said Town Solicitor Patricia A.
Buckley.
</TEXT>
