<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 0138EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-SaudiOil Bjt   09-12 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Saudi Oil, Bjt,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration in Talks with Saudis on Leasing Emergency Oil Stocks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is seeking to save
money on U.S. emergency oil reserves by possibly leasing _ rather
than buying _ oil from Saudi Arabia and other major producers,
sources say.
   Saudi Oil Minister Hisham Nazer expressed his government's
interest in the idea during private talks last Thursday with Energy
Secretary James D. Watkins, although no specific proposals were made
by either side, the sources said.
   The talks with the Saudis and other potential foreign suppliers _
including Norway, Kuwait, Venezuela and the United Arab Emirates _
are in a preliminary stage and the United States has made no
decision to shift from the current practice of buying and holding
title to all the oil put into the oil reserve, sources said.
   The main reason for leasing would be to reduce the cost of
filling the Strategic Petroleum Reserve, which was created in 1975
in response to the 1973 Arab oil embargo led by Saudi Arabia. Mexico
currently is the exclusive supplier under a sales contract due to
expire Nov. 30 and providing 60,000 barrels a day.
   The oil is held in underground salt caverns in Louisiana and
Texas. Congress earlier this year ordered the Energy Department to
study leasing and to assess interest among foreign suppliers.
   Nazer told Watkins his government was interested in a crude
leasing deal as a way of strengthening Saudi ties to the United
States, which is the largest market for Saudi crude, said the
sources, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``They're very interested,'' one source said, adding that leasing
was the first subject raised by Nazer in the meeting at Energy
Department headquarters.
   No details of a possible leasing deal were discussed, and Watkins
told Nazer the next step could be a meeting of the two sides'
technical experts, the source said, adding that senior U.S. and
Saudi officials will pursue the matter further during regularly
scheduled talks in October.
   James Akins, who served as U.S. ambassador to Saudi Arabia from
1973-76, said a leasing arrangement would appear to be a good move
for the Bush administration.
   ``From the point of view of the United States it's an
extraordinary good deal,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``I
can't see anything wrong with it, although I can't see any greater
economic benefit for the Saudis.''
   Leasing rather than buying additional oil could be cheaper and
could allow the administration to fill the reserve faster. Some
critics have noted that because the nation is importing more of its
daily crude requirements, the strategic reserve's value as an
emergency fallback is diminishing.
   At one point in 1985 the reserve held the equivalent of 115 days'
worth of U.S. oil imports. Now it holds 73 days' worth, even though
the reserve itself has continued to grow.
   The Energy Department has not yet worked out the mechanics of a
possible leasing arrangement, although it is expected that a lease
would allow the United States to take possession of the oil in the
event of an emergency, the source said. A means of setting a
purchase price would be included, too.
   ``We're at the stage of entertaining any bright ideas'' about how
a lease could be structured, said one source.
   Norway also has expressed interest in the leasing idea, although
it has far less unused production capacity that could be activated
for such a supply arrangement than do the Saudis.
   Tore Sandvold, energy counselor at the Norwegian Embassy, said he
discussed leasing with Energy Department officials in August. He
said his government had made no decisions on the matter and ``it's
really just in the question-and-answer stage right now.''
   Mexico has rejected the leasing idea, one U.S. source said, while
Kuwait, Venezuela and the United Arab Emirates have indicated an
interest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
