<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     09-12 0927</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,870</SECOND>
<HEAD>Autumnal Gloom: End of the Tomato Season</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tomato lovers who shop at farm markets or have
backyard patches of their own are nearing the time of autumnal gloom.
   It descends with the first killing frost, and nothing will
suffice until next year. Not tomatoes shipped from Mexico or the
warm southern areas of the United States.
   Soaring tomato prices were a major contributor to a sharp rise in
consumer food costs last winter, says the Agriculture Department.
Retail vegetable prices, which had been expected to ease in the
first quarter of 1989, rose an average of 5.7 percent.
   Much of that increase was blamed on cold weather in Mexico,
Florida and California, which cut supplies of fresh vegetables,
including tomatoes. There was also some lingering effect from last
year's searing drought.
   In the first half of 1989, prices paid to commercial tomato
growers averaged more than $41 per 100 pounds, up from $26 during
the same period of last year.
   A late January freeze in Mexico slowed shipments to U.S.
consumers and boosted retail tomato prices by 48 percent in the
first quarter. A freeze in Florida in late February damaged the
newly planted spring crop and added further problems.
   Prices paid to U.S. tomato growers rose to a record of $55.80 per
100 pounds in April, and retail prices averaged a record $1.32 per
pound in May.
   Gary Lucier of the department's Economic Research Service said
August figures show tomato prices at the farm dropped to less than
half of the earlier record level.
   ``We're in better shape now,'' Lucier said Monday in a telephone
interview. ``We could see some fluctuations up and down for the next
few months, but typically _ if there aren't any freezes _ I don't
see any problem.''
   After peaking in May at the record retail price of $1.32 per
pound nationally, consumers by June saw tomatoes ease back to 87
cents per pound as new seasonal supplies took hold.
   And then it was time for locally grown produce to make its market
entry _ the tomatoes, melons, sweet corn, squash and other items
that headline thousands of roadside stands and farm markets each
summer.
   ``Even the industry recognizes that in the summertime, anyway,
there's a lull in demand for tomatoes because of home gardens,''
Lucier said. ``Prices are typically at their low point.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. sheep flock has increased slightly in
recent years but still is one of the smallest inventories since the
Agriculture Department began keeping track in 1867. Global sheep
numbers, meanwhile, are at record levels.
   Currently, the world's sheep flock is estimated at 1.145 billion
head, up 2 percent from a year ago, according to a report by the
department's Economic Research Service. Most of the increase is in
China, Australia and the European Economic Community.
   The U.S. flock of sheep and lambs as of Jan. 1 was estimated
earlier this year at 10.8 million head, up fractionally from a year
earlier. Inventories have been declining generally for many years,
since a peak of 56.2 million in 1942.
   As a result the U.S. wool clip has also been relatively small,
although the 1988 production of shorn wool increased 5 percent from
1987 to 89.2 million pounds.
   Comparatively, U.S. mills used about 35.2 million pounds of wool
in the second quarter of this year, down slightly from January-March
but up about 4 percent from the second quarter of 1988, the report
said.
   With mill use up, wool imports have risen, totaling 31.9 million
pounds in the second quarter of 1989, up nearly 10 percent from
January-March and 26 percent more than in the same period of last
year.
   Australia, New Zealand and the United Kingdom are major suppliers.
   The 1988-89 world output of wool is estimated at a record 7.12
billion pounds, on a greasy or uncleaned basis, up by more than 2
percent from last year, the report said.
   ``Most of this increase occurred in Australia (the main source of
apparel wool entering export trade) where excellent pasture
conditions and large sheep numbers caused 1988-89 production to be
almost 2.09 billion pounds, greasy, 3.6 percent above the previous
season,'' the report said. ``China and Argentina also experienced
larger production.''
   New Zealand, the major source of coarser grades of wool used in
carpets, blankets and heavy clothing, reported a decline in
production because of drought-related lower yields and fewer sheep.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last week's sale to the Soviet Union of 50,000
metric tons of surplus butter held by the Agriculture Department
averaged less than 74 cents a pound, or a little more than half of
what it cost American taxpayers.
   The sale, for a total of $80.9 million, involved a price to the
Soviets of $1,618 per ton, the department said. At 2,205 pounds per
ton, that was about 73.3 cents per pound.
   According to a recent USDA inventory accounting, the Commodity
Credit Corp. _ which acquires and stores surplus butter under the
government's milk price support program _ had about $1.40 per pound
invested in its butter stockpile. That translates into about $3,087
per ton.
   But Moscow didn't get a special price break, according to USDA
officials. Congress in 1985 and 1988 legislation ordered USDA to
sell for export 150,000 tons of dairy products per fiscal year
through September 1990.
   So far this year, sales total about 84,000 tons, including the
butter sale to the Soviet Union. Prices charged foreign buyers must
be competitive on the world market.
</TEXT>
