<FIRST>r w PM-AgingAirliners     09-12 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aging Airliners,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Ordering Modifications On Aging McDonnell Douglas Jetliners</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says it will order modification
of more than 1,100 McDonnell Douglas jetliners to help them grow old
safely.
   The action, similar to that taken for Boeing airliners earlier
this year, is the result of an airline industry-government task
force's effort to address growing concern over the world's aging
airliner fleet. More than half the passenger jets flying are over 20
years old.
   The Federal Aviation Administration announced Monday it will
issue within a few days ``airworthiness directives'' covering older
DC-10, DC-9, DC-8 and MD-80 airliners, in line with task force
recommendations announced at the same time. The cost for U.S.
airlines flying McDonnell Douglas jets is expected to total $53
million over the next four years, the FAA said.
   Industry officials, at a joint news conference with the FAA, said
it could eventually cost 10 times that much for the worldwide
McDonnell Douglas fleet over the next 20 years. But officials said
much of the work already has been done or planned and they do not
expect it to affect service or fares.
   ``Let me emphasize that the safety record of commercial aircraft
continues to be excellent,'' said Clyde Kizer of the Air Transport
Association.
   Jim Lundy, spokesman for Delta Air Lines, which flies 75
McDonnell Douglas planes, said the FAA orders do not indicate older
airlines are unsafe.
   ``This a way to make absolutely, positively sure that the
integrity of the airplane is maintained,'' he said.
   Industry officials said the McDonnell Douglas and Boeing planes
can fly safely as long as various parts of the fuselage, landing
gears and doors are replaced.
   The task force, which made recommendations affecting Boeing
airliners earlier this year, included engineers and officials from
the FAA, other government agencies, airlines, airplane manufacturers
and foreign airlines and aviation agencies. It is to report on
planes built by other manufacturers by the end of the year.
   The work is to be done after each plane reaches a set number of
landings, depending on the aircraft model and the items to be
replaced.
   So far, the government has agreed airliners can continue to fly
well beyond their original design goals as long as they are properly
maintained, although there is some support in Congress to set a
mandatory retirement age for jetliners.
   The initial McDonnell Douglas changes are less extensive and less
costly than those affecting Boeing, which average more than $1
million per plane.
   Dale Warren, McDonnell Douglas vice president, estimated the cost
under the planned FAA order would average $290,000 per plane:
$74,000 for DC-10s, $161,000 for DC-8s, $490,000 for DC-9s and
$90,000 for MD-80s.
   The higher cost for DC-9 modifications was due primarily to the
need for costly replacements in the landing gears, Warren said.
   The FAA order will cover only U.S. planes over the next four
years, with work required as each airliner logs a set number of
landings, said Ray Ramakis, assistant FAA director for maintenance
programs and flying standards. The landings threshold varies for
each type of aircraft and for the type of work to be done.
   Ramakis said the orders initially will cover 218 DC-8s, 568
DC-9s, 173 MD-80s and 194 DC-10s. The DC-8s date back to the late
1950s, with DC-9s first built in 1964 and replaced by the MD-80 in
the 1980s. DC-10s were first used in the early 1970s.
   Foreign airlines and regulatory agencies generally adopt FAA
orders for U.S.-built aircraft.
   Robert Aaronson, ATA president, said the orders are not linked to
the July 19 crash of a United Airlines DC-10 in Sioux City, Iowa,
which killed 112 people. A separate industry-government group is
studying the design of larger airliners, partly as a result of that
crash.
   The aging airliner task force was set up after an Aloha Airlines
737 with nearly 90,000 flights lost an 18-foot section of fuselage
in an April 1988 flight over Hawaii. A flight attendant was killed.
</TEXT>
