<DOCNO> AP890912-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 0219EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Democrats     09-12 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Democrats,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Tread Lightly on Tax Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats say they must take care not to head
into the 1992 presidential campaign as the party of taxes while
Republicans take credit for the war on drugs.
   ``In fighting with the president for our vision of America's
future, let's not lead with our chin,'' party chairman Ronald H.
Brown told a meeting of Democratic strategists Monday.
   ``When we entangle ourselves in talk about taxes before we lay
out clear long-term goals and objectives, we dampen the
public-spirited response of Americans who want to believe that we
can act together to make a difference,'' Brown said.
   Robert G. Beckel, a veteran Democratic political consultant, said
the response of some Democrats to President Bush's drug speech
identified their party with higher taxes.
   ``Within 24 hours of the news cycle, they (the Republicans) got
drugs and we got taxes'' as issues, Beckel said.
   Looking forward to the 1992 presidential campaign, he asked,
``Why give the next guy a drug policy in which the Republicans stand
for getting tough on drugs and we stand for taxing to get tough on
drugs?''
   Democrats have criticized Bush's program as being inadequately
funded, and Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the House
Ways and Means Committee, said, ``unless the president supports the
tax increases that will be necessary to fight this war, the drug
dealers are going to win.''
   The one-day conference was organized by Robert Rubin, a New York
investment banker active in Democratic affairs, and Richard Medley,
who runs a consulting firm in Washington that concentrates on
economic issues.
   Brown urged Democrats to ``starting preaching the Democratic
gospel'' by calling for ``a newly vigorous public spirit.'' But he
added, ``programmatic liberalism is not the gyroscope that guides
the national Democratic party.''
   He said rank-and-file Democrats ``believe that the New Deal
shaped our history and message as Democrats over four decades _ but
now they are ready for something more.''
</TEXT>
