<FIRST>r w PM-MinorityHealth     09-12 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minority Health,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sullivan Supports Program to Train Minorities in Health Field</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is giving tentative
backing to legislation that would attack the disparity between the
health of whites and minorities by encouraging training of more
black and Hispanic doctors and nurses.
   Health and Human Services Secretary Louis Sullivan told Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy on Monday that several of the provisions in a bill
Kennedy is introducing would help in his own quest for improved
minority health.
   Sullivan, former head of the Morehouse University School of
Medicine, said he favors Kennedy's proposal to spend $117 million in
fiscal 1991 to expand minority training programs. He said he expects
the money to be added to the HHS budget rather than be transferred
from other programs.
   But Sullivan stopped short of a formal endorsement, saying the
Justice Department has expressed concern about the constitutionality
of provisions that would set aside grants for scholarships at
predominantly black medical schools.
   Kennedy, D-Mass., expressed confidence any problems could be
worked out since they involved distribution formulas rather than the
shared goal of increasing financial support for minority medical
students.
 be set
up for nursing schools.
   While the legislation would focus on stimulating medical training
for minority students, lawmakers said general health education
directed at minority groups will play a major role in improving
health among those groups.
   Hatch said at a hearing of the Senate Labor and Human Resources
Committee that much of the gap between white and minority health can
be closed ``through improved public education and better
coordination of services'' for minorities.
   ``Smoking among adult males continues to be about 25 percent
higher among blacks than among whites,'' he noted as an example.
   Dr. Herbert Nickens, vice president for minority health, disease
prevention and health promotion for the Association of American
Medical Colleges, called for a special congressional committee to
ride herd on how minority health issues are coordinated at the
federal level.
   He agreed that mass education is a cornerstone to improved health.
   ``Health promotion and disease prevention is an essential
component of any minority health strategy because the diseases which
kill us in America now depend heavily on our behavior and
lifestyle,'' said Nickens, a former head of the HHS Office of
Minority Health.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
