<FIRST>r w PM-FlagBurning     09-12 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flag Burning,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Prepares to Vote on Flag-Protection Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republican Leader Bob Michel says it's
all right with him if lawmakers vote for a statute prohibiting
desecration of the flag, so long as Democrats allow a vote this fall
on a constitutional amendment.
   ``While I personally have to be opposed to the statute because
I'm supporting the amendment process, there are a number of members
who want to vote for most anything (to protect the flag),'' Michel
said Monday.
   Although there is little argument between Democrats and
Republicans about the desire for congressional remedy for a Supreme
Court decision giving First Amendment protection to flag
desecration, there has been wide disagreement about how that should
be done.
   The House was taking the first crack at the matter today in the
form of the statute pushed by Democrat leaders who don't want to go
the Republican-backed route of amending the Constitution.
   ``I happen to think the language even tends to weaken the current
statute,'' Michel said. The bill would make desecration of a flag a
federal offense punishable by fines and imprisonment.
   On the eve of today's House action, Republican and Democrats
discussed an agreement that would allow a vote on the statute as
well as a later vote on an amendment.
   These talks came as President Bush traveled to Capitol Hill and
had lunch with former House colleagues Reps. Sonny Montgomery,
D-Miss., and John Paul Hammerschmidt, R-Ark. The congressmen said
Bush briefly discussed the flag issue with them.
   Although Bush made no comments as he left the Capitol, both
Montgomery and Hammerschmidt said they believed the president,
despite his preference for a constitutional amendment, would not
veto flag-protection legislation passed by Congress.
   ``He understands that, politically, members have to have a chance
to vote on a statute,'' Hammerschmidt said.
   Montgomery, chairman of the Veterans Affairs Committee, said
House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., told him Friday he would let
the House vote on a flag amendment in November.
   ``I think it's pretty locked in,'' Montgomery said.
   Montgomery said he would vote for the statute. Until now, many
veterans groups have been pressuring lawmakers to oppose the statute
because they fear it would preclude a vote on a constitutional
amendment, which they prefer.
   Michel sidestepped reporters' questions about the discussions
with the congressional leadership.
   Michel said he was ``still working'' with Foley ``with the
expectation we would have the same kind of agreement as is current
in the Senate, where there'll be a vote on the statute and assured
vote on an amendment some time later.''
</TEXT>
