<FIRST>r w PM-Root-Bankruptcy     09-12 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Root-Bankruptcy,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firm Files for Protection from Creditors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas Root, who gained fame and public
scrutiny when his mysterious flight private plane flight ended by
crashing in the Atlantic Ocean, is asking a court to protect his
communications law firm under Chapter 11 bankruptcy laws.
   Root said Monday his money woes stemmed from non-payment from an
``entity'' he would not name.
   He has acknowledged collecting $1.64 million in fees for
representing FM radio station applicants before the Federal
Communications Commission in the last two years.
   Root refused to say if the entity was Sonrise Management
Services, a Columbus, Ga., company that has sued Root over his legal
services for investment groups that Sonrise organized.
   Asked by a reporter if it was Sonrise, Root said, ``Who do you
think it is?''
   Root said his firm, Thomas L. Root, P.C., filed for Chapter 11
protection Aug. 30 in federal bankruptcy court in the District of
Columbia.
   Root said in a statement that besides non-payment, ``The firm
also has suffered disruption of revenue because of the accident in
July 1989 of Thomas L. Root, president of the firm.''
   Root gained fame when he apparently lost consciousness while at
the controls of his single-engine plane and flew, apparently on
auto-pilot, for six hours before crashing into the waters near the
Bahamas.
   After his rescue, doctors at a Florida hospital discovered he had
been shot in the abdomen.Root says he passed out at the controls of
the aircraft and can't remember how he was shot. Federal authorities
were investigating the crash.
   Less than a week after the crash, Sonrise filed a $584,000
lawsuit against Root, alleging he failed to perform work and
double-billed a client.
   Sonrise said it had paid him $1.9 million since 1986 in advances
against legal fees for some 167 FM applicants. Root says he received
$1.64 million.
   The FCC has said Root's firm repeatedly failed to comply with
deadlines and other requirements in the FM application cases, and a
number of Root's applications have been dismissed.
   Root said Monday his firm still represented ``in excess of 50''
of those clients and that 12 had changed counsel.
   ``We're still answering our phones,'' he said. ``The firm will
remain in business.''
</TEXT>
