<HEAD>Three People Killed in Highway Pileup</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with authorities now saying at least
three were killed, sted four.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SODA SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Up to 15 vehicles piled up during a
hailstorm Monday on Interstate 80, killing at least three people and
injuring 12, the California Highway Patrol said.
   CHP dispatcher Vic Hopner said three deaths were confirmed in the
4 p.m. accident near Donner Pass. The injured were taken to Tahoe
Forest Hospital in Truckee, Hopner said.
   Nursing supervisor Ann Delforge said two of those killed were
pronounced dead at the accident scene and a third was pronounced
dead upon arrival at the hospital. Delforge originally said there
were four deaths.
   Two of the injured were flown to St. Mary's Hospital in Reno,
Nev., to be treated for spinal and chest injuries. The others were
being evaluated, she said.
   About 2 inches of hail fell on the Donner Pass area Monday
afternoon, and a tractor-trailer rig lost control on the slick
pavement and crushed two cars against a guard rail. At least nine
other vehicles piled up behind, a CHP spokeswoman said.
   The highway was closed more than two hours after the crash,
officials said.
