<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 0339EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-RoyalEngagement     09-12 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Royal Engagement,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Engagement Announced For Japanese Emperor's Second Son</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials today said Prince Aya, the second-in-line
to the throne, will take as his bride a college student whose humble
background gave her the nickname ``Apartment Princess.''
   The announcement by the Imperial Household Council came a day
after Kiko Kawashimashe celebrated her 23rd birthday with the
prince, the emperor and empress at Akasaka Palace, a far grander
home than the simple apartment where she lives with her parents.
   Prince Aya's choice of his college sweetheart, who has no noble
background and whose family is well-off but not wealthy, has caused
a stir among some palace conservatives.
   ``It will be hard for her because she is the closest person to
the general public ever to marry into the royal family,'' said one
palace source, who requested anonymity. ``Empress Michiko may have
been a commoner, but her family was certainly upper class.''
   Michiko, the first commoner to become empress, reportedly helped
deflect opposition to the marriage.
   The idea of 23-year-old Aya marrying before his 29-year-old
brother, Naruhito, also had met considerable opposition from palace
conservatives, another palace source said.
   ``But the crown prince seems to be in no hurry, and hasn't found
the right woman yet,'' the source said earlier this month,
requesting anonymity.
   The plans were announced after the 10-member Imperial Household
Council, headed by Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu, met this morning.
   ``Together with the people of Japan, I express my salutations
regarding this auspicious engagement and pray for the continued and
increased prosperity of the imperial family. ... Kiko has a
wonderful personality and is a most fitting princess,'' Kaifu told
reporters after the announcement.
   Although Prince Aya chose his bride himself, by law the council
has to meet to discuss the marriage of any male member of the
imperial family.
   In sharp contrast to the empress, whose family business is the
nation's largest flour miller, Miss Kawashima lives with her parents
and younger brother in humble on-campus housing at Tokyo's Gakushuin
University, where she studies psychology and her father, Tatsuhiko,
teaches economics.
   That university, however, is the alma mater of much of Japan's
royalty, including Aya and the emperor.
   Aya, 23, is second-in-line to the Chrysanthemum Throne after
Naruhito, who will be formally installed as crown prince next year
on a date yet to be decided.
   Aya will complete postgraduate studies in zoology at Oxford
University's St. John's College in June.
   No date has been set for ceremonies related to the wedding, but
they will not be held until after Jan. 7, when a one-year mourning
period marking the death of the late Emperor Hirohito ends.
   Hirohito, who died at age 87, is Aya's grandfather.
   Once the mourning period is over, an imperial envoy will be sent
to the Kawashima residence to present her family with gifts _ rice
wine, fish and red and white silks _ that future imperial in-laws
traditionally receive.
   The gifts seal the engagement much as a ring would in the West.
   After the presents are given, Miss Kawashima will begin
``princess studies,'' daily classes in imperial history and customs,
the constitution, foreign language and etiquette.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
