<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     09-12 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Share Prices Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed lower against the Japanese yen
Tuesday, while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues regained 219.22
points, or 0.64 percent, to close at 34,332.88.
   The dollar closed at 146.73 yen, down 1.04 yen from Monday's
close of 147.77 yen. It opened at 146.80 yen and ranged between
146.60 yen and 146.93 yen.
   Mitsuhiko Kinugasa, a trader at Daiwa Bank, said the dollar's
bullishness remained despite its temporary fall ignited by a rumor
in New York overnight.
   The dollar plunged overnight following the rumor that the U.S.
Federal Reserve Board is to hold an emergency meeting to ease
monetary policy.
   ``They say all kinds of things over there (in New York) to force
the market in a certain direction,'' he said, ``But trading here in
Tokyo is rather quiet.''
   He said the Bank of Japan intervened in the market by selling
dollars in an attempt to stop the currency's excessive strength. The
amount of the central bank's dollar-selling was unknown. The Bank of
Japan does not comment on its monetary actions.
   Traders said the dollar's trading range was narrow prior to the
release of a series of U.S. economic reports later this week,
including the nation's retail sales figures for August, due Thursday
in Washington, and the July trade figures and the wholesale prices
for August, both slated for Friday.
   On the stock exchange, dealers said the index moderately
rebounded in early trading as market players were reassured by the
yen's overnight rebound against the dollar, but the index's upswing
did not last as participants started selling for profit-taking.
   Trading was light due to lack of energy in the market as well as
a wait-and-see mood especially among institutional investors due to
concerns over the U.S. economic indicators due out later this week,
said a trader with a major securities firm in Tokyo, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
