<FIRST>r a PM-SalcidoHearing     09-12 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salcido Hearing,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blood Samples on Murder Victims Linked to Salcido</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defense lawyer said he does not plan
to challenge blood samples and other physical evidence that
incriminate Ramon Salcido in seven slayings during a wine country
rampage.
   But Marteen Miller said Monday he will seek to disqualify
Salcido's confession to Mexican authorities on the grounds that it
was not voluntary.
   Miller outlined his strategy following the first day of a
preliminary examination to determine if there is enough evidence to
hold Salcido over for trial.
   Salcido, 28, who has pleaded innocent to the charges, is accused
of killing his wife, two daughters, his mother-in-law and her two
daughters, and a co-worker on April 14. He also is accused of
attempting to murder his third daughter, another co-worker and the
colleague's wife.
   During the hearing, a sheriff's deputy fought tears when asked to
identify a photograph of Salcido's daughters found with their
throats slashed in a dump.
   Sonoma County Sheriff's Deputy Mike McManus, the first officer to
arrive at the grisly scene, spoke haltingly as he described finding
the bodies of Sofia, 4, and Teresa, 1, lying near their sister
Carmina, then 2, who survived.
   Also testifying was Richard Waller of the California Department
of Justice Laboratory, who said blood found on the body of Salcido's
mother-in-law, Marion Richards, and her 12-year-old daughter, Ruth,
appeared to be Salcido's.
   The finding also linked to Salcido a blood sample found on a
.22-caliber semiautomatic pistol used in at least two of the
shootings, said Waller.
   After the hearing, Assistant District Attorney Peter Bumerts
called the physical evidence ``as conclusive as it gets.''
   ``I don't think this is a who-done-it, and I don't think Mr.
Miller has ever indicated it would be,'' said Bumerts.
   Municipal Judge Knoel Owen denied a defense motion to continue
the hearing for 30 days to assure the appearance of two special
agents with the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration who were with
Salcido when he was arrested by Mexican authorities five days after
the rampage.
   Salcido told the agents he killed his wife and a co-worker in a
jealous rage believing they were romantically involved, authorities
have said.
   Miller accused the Mexican authorities of coercing Salcido's
confession. The defense attorney said it would take 30 days for
authorities in Washington, D.C., to ensure the agents' appearance.
   Owen said he would reconsider Miller's motion if at the end of
the preliminary hearing the agents have not testified.
   The hearing is expected to last two weeks.
</TEXT>
