<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 0449EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Gann     09-12 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Gann,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Proposition 13 Co-author Dies of Complications from AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Gann, who helped lead the
Proposition 13 tax revolt in the '70s and fought a losing battle for
criminal penalties for those who knowingly spread AIDS, died from
the effects of the disease. He was 77.
   The self-proclaimed ``people's advocate,'' who continued fighting
for ceilings on government spending into the 1980s, died Monday of
pneumonia, ``complicated by a problem with the AIDS virus,'' said
Ted Costa, his longtime political aide.
   Gann had been under treatment for a broken hip at the Kaiser
Permanente Medical Center since a fall at his home on Sept. 2. He
said he contracted AIDS from blood received during open-heart
surgery in 1982, before blood screening for the AIDS virus had been
developed.
   Gann co-wrote the property tax-slashing Proposition 13 initiative
in 1978 with the late Howard Jarvis.
   Gov. George Deukmejian called Gann ``a tireless crusader on
behalf of lower taxes, fiscal responsibility and good government.''
   ``Paul and Howard Jarvis will be remembered for leading the
modern-day version of the Boston Tea Party, which culminated in the
overwhelming approval of Proposition 13,'' the Republican governor
said.
   The state Senate adjourned in Gann's memory; the Assembly had
left for the day before his death.
   Proposition 13, which cut California property taxes by 57
percent, sparked a national trend of tax-cutting movements in other
states. In 1979, Gann successfully sponsored another voters'
petition drive that set limits on state and local government
spending.
   During two decades of crusading in California, Gann sponsored or
co-authored 12 ballot initiatives for conservative causes dealing
with taxes, crime, AIDS and public salaries.
   The June 1990 ballot will include a proposal, sponsored by
Deukmejian and leaders of both parties, to modify the ``Gann limit''
on state spending to allow enactment of an $18.5-million, 10-year
transportation package.
   In his only bid for elective office, Gann won the Republican
nomination for the U.S. Senate in 1980, but was crushed by 4.7
million to 3 million votes by incumbent Democrat Alan Cranston in
the general election.
   Gann first announced he had AIDS on June 9, 1987, when he
declared that his fight against AIDS would be ``the last campaign of
my life.''
   After the announcement, Gann fought for criminal prosecution of
people who knowingly spread AIDS and mandatory reporting of the
names of people who test positive for the virus that causes acquired
immune deficiency syndrome.
   ``I feel I have the gravest responsibility to accomplish this,
more so than anything I've ever done, actually,'' Gann said of his
war on AIDS during a 1988 interview.
   Voters in California's 1988 election rejected the measure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
