<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 0445EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-12 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Drops Sharply, Stocks Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dropped sharply against the Japanese yen
today, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index bounced back after
a weeklong decline.
   After losses totaling more than 370 points over five trading
days, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues climbed 219.22
points, or 0.64 percent, Tuesday and closed at 34,332.88.
   Market players were reassured by the yen's overnight recovery in
New York, dealers said.
   The dollar plunged in New York Monday after a rumor that the U.S.
Federal Reserve Board planned an emergency meeting to ease monetary
policy.
   ``The yen's rebound helped bond prices to rise, which also
encouraged market players to buy stocks,'' said Masahiro Umemori, a
stock analyst with Nomura Securities.
   Trading was thin, however, with first section volume estimated at
500 million shares. Among gainers were electrical, shipbuilding and
construction issues.
   In currency dealings, the dollar closed at 146.73 yen, down 1.04
yen from Monday's finish of 147.77 yen, its highest close in nearly
three months. It opened at 146.80 yen and ranged between 146.60 yen
and 146.93 yen.
   After opening sharply lower following its overnight plunge in New
York, the dollar moved little in Tokyo, said Yoshitsugu Hanada, a
trader with Mitsui Bank.
   ``Although some market sources had expected the dollar to fall
further during Tokyo trading, it didn't, mainly because many
investment trust companies bought the currency whenever it moved
lower,'' he said.
   ``But the dollar could fall some more, considering many market
players still have long dollar-holding positions,'' he said.
   He said the Bank of Japan's dollar-selling intervention, which
totaled some $400 million today, also was likely to check the
dollar's rise.
   The Bank of Japan does not comment on its exchange market
activities.
   Mitsuhiko Kinugasa, a trader at Daiwa Bank, said, however, that
expectations of a strong dollar persisted despite the temporary fall.
   Hanada said there was little news to prompt major moves by market
players, who were awaiting the release of U.S. retail price figures
for August on Thursday and trade figures for July on Friday.
</TEXT>
