<HEAD>Indicted Man Shot to Death on NYC Street</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man shot in the head at point-blank range
outside his home had been indicted in what authorities called one of
the worst environmental crimes in New York City history.
   Fred E. Weiss, 50, a partner in W&amp;W Properties, was shot numerous
times Monday in a late-model Jeep parked outside his home. He had
been charged with two other men and eight companies with illegally
dumping medical waste, asbestos and other hazardous materials in a
Staten Island landfill.
   In the indictment, U.S. Attorney Benito Romano said the companies
operated nearly around the clock between May and September of 1988
and reaped more than $4 million for the defendants. Weiss was free
on $250,000 bond while awaiting trial on mail fraud charges and
violating the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act.
   Investigators said Weiss may have been slain because some of his
associates _ trash haulers linked to mobsters _ believed he was
cooperating with authorities, sources told the Daily News. The
sources were not identified.
   The killer or killers fled without being seen, police said.
