<FIRST>r a PM-Alaska-Cleanup     09-12 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alaska-Cleanup,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Says State Will Clean After Exxon Leaves ^LaserPhoto VDX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROSANNE PAGANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state intends to begin its own oil
spill cleanup after Exxon removes the last of its crews this week
from the fouled coastline of Prince William Sound and the Gulf of
Alaska.
   David Ramseur, a spokesman for Gov. Steve Cowper, said the
details are still being worked out, but the governor will agree to a
state-financed cleanup to begin after Exxon withdraws Friday.
   Cowper plans to announce the plan in Valdez, home port of the
tanker Exxon Valdez, which ran aground March 24 on a charted reef,
spilling nearly 11 millions gallons of Alaska crude in the nation's
worst oil spill.
   He will spend the next few days working with the state Department
of Environmental Conservation, figuring out what kind of cleanup the
state should attempt during Alaska's stormy, dark and frigid winter.
   ``We're looking at some light, manual cleanup, picking up
remaining tar balls and funding some research and development that
goes beyond squirting hot water on rocks,'' Ramseur said.
   The governor's office had no estimate Monday of how much its
cleanup might cost. Press aide Ernie Piper said the state was
confident that, based on Exxon's past willingness to pay its oil
spill bills, the company also would cover the cost of the state's
wintertime cleanup.
   Exxon estimates its expenses for the summer cleanup at more than
$1.2 billion and disputes state and federal agencies' claims that
the cleanup has been inadequate. The company says it has treated
more than 1,000 miles of shoreline, leaving only four miles undone.
   State authorities say Exxon is overstating the work it has done
and is quitting before the job is finished.
   Environmental Protection Agency Administrator William Reilly has
defended Exxon's decision to leave for the winter, but said the oil
company must finish the cleanup next spring or pay the government to
do the job.
   In San Diego, meanwhile, shipyard workers cut pieces of steel off
the bottom of the Exxon Valdez on Monday as repairs started on the
tanker. The repairs at National Steel and Shipbuilding Co., where
the ship is in dry dock, will take about nine months and cost an
estimated $25 million.
</TEXT>
