<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Housing 1stLd-Writethru a0486 09-12 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Housing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0486,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poles Line Up For Chance At A Dream _ A Home Of Their Own</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to ADD that Drewbud privately owned, CLARIFY
higher up that company is not selling finished houses. Picks up 7th pvs,
`Each share ...' ^By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For days, people stood in line by the
hundreds in material-scarce Poland to pay about 13 months' wages
just for the chance to buy a prefabricated house within the next
four years.
   ``I prefer this to waiting 15 years for an apartment at a housing
cooperative,'' one man told state radio Monday, when shares in the
project went on sale.
   ``Realization of a dream'' read the newspaper advertisement
placed by the privately-owned Drewbud Bank, which offered shares
that would entitle some lucky stockholders to buy a house by 1993.
   The company said it would also give away 100 free houses annually
to stockholders.
   The company is making the first large-scale effort to sell houses
in Poland, an effort that reflects hopes that through fundamental
economic reform engendered by a truly representative government a
solution might finally be found for the country's desperate housing
shortage.
   Drewbud is not selling finished houses, however, just the
prefabricated pieces needed to put them together.
   The housing situation is so dire in Poland that just the chance
of being able to buy the elements of a house drew hopeful crowds to
the 11 banks nationwide where the 15,000 shares went on sale. Some
people stood in line as long as four days.
   Each share entitles its owner to enter one drawing for the free
houses and another to set the order in which the prefabricated
houses will be sold.
   The price for a share in the Poznan-based company was 2 million
zlotys, about $222 at the free-market exchange rate.
   The average monthly salary is about 150,000 zlotys, an income
Poles find they must supplement with cash earned on the side or with
hard currency obtained from relatives abroad or by working in the
West several months a year.
   Currently, the homes Drewbud is offering cost an estimated
180,000 zloties per square meter, or about $3,160 for a
158-square-meter two-bedroom plan.
   However, there is no accurate estimate of what the houses will
cost when sold. The inflation rate was 40 percent for last month and
is thought to be edging toward 200 percent annually.
   The price does not include the property, the cost of assembling
the house or providing connections to power, water and sewage
systems.
   Nor does it include a furnace, plumbing or any other fittings
such as floor, tile or appliances.
   The advertisement included two pages of plans for 10 styles of
homes, ``from rowhouses to manor style.''
   The plans appealed to those facing often decades-long waits for
the more typical residence, which are two or three tiny rooms in a
worn apartment block.
   A government report, citing severe shortages in almost all
building materials, high cost and government bureaucracy, said
housing construction will be 30,000 units below projections this
year.
   The difficulty of obtaining materials, as well as red tape and
expense, also stalls private efforts to build homes.
   The report, issued this week, said the efficiency of housing
construction approaches that of the late 1960s. It said the problem
is aggravated by the lack of hard currency with which to buy
materials and equipment in the West.
   But Drewbud promised homes that were ``one's own, healthy,
energy-saving, made of natural materials and easy to assemble.''
   The sale was advertised to last for five days. By Monday
afternoon, 250 of the 1,150 shares available at the Warsaw bank
branch had been sold.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
