<FIRST>r a PM-PreschoolMolest     09-12 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Preschool Molest,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge: McMartin Case `A Heartbeat Away From a Mistrial'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The possibility of a mistrial in the nearly
6-year-old McMartin preschool molestation case became more likely
with the final alternate juror replacing an ailing member of the
panel.
   ``We are a heartbeat away from a mistrial,'' Superior Court Judge
William Pounders said Monday.
   Pounders said he is ``desperately concerned'' about getting the
case to the jury soon. If one more juror drops out, the case would
have to be mistried because it would lack the required 12 votes.
   Pounders said the stress of the trial has taken its toll on
jurors' health. There originally were six alternates.
   The excused juror suffers from a blood disorder his physician
said could prove fatal if he continued to serve.
   ``The pressure is too much for the jury,'' Pounders said. ``We
have 12 healthy jurors right now that should be able to stay with
us. But the minute that one of them is gone, we've lost 2{ years of
effort.''
   Raymond Buckey, 31, and his mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey, 62,
are charged with 64 counts of molestation and a joint count of
conspiracy. Prosecutors allege they molested 11 children at their
family owned McMartin Pre-School in Manhattan Beach. Seven teachers
originally were charged in the case, which has lingered in the
courts nearly six years. Charges against the others were dismissed.
   Despite his desire to end the case quickly, Pounders granted a
prosecution request to present nine more witnesses in their rebuttal
case.
   ``It feels to me to be a clear gamble to present evidence like
this,'' he said, noting the longer the case, the greater likelihood
of a mistrial.
   ``I feel like we are in Las Vegas rolling the dice,'' he said,
``and I lose in Las Vegas. I feel like we are going to lose it.''
   But Pounders said he granted the prosecution request for more
testimony because he blames the defense for prolonging what is now
the longest and costliest criminal trial in American history.
   ``The vast majority of time has been taken by the defense in this
case,'' he said.
   He summoned the remaining jurors and told them their absent
colleague was ill with a blood disease and with shingles. The latter
disease is contagious, but he told them if they were going to
contract it, ``you would have had it by now.''
   ``These are the 12 jurors who will decide this case,'' he said.
``So your participation is vital until the conclusion of the trial.''
   The trial has been plagued by jury illnesses. Pounders frequently
has called recesses when jurors had to keep doctor appointments. At
one point, he recessed for several weeks to allow a juror to have
spinal surgery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890912-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 0602EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     09-12 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ship Runs Syrian Blockade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A freighter carrying bales of newsprint
and canned food for the besieged Christian enclave ran the Syrian
blockade today as Syrian and Christian gunners fought a shelling
duel in and around Beirut.
   Police said two people were killed and 17 wounded in the
overnight duel, which escalated at 3:30 a.m. as the Princess-Hand
entered Lebanese territorial waters about 20 miles north of Beirut.
   By police count, the six-month confrontation between Gen. Michel
Aoun's mainly Christian troops and the Syrian army has claimed the
lives of 847 people and left 2,528 wounded.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named in line with regulations,
said the Syrians opened up at the Princess-Hand using
radar-controlled 130mm howitzers deployed north of the Christian
enclave.
   The ship, he said, sailed ``very close'' to the
Christian-controlled coast as shells exploded around it, but made it
safely to the port of Jounieh and dropped anchor at 4:30 a.m. He
said further details about the ship's nationality and agents were
not available.
   However, the spokesman said the bales of newsprint were imported
by three newspapers operating in Christian east Beirut. He did not
elaborate.
   East Beirut and the rest of the 310-square-mile Christian enclave
northeast of the capital has been besieged by the Syrians for more
that six months in retaliation for a blockade imposed by Aoun on
ports run by Syria's militia allies south of Beirut.
   Syrian gunboats have intercepted several ships trying to defy the
blockade, and several vessels have been hit by Syrian shellfire as
they approached Christian ports. Most such attacks have not been
reported.
   The daily newspaper An-Nahar published a study released by the
government-run Maritime Transport Directorate which said 27 ships
have been affected by the Syrian blockade of Christian waters, which
has killed 14 seamen and wounded five.
   The study said five of the ships were set ablaze by Syrian
shelling, six suffered direct shell hits, 11 were hit by shrapnel
and five were intercepted by Syrian gunboats and taken to
Syrian-controlled ports.
   Meanwhile, Lebanese newspapers predicted that a truce in the
Syrian-Christian confrontation would result from a meeting by a
three-man Arab mediation committee scheduled for Wednesday in Saudi
Arabia.
   An-Nahar said Aoun has agreed to the idea forming a team to
monitor the import of weapons by the warring Lebanese factions, an
issue which has been a sticking point.
   The Syrians claim Iraq, their Arab arch rival, is providing Aoun
with weapons and ammunitions by sea.
   The 54-year-old Maronite Catholic general has repeatedly refused
proposals for the formation of a team of observers to monitor the
28-mile Christian-controlled stretch of Lebanon's 130-mile
Mediterranean coast.
   Aoun's reported acceptance of an observation team, which could
not be officially verified, is expected to facilitate efforts of the
mediation committee, which comprises the foreign ministers of Saudi
Arabia, Morocco and Algeria.
   The three chief diplomats, after Wednesday's meeting, are to
report to their leaders on the possibility of stabilizing the
situation in Lebanon.
   Kind Fahd of Saudi Arabia, King Hassan II of Morocco and Algerian
President Chadli Bendjedid were asked by a full-fledged Arab summit
in May to find a settlement by November to Lebanon's 14-year-old
civil war.
   However, the mediation committee announced July 28 that its
efforts on Lebanon were deadlocked and blamed Syria for blocking its
mission.
   Aoun and other Christian leaders accuse the Syrians of betraying
their 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the 22-nation Arab League by
siding with Moslems against Christians in the civil war, which has
taken more than 150,000 lives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
