<FIRST>r a PM-ChicagoCorruption     09-12 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chicago Corruption,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Harold Washington Aide Sentenced to Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former aide to the late Mayor Harold Washington
delivered an hour-long speech protesting his innocence, but was
sentenced to eight years in prison for his conviction on fraud and
racketeering charges.
   Clarence McClain also was ordered Monday to pay $35,000 in
restitution and placed on five years' probation.
   McClain, 48, was convicted in July of racketeering, fraud and tax
evasion for taking $35,000 in bribes from undercover FBI informant
Michael Raymond.
   During the sentencing hearing Monday, McClain repeatedly handed
U.S. District Judge Ilana Rovner documents that he said would prove
his innocence, and castigated the prosecution and news media ``who
created this diabolical event.''
   McClain, who did not take the stand at his bribery trial, accused
federal prosecutors of suppressing tapes he said would have cleared
him. He said he would call for a congressional investigation of his
prosecution, which was part of the FBI's Operation Incubator probe
of corruption in city government.
   McClain became so agitated during his speech that Ms. Rovner
ordered a five-minute recess so he could calm down.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael Shepard told the judge that
McClain's speech was one more reason why she should not consider
leniency.
   Shepard said McClain would not subject himself to
cross-examination, but could not resist ``a chance to rant and rave
in front of an audience as if a trial had not occurred.''
   McClain was accused of accepting bribes from Raymond and the
president of a New York-based company in exchange for using his
influence to make sure the company, Systematic Recovery Services,
got a lucrative city contract for retrieving delinquent parking
fines.
   ``Clarence McClain traded Harold Washington's dream of reform for
cash and he put it in his own pocket,'' Shepard said.
   McClain served as an aide to Washington when he was a state
representative and a member of the Illinois congressional
delegation, but was dismissed by the mayor shortly after his 1983
election when reports surfaced about McClain's prior criminal
record, which included a conviction for pandering.
   McClain reportedly told Raymond and others that he still had the
ear of the mayor and could direct bribes in Washington's direction.
   Raymond, a convicted swindler, was the central figure in the
undercover investigation. Operation Incubator netted 16 convictions
in Chicago and spawned a a probe in New York City that led to 10
convictions, including that of Stanley M. Friedman, Democratic
chairman of the Bronx.
   Raymond agreed to serve as an undercover FBI operative after
being arrested on weapons charges in Nashville, Tenn., in 1984.
</TEXT>
