<FIRST>r i PM-China-Soviet     09-12 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Soviet,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Parliamentary Delegation Arrives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese officials today welcomed the first Soviet
parliamentary delegation to visit since the two countries normalized
relations in May.
   The six-member Supreme Soviet delegation, led by Anatoly
Lukyanov, vice president of the body's presidium, will be in China
for six days and is also to tour Wuhan and Shanghai, Soviet
officials said.
   It is the first parliamentary group to come to China since
Mikhail S. Gorbachev normalized party and government ties in a May
visit, the first by a Soviet leader to China in 30 years.
Gorbachev's trip was overshadowed by massive pro-democracy
demonstrations.
   Since the movement was suppressed in a bloody June 3-4 military
assault, China has emphasized its good ties with communist and Third
World countries which, unlike the West, have generally withheld
criticism of the use of violence to put down the protests.
   The head of China's Communist Party International Liaison
Department, Zhu Liang, is currently in Moscow to discuss ways to
develop inter-party ties following the Gorbachev visit.
   Sino-Soviet relations were frozen at most party and government
levels after a 1960 split over ideological and strategic
differences, and did not begin to thaw until the mid-1980s.
   The first Supreme Soviet visit to China after the split took
place in 1985. There have been two more lower-level parliamentary
visits before the current delegation.
</TEXT>
