<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was lower in cautious trading in Europe
this morning as dealers awaited U.S. economic figures to be released
later in the week.
   Gold prices were mixed.
   Traders said the dollar was stuck in a narrow range as market
players sifted through predictions and rumors to decide what
positions they were going to take before the release at U.S. trade
figures for July, due on Friday.
   ``I believe the dollar will find a floor at 1.9750 (West German)
marks before the trade numbers come out,'' said Jens-Uwe Fischer,
vice-president at Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co. in Frankfurt. At
the high end of the range, the dollar was unlikely to rise above
2.0000 marks, he said.
   The Bank of Japan was sighted selling dollars early in Tokyo's
trading session today, dealers said. The action had little effect on
the dollar, they said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 1.04 yen to a closing 146.73 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at a rate of 146.70 yen.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5486 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.5450 late Monday.
   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday:
   _1.9847 West German marks, down from 1.9875
   _1.7120 Swiss francs, down from 1.7150
   _6.6850 French francs, down from 6.6970
   _2.2335 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2425
   _1,421.00 Italian lire, down from 1,424.75
   _1.1872 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1873
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $358.50 a troy ounce,
compared with Monday's late bid price of $358.75. At mid-morning
London bullion dealers fixed a recommended gold price of $358.95.
   In Zurich, gold traded at a bid price of $359.20, down from
Friday's $360.00. Markets were closed Monday afternoon for a holiday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.03 to close at a bid $359.93.
   Silver bullion prices traded at $5.08, unchanged from Monday's
late price.
