<SECOND>PM-NYC Politics,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Koch and Dinkins Race a Dead Heat in New York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters in New York's tightest mayoral race in 12
years decided today whether to nominate Ed Koch for an unprecedented
fourth term or send David Dinkins on his way to becoming the city's
first black chief executive.
   Last-minute polls showed the race for the Democratic nomination a
dead heat. In the Republican primary, former U.S. Attorney Rudolph
Giuliani was expected to beat Ronald Lauder, heir to the Estee
Lauder cosmetics fortune.
   For the 64-year-old Koch, the race represents a fight for his
political life. The brash, garrulous mayor of 12 years started out
far behind Dinkins, the Manhattan borough president, but moved up
strongly in the polls.
   On Monday, Koch pleaded with a crowd of about 500 at a rally,
reminding them, ``I'm No. 2.''
   ```Mayday' is a signal of distress for those who are nautically
minded,'' he said. ``I'm saying to everybody who understands that
expression, I need you. Come out tomorrow. Vote for me. Mayday!
Mayday!''
   Dinkins had 48 percent and Koch 47 percent in a poll of
Democratic voters taken Sunday and Monday for WABC-TV and the Daily
News. Far back were former city transit chief Richard Ravitch and
Controller Harrison J. Goldin.
   Polls have shown Giuliani with two-thirds of the vote over
Lauder, who has spent an estimated $12 million, most of it his own,
on the race against the prosecutor who put Mafia bosses, Wall Street
cheats and corrupt politicians behind bars.
   Koch's critics have portrayed him as having lost interest in the
job and have accused of him being racially insensitive for such
things as saying last year that Jews would be ``crazy'' to vote for
Jesse Jackson.
   The softspoken Dinkins has sought to portray himself as a
conciliator who could heal divisions in the city.
   Drugs, crime and homelessness were among other major issues.
   The slaying of a black teen-ager by a gang of whites in Brooklyn
Aug. 23 brought the largely unspoken issue of race to the surface,
especially after Koch criticized blacks for holding protest marches
in the neighborhood.
   Both men pinned their hopes on turnout _ Dinkins from union
workers and blacks, Koch from Jews and mainstream Democrats.
   Koch hasn't faced a battle like this since 1977, when he first
won the office in a close fight against Mario Cuomo, now the
governor. Koch handily won his primaries in 1981 and 1985.
   On Monday, Koch and Dinkins shook hands and agreed to hold a
unity rally Wednesday no matter who wins to kick off the fall
campaign against the GOP.
   ``We gotta get started on Giuliani,'' Koch said. ``This guy's got
clay knees, and the reporters are only up to his ankles.''
   On the last full day of campaigning Monday, comedian Jackie Mason
campaigned with Giuliani in senior citizen centers. Mason said
Lauder should be ``locked up or 30 years without toilet paper'' for
his attacks on Giuliani.
   Lauder, for his part, said his polls showed ``it's going to be a
major upset.'' He toured a shopping district in Brooklyn, where one
woman told him: ``I like your mother. I use her makeup all the
time.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
