<FIRST>u i PM-Israel     09-12 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peres Says He Accepts Most of Egyptian Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Party leader Shimon Peres said today he
supports most of the provisions in an Egyptian peace plan and is
willing to push for a Cabinet vote if the proposal is accepted by
the Palestinians.
   The statement was likely to stir unease in Israel's joint
government, led by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of the right-wing
Likud bloc.
   Shamir said Monday that his own peace initiative, which he
unveiled in April and was approved by the government, must be
implemented ``without any additions or eliminations.
   ``Nothing is obliging apart from the peace initiative that has
been approved by the government and the Parliament,'' Shamir said.
``Those who say other things are harming the decisions.''
   The Israeli plan calls for elections in the occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip to choose Palestinians for talks on an interim
autonomy period, with the final status of the occupied territories
to be determined later.
   The 10-point plan proposed by Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
includes Israeli acceptance of the U.S.-backed concept of trading
land for peace. It also calls for allowing the 140,000 Arabs in
annexed east Jerusalem to vote.
   Those points are acceptable to Labor but not to Likud. The
Israeli proposal worked out by the two parties deliberately leaves
these issues open.
   The Israeli daily Davar said today that Shamir was willing to
show flexibility on the question of letting east Jerusalem Arabs
vote and on the possible participation of two Palestinian deportees
in peace talks in exchange for a summit with Mubarak.
   Shamir's aide, Yossi Ahimeir, denied the report and told Davar it
was ``an attempt to ignite fire within Likud by showing that Shamir
is considering some concessions.'' Davar is affiliated with the
Labor Party.
   Peres, who serves as finance minister in the government, said on
Israel army radio he would be willing to talk to a Palestinian
delegation with ``positions that would more or less conform with the
10 points.
   ``I don't think I have to accept all the 10 points or their
style,'' Peres said. ``I accept most of them, and most of them are
also accepted by the Labor's central committee,'' or the party's
governing body.
   Peres confirmed that Abba Eban, a former foreign minister and a
senior Labor politician, is likely to convey his views to Egyptian
leaders during his current visit to Cairo.
   Eban's visit coincides with one by PLO leader Yasser Arafat, and
Egyptian newspaper Al-Akhbar said Arafat has told Mubarak he
supports the Egyptian initiative. However, Arafat left Cairo Monday
night without making any statement.
   Two leading Israeli dailies called on the government to adopt the
Egyptian proposal, which the Haaretz newspaper termed ``a positive
document.''
   The mass-circulation Yediot Ahronot newspaper accused Shamir of
undermining his own initiative by not showing ``a minimum of
tactical flexibility.''
</TEXT>
