<FIRST>u a PM-ChemicalExplosion     09-12 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chemical Explosion,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blast Kills One, Injures at Least 15</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion and fire struck a chemical plant
early today as workers were repairing damage from a blast three
months ago, authorities said. One person was killed and at least 15
were reported injured.
   At least six of the injured were in critical condition, said
hospital officials.
   Witnesses said they could see flames shooting into the air from
10 miles away. Others said they were jolted awake by the explosion
at the Quantum Chemical Corp. plant near this town 50 miles
southwest of Chicago.
   The 2:44 a.m. blast was caused by a leak of flammable ethylene
gas, said Tim Crowley, Quantum manager of administration. The
ethylene unit was being repaired after an explosion and fire that
had shut the plant since June 7.
   The injured were Quantum workers and maintenance contractors,
said Larry Oetzel, technical manager at Quantum.
   Killed was was Robert Brown, 36, of Morris, a contract worker,
Oetzel said. As many as 24 workers were at the scene when the blast
occurred, Crowley said.
   Some of the injured were sprayed with ethylene, which the plant
combines with propylene to make plastic pellets, officials said. The
pellets are used to make garbage bags, storage containers, tackle
boxes and battery cases.
   The plant was shut down since the June 7 explosion, which was
blamed on a leak of propane and propylene gas, Oetzel said. Workers
were ``trying to bring that ethylene unit back up'' when today's
blast occurred, Oetzel said.
   The plant is across the street from a residential area and is
surrounded mostly by farmland. The fire was still burning four hours
after the explosion but was contained, Oetzel said. The fire
produced no hazardous fumes, he said.
</TEXT>
