<FIRST>u p PM-DetroitMayor     09-12 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Detroit Mayor,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detroit's Mayor Gets Easy Odds to Win Primary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN L. ADLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters went to the polls in a primary today with
Mayor Coleman Young a sure bet to advance to November's runoff for
an unprecedented fifth term.
   The real question was who would finish second _ 13-term U.S. Rep.
John Conyers or accountant Tom Barrow.
   The top two vote-getters in the 13-way, non-partisan primary will
meet in the runoff, and political analyst and racing handicapper
Bill Ballenger judged Young a 4-5 favorite _ better than even _ to
finish first or second.
   Young's challengers have charged that the 71-year-old mayor has
been in office too long, and they ran what were dubbed ``ABC''
campaigns, for ``Anyone But Coleman.'' The dean of America's black
mayors branded his challengers ``Uncle Toms.''
   Slightly more than 30 percent of the city's registered voters
were expected to go to the polls, Deputy City Clerk Jeff Blaine
said. Turnout for the last mayoral primary, in 1985, was 23 percent,
he said.
   Ballenger, who publishes a newsletter on Michigan politics and is
the race handicapper for the Detroit Free Press, said Conyers was a
slight favorite over Barrow, while City Council President Erma
Henderson had a slight chance of finishing in the top two.
   Barrow, who like Young, Conyers and Henderson is black, is
thought to have a strong chance of finishing No. 2 because of his
appeal among whites, who make up about 25 percent of Detroit's
507,000 registered voters. Barrow got more than 55 percent of the
white vote in the 1985 primary but lost to Young 61-39 percent in
the general election.
   Conyers and Barrow have accused the mayor of neglecting
neighborhoods at the expense of downtown development and not doing
enough about drug use among police.
   Conyers, a late entry in the race, picked up the endorsement of
the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who exhorted a crowd Monday to ``keep hope
alive'' by voting for Conyers. Barrow, who led last year's
opposition to Young's third effort to bring casino gambling to
Detroit, has been endorsed by a few unions and church leaders; most
have committed to Young.
   One matter that put Young into the headlines a few months ago _
the disclosure that he fathered a child by a former city
administrator _ hasn't been much of an issue.
</TEXT>
