<FIRST>r a PM-MissAmerica-Marks     09-12 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miss America-Marks,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Pageant Director Has Heart Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOMERS POINT, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who directed the Miss America
Pageant for 35 years, firing Bert Parks and presiding over the
dethroning of Vanessa Williams, was in critical condition today
after suffering a heart attack.
   Albert A. Marks Jr., 76, was stricken at home Monday and taken to
Shore Memorial Hospital, said hospital spokeswoman Margie Barham.
   Marks retired in 1988 after directing the pageant as a volunteer
for 35 years. He was succeeded by lawyer Leonard Horn, the pageant's
first full-time, paid director. Marks was stricken days before this
year's pageant.
   ``Of course, the pageant will go on,'' Horn said of this week's
preliminaries and finals Saturday night. ``Al, above all, would
understand that.''
   As director, Marks had the final say in every aspect of the
pageant, from the production numbers to the judges to the volunteer
hostesses who chaperone the 51 contestants.
   Marks, an investment broker, carried the pageant from a publicity
stunt designed to extend Atlantic City's summer resort season into a
multimillion-dollar TV production.
   He defended the pageant from criticism from the women's movement,
the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People,
labor organizations and others.
   Marks fired host Parks, replacing him first with actor Ron Ely
and then with the current host, Gary Collins. Parks was host from
1955 to 1979, singing ``There She Is'' as the pageant's winner
walked down the runway.
   Marks also presided over the board of directors when it lifted
the crown of Miss America 1984, Vanessa Williams, after nude photos
of her appeared in Penthouse.
   In the 1960s, Marks was the first to suggest dropping the
controversial swimsuit competition, but was overruled by pageant
directors and fans. Horn has since tried to reduce the significance
of the swimsuit contest by lowering its value in the judging.
</TEXT>
