<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 1033EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Palme     09-12 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palme,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeal Begins for Man Convicted of Killing Swedish Prime Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BITTE LARSSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for the man convicted of killing
Prime Minister Olof Palme asked an appellate court today to overturn
the ruling for lack of evidence.
   ``He totally lacked a motive to murder Palme,'' defense attorney
Arne Liljeros said of Christer Pettersson, who was convicted in July
of the 1986 shooting and was sentenced to life in prison.
   Liljeros said Pettersson sympathized with Palme's politics and
admired the Social Democratic leader. Liljeros also said there was
no forensic evidence pointing to Pettersson as the killer.
   Palme and his wife, Lisbeth, were walking home from a late movie
on Feb. 28, 1986, when an assailant shot Palme and wounded his wife.
   Pettersson, 42, had been convicted in a split decision by the
lower District Court jury, with six lay jurors voting to convict and
the panel's two professional judges voting to acquit.
   The conviction came even though no motive was established, no
murder weapon was found and no one saw Pettersson shoot Palme.
   The Svea Court of Appeals, which will hear many of the 43
witnesses who testified in the lower court, consists of four
professional judges and three lay jurors. Two new witnesses were
also scheduled to testify.
   The prosecution today asked the court to change Pettersson's
conviction of endangerment in the shooting of Mrs. Palme to one of
attempted murder. Asking for stiffer sentences during appeals is the
prosecution's prerogative under the Swedish system.
   The lay jurors in the lower court based their judgment heavily on
the testimony of Mrs. Palme, who said she saw Pettersson standing
nearby just after her husband was shot. She did not testify to
seeing him with a gun, however.
   Liljeros complained he had not been allowed in the room when Mrs.
Palme picked out Pettersson in a police lineup after Pettersson's
arrest in December.
   ``I haven't heard any statements, seen any reactions or been able
to pose any questions,'' about the first identification by Mrs.
Palme, Liljeros said.
   Arguments in the appeal were scheduled to end Oct. 5.
   If the lower court's decision is overturned, Pettersson must be
released immediately.
</TEXT>
