<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-ChinaMemorial     09-12 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-China Memorial,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ceremony Marks 100 Days Since Tiananmen Square Crackdown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One hundred white paper flowers were laid on a
street in London's Chinatown today, marking 100 days since the
Chinese crackdown on pro-democracy protesters.
   Chen Yizi, the highest-ranking official known to have escaped
China since the June 3-4 crackdown, led the ceremony in Gerrard
Street attended by about 50 supporters.
   It was part of a number of events held worldwide to mark the
military crackdown, in which the respected human rights group
Amnesty International estimates at least 1,000 people died.
   ``It is important to remember what happened and why it
happened,'' said a Chinese poet, Duo Duo. ``Today is a day to
remember Tiananmen (Square), which was a humiliation to us all, to
humanity and for all mankind.''
   At the ceremony, Chinese students and supporters laid the flowers
in an arrangement spelling the Chinese word for grief and a refugee
played a tape of gunshots that rang out in the square when soldiers
moved in to break up a sit-in by demonstrators.
   The ceremony was organized by a group called the June 4 China
Support and China Appeal.
   Chen is former head of the Institute of Restructuring the
Economy, an organ of the state council, or cabinet, and was a close
advisor to the purged Communist Party head Zhao Ziyang.
   He arrived in London Saturday with fellow exile, Wan Runnan, the
founder of a computer company.
</TEXT>
