<FIRST>u w PM-Immigration 1stLd-Writethru a0459 09-12 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Immigration, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0459,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Wants to Admit 125,000 Next Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with congressman confirming numbers, saying funding
lacking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration will hold admissions of
refugees to the United States to 125,000 in the next fiscal year, an
increase of slightly less than 8 percent from this year, the
chairman of a House panel said today.
   The administration, which doubled the allotment for people from
the Soviet Union this year to 50,000, has decided the country cannot
handle more and will leave the figure the same for the year
beginning Oct. 1, said Rep. Bruce Morrison, D-Conn., who heads the
House subcommittee on immigration.
   But Morrison, speaking at the start of subcommittee hearings
about the administration's proposed plan, said the government's
proposal only provides funding for 84,000 refugees.
   ``Where do we get the money for the rest?'' he asked a panel of
private witnesses. Government officials will testify Wednesday.
   Morrison also expressed concern about the backlog of an estimated
20,000 Soviet emigres in Rome and Vienna awaiting U.S. decisions on
their eligibility to enter this country. He said the administration
had wasted money through this processing method and changes would
have to be considered.
   The administration would like to shut down the Vienna and Rome
facilities and handle all applications at the U.S. Embassy in Moscow
by increasing the current staff of several processors to more than
two dozen.
   Morrison said Congress will also debate pending legislation that
would determine the criteria for granting refugee status to Soviet
and other emigres.
   Under a revision of regulations ordered last year, each person
applying must prove individual eligibility for refugee status, which
means government aid in resettlement and admission outside the
normal immigration rules. Previously, Jews from the Soviet Union
were automatically considered refugees.
   The new decision has made the backlog grow.
   The Hebrew Immigrant Aid Society, which helps resettle Soviet
Jews, told Morrison's subcommittee that 46 percent of the applicants
in Moscow had been rejected for refugee status.
   Karl Zukerman, executive vice president of the organization,
predicted that at least 72,000 Jews will apply to enter the United
States next fiscal year.
   Overall, this year's refugee quota, arrived at by the
administration each year in consultation with the House and Senate
Judiciary committees, is 116,000 people, up from 94,000 at the start
of the 1988 fiscal year last Oct. 1.
   The 125,000 figure for next year would include 4,000 whose
resettlement would be paid for by private organizations.
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, said the number of people facing
persecution around the world grows every day, at the same time as
U.S. budget resources are shrinking. He urged other countries to
help the United States share the burden.
</TEXT>
