<HEAD>Precede NEW YORK</HEAD>
<HEAD>Haig Denies Report He Would Reveal He Was Deep Throat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New material with Haig denial, editing throughout.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Haig today denied as ``totally
untrue'' a published report saying he would reveal in a future book
that he was the ``Deep Throat'' source for many newspaper stories
about Watergate.
   ``My efforts then and now have been to preserve the presidency,
not to tear it down,'' said Haig, who was Richard Nixon's chief of
staff in his last 16 months in office.
   ``The story regarding my being `Deep Throat' is totally untrue,''
Haig said.
   The New York Daily News, quoting unnamed sources, said Haig would
disclose that he was ``Deep Throat'' in his memoirs, to be published
in 1992 by Warner Books.
   Washington Post reporters Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein, who
wrote many of the stories that led to exposure of the Watergate
scandal that brought about Nixon's resignation, have conistently
refused to identify ``Deep Throat,'' who they said was a major
inside source.
   The Washington Post won the Pulitzer Prize for distinguished
public service for its Watergate coverage.
   Haig came to the White House with the Nixon administration in
1969, serving as military assistant to the president and to National
Security Adviser Henry Kissinger until 1973. He left briefly to be
vice chief of staff of the Army and returned to succeed White House
chief of staff H.R. Haldeman, who had resigned in the Watergate
affair. He served as secretary of state early in the Reagan
administration.
</TEXT>
