<FIRST>u a PM-TeachersStrikes     09-12 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teachers Strikes,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tentative Accord Reached in Sacramento Teachers' Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,400 teachers began returning to work today in Sacramento,
Calif., after reaching a tentative contract agreement in the
nation's biggest school strike. Teachers also ended walkouts in
Illinois and Michigan.
   The settlements left some 5,300 teachers on strike, affecting
more than 93,000 students in eight states.
   Details on the agreement that ended the two-week Sacramento
strike were not released, but union spokeswoman Pat Walden said
major issues in the contract are salary, class size and working
conditions in the 47,000-student district. Teacher salaries average
$32,509.
   Substitutes, administrators and non-striking teachers had kept
schools open.
   In Illinois, negotiations solved a teachers' strike in Quincy but
did little to end the state's largest walkout, in Elgin, or avert a
new one in the Chicago suburb of Roselle.
   Quincy's 6,800 students headed back for a half day of school
today and faced a full day Wednesday for the first time in two
weeks, said superintendent Myrl Shireman.
   But 1,500 teachers and 27,000 students were still off the job in
Elgin, west of Chicago, where teachers worked four days without a
contract before walking out Sept. 5. They were joined by about 250
school employees in Roselle, who voted to strike Monday.
   In Michigan, students returned to class today in the
Melvindale-North Allen Park, Ferndale, Ishpeming and Saginaw
Township districts. Strikes continued in four other districts.
</TEXT>
