<FIRST>u a PM-PaperMillViolence     09-12 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paper Mill Violence,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Looking For Those Who Incited Mob Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INTERNATIONAL FALLS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police and FBI officials said
they would study videotapes today of a weekend riot at a paper mill
to learn who incited the mob violence against non-union construction
workers.
   ``If we have 200 trials, so be it,'' City Attorney Joseph Boyle
told the City Council on Monday.
   Koochiching County Attorney Dave Johnson, who charged six people
Monday with a variety of counts, said he would file charges today
against 18 others arrested in the violence Saturday at the Boise
Cascade Corp. mill.
   In addition, four union mill workers were suspended while company
officials determine if they participated, said Boise spokesman Bob
Anderson, a former mayor of the town of 6,500 on the Canada border.
   During the weekend melee, rioters set fire to vacant trailers,
overturned cars and threw rocks. Law enforcement officers used tear
gas to break up the crowd and arrested 31 people. Five people were
injured, and damage was estimated at $1.3 million.
   The melee involved mostly union construction workers angered by
the use of non-union labor on the mill's $535 million expansion
project.
   Police planned to join FBI agents and sheriff's officials in
studying videotapes police made Saturday to determine who instigated
the violence.
   Earlier, police watching the tape identified five or six people,
who will be arrested and charged, Johnson said. A meeting between
company and union officials also was planned for this afternoon to
review the tapes, Anderson said.
   ``There could be a penalty up to and including discharge,''
Anderson said. ``If there is nothing found the employees will be
paid as if they worked all their hours.''
   ``If they start going after the mill employees they'll have a
real mess on their hands,'' said Bruce Ness, a 20-year mill employee
who was one of the four suspended. Also suspended was Ness's father.
   ``We were just standing on the street watching,'' Bruce Ness
said. ``I guess Boise Cascade is trying to say we don't have any of
our own civil rights.''
   Union leaders condemned Saturday's riot but said violence could
break out again.
   An FBI agent arrived in International Falls because some rioters
crossed state lines to get to the Boise plant, Johnson said. Two of
the six people charged Monday were from Michigan; the others from
Minnesota.
   The charges against the six included riot, damage to property,
arson, trespassing and assault, Johnson said. They appeared before a
judge who set the maximum bail in each case of $13,000 to $30,000.
   All six remained in jail, along with 18 others arrested, Johnson
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
