<FIRST>r a PM-SolicitingSuit     09-12 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soliciting Suit,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Wins Order to Stop Stockbrokers' Calls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer fed up with unsolicited sales calls has
won a court order barring the nation's biggest brokerage and its
12,000 stockbrokers from calling him at work.
   ``It's been something that has bothered a lot of people, but they
don't have the sense they can do something about it,'' said Alan J.
Schlesinger.
   Merrill Lynch said it will appeal the order, which was issued
June 2 in Superior Court and was reported today in The Boston Globe.
   William Fitzpatrick, general counsel for the Securities Industry
Association, said, ``It sounds like he's using an atom bomb to deal
with a gnat.''
   ``Being a fellow lawyer, I guess he doesn't have enough brains to
hang up,'' Fitzpatrick said.
   Schlesinger said he took action after getting a couple of
unsolicited calls from stockbrokers every month for years. In 1984
and 185 he wrote to Merrill Lynch _ the most persistent firm _
asking that it order its brokers to stop calling.
   The last straw came in 1988 when Schlesinger returned a call from
an woman in New York and found she was a Merrill Lynch broker with
an investment proposal. ``At that point, I said I am going to get
their attention,'' he said.
   Fred Yager, a Merrill Lynch vice president, said he believes the
company will win on appeal.
   ``We have 12,000 brokers working for us alone,'' he said. ``It's
virtually impossible to prevent another call from getting through to
him accidentally.''
   Merrill Lynch said that after Schlesinger won the court order it
asked its Boston-area brokers to stop calling him. Two week later, a
Merrill Lynch broker who said he was unaware of the court order
called Schlesinger with a sales pitch.
   Schlesinger filed for contempt charges and was awarded $300 in
court costs.
</TEXT>
