<FIRST>r w PM-HostageAwareness     09-12 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostage Awareness,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contest, `Awareness Day' Planned To Honor Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is being asked to designate journalist
Terry Anderson's birthday next month as a national day of prayer for
the eight Americans held hostage in Lebanon.
   Rep. Paul Henry, R-Mich., today introduced a joint resolution to
mark Oct. 27 as National Hostage Awareness Day. The resolution says
church bells should be rung for one minute at noon that day.
   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, was kidnapped March 16, 1985, and has been held the longest
of any of the eight Americans still believed to be alive.
   Anderson will be 42 on Oct. 27.
   ``It's ... an exercise in conscience for the American people, so
we can say we did what we could,'' Henry said at a news conference.
``This is something we want to have all Americans rally behind.''
   Also at the news conference was David Aikman, foreign affairs
correspondent for Time magazine and chairman of the Journalists'
Committee to Free Terry Anderson.
   Aikman said other activities being planned for Oct. 27 include a
nationwide essay writing contest for high school students, who will
write on the subject, ``How I would cope with being a hostage.'' The
winner will receive $1,000.
   The contest and awareness day are intended to keep international
attention forcused on the hostages as publicity over the presumed
murder of hostage Marine Lt. Col. William Higgins fades, Henry said.
</TEXT>
