<FIRST>r a PM-Freighter-Cocaine     09-12 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Freighter-Cocaine,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Arrests Seven Danish Crewmen in Cocaine Seizure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents seized more than 2,700 pounds of
cocaine and a freighter and arrested 19 people in the biggest drug
busts since President Bush announced his battle plan against drug
trafficking, officials said.
   Seven Danish crew members of the freighter were ordered held
without bail Monday. Their ship was seized the day before and
authorities found more than 1,100 pounds of cocaine in bales thrown
overboard. Also arrested were six people waiting aboard speedboats
nearby to pick up the drug, officials said.
   On Monday, agents seized a 42-foot fishing boat and claimed an
additional 1,600 pounds of cocaine, Drug Enforcement Administration
spokesman John Fernandes said today. Six people were arrested.
   The freighter, registered in the South Pacific island nation of
Vanuatu, was intercepted in Bahamian waters. Fifteen bales of
cocaine floating alongside and three speedboats were also seized,
authorities said. Another bale was found on the freighter.
   Each 70-pound bale consisted of plastic packages bundled around
flotation devices.
   At a hearing Monday, authorities said it was unusual for Danes to
be arrested in drug cases in the area.
   ``At first I couldn't find a Danish interpreter,'' said the head
of federal court interpreters for Miami, Irene King-Tomassini.
