<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 1153EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Cocaine-Cartels 1stLd-Writethru a0445 09-12 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cocaine-Cartels, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0445,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Report Details Cartels' Organization</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 11 grafs new to include testimony; picks up 5th graf pvs,
A rivalry.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia's Cali cocaine cartel is more
efficient than its more well-known Medellin counterpart and as a
result, it may be shipping more drugs to the United States,
according to a Senate report today.
   The report by the Senate permanent subcommittee on
investigation's minority staff says U.S. law enforcement agencies
agree the Cali cartel, ``although smaller in number, runs a much
more businesslike, less high-profile operation than the Medellin
cartel.''
   ``Medellin appears to be more loosely organized, informal and
spontaneous in its operational style than Cali,'' the report says.
``In fact, some law enforcement officials believe Cali actually
ships more cocaine to the United States than Medellin.''
   Mary Vincent, who presented the report, said there are estimates
that the Medellin cartel has as many as 100,000 members, and the
Cali cartel from 2,500 to 6,000 members.
   Bruce M. Carnes, a top aide to national drug control policy
director William Bennett, told the subcommittee that ``the enemy is
the organizations that produce cocaine and other dangerous drugs,
transport it to our shores, distribute it to retailers and users
throughout America, and launder the profits and return them to the
organizations' coffers.''
   The objective of the war on drugs, he said, ``is to put these
organizations out of business, dismantle them.''
   Under questioning by subcommittee chairman Sam Nunn, D-Ga.,
Carnes acknowedged that the two primary measures of drug abuse in
the United States, the household survey by the National Institute on
Drug Abuse and a high school survey, are not comprehensive.
   The household survey does not measure use by students in dorms or
people in institutions and the survey of high school seniors does
not take into account those young people who have dropped out of
school.
   ``So basically what you're saying is after 20 years of fighting
the so-called war against drugs that's been declared by at least
four to five presidents of both political parties...we still not
only don't have adequate tools and we aren't using the tools in the
right direction, and the ones we are using to measure our success or
failure are not even developed yet. Is that too strong?'' Nunn asked.
   ``This glass is half full in my view and I think we're better
than we used to be,'' Carnes said.
   The subcommittee report says Fabio Castillo, a Colombian
journalist who fled his native country due to threats from drug
traffickers and who was to testify before the subcommittee today,
``believes that Cali is indeed the more significant of the two
cartels.''
   A rivalry between the Medellin and Cali organizations ``does not
yet appear to have either threatened the existence or significantly
affected the operations of these two cartels,'' says the report,
which was obtained Monday by The Associated Press.
   Sen. William V. Roth, Jr., R-Del., the panel's ranking minority
member, said the report and hearings this week are ``the first major
public effort to expose in detail these organizations, their
membership, and their methods of operation.''
   ``We can't win the war on drugs if we don't know the enemy,''
Roth said in a statement.
   Administration drug experts say 80 percent of the cocaine in the
United States is processed in and shipped from Colombia, although 60
percent of the coca leaf is grown in Peru, 30 percent in Bolivia and
only 10 percent in Colombia.
   While the report confirms the belief that the Medellin and Cali
cartels dominate the cocaine trade in the Western Hemisphere, it
notes ``secondary trafficking groups'' along Colombia's north coast
``rent a variety of their smuggling services'' to the top two and
conduct their own trafficking operations.
   Larger drug trafficking organizations are run like corporations,
with each stage of the cocaine processing and distribution handled
by a separate department, the report says.
   ``We found definite indications that a trafficker of the stature
of (Medellin cartel leader Jose Gonzalo) Rodriguez Gacha, for
example, will have his own (coca) paste suppliers, his own
laboratories, his own stash sites and his own warehouses in the
United States,'' the report says.
   The report, resulting from a year-long investigation, does not
attempt to determine how the organizations may have been changed or
disrupted by the crackdown imposed by Colombian President Virgilio
Barco.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
