<FIRST>r w PM-US-Jordan 1stLd-Writethru a0548 09-12 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Jordan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0548,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hassan Calls for Arafat Address to United Nations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crown Prince Hassan of Jordan called on the
Bush administration today to permit Yasser Arafat, the chairman of
the Palestine Liberation Organization, to address the United Nations
in New York.
   ``We think Arafat should be granted diplomatic recognition,''
Hassan said after a 45-minute meeting with Secretary of State James
A. Baker III.
   Jordan nearly 20 years ago suppressed the PLO and killed
thousands of its Palestinian supporters. But King Hussein's
government now demands a role for the PLO in the Arab drive to force
Israel to relinquish the West Bank and Gaza.
   The territories, held by Jordan and Egypt until the 1967 Mideast
War, are now under Israeli control. The PLO demands establishment of
a state on the land, while the United States supports an Israeli
proposal for limited self-rule to be followed by broader
negotiations.
   Hassan, scheduled to see President Bush later in the day, said
this was a ``wait-and-see'' period in Mideast diplomacy. But, he
said, ``the human imperative has to come to the fore'' and referred
to the region under discussion as Palestine.
   Arafat, in an interview last weekend with a Saudi Arabian
newspaper, said he would address the U.N. General Assembly session
that opens Sept. 25 in New York. But Richard Boucher, a State
Department spokesman, said Monday the PLO chairman had not applied
for a visa.
</TEXT>
