<HEAD>Four Embassy Employees Arrested in Visa Fraud Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Israeli employees of the U.S. Embassy have
been arrested on charges they were involved in a scheme to produce
counterfeit U.S. visas, the embassy announced Tuesday.
   The four were arrested by Israeli police Monday for alleged
participation in a conspiracy involving the purchase of U.S.
non-immigrant visas, an embassy statement said. It said no American
employees of the embassy were believed involved.
   Non-immigrant visas are issued to tourists, visitors on exchange
programs and people with specialized, short-term jobs.
   The Maariv newspaper said in a report Tuesday that police had
uncovered ``a network of people producing bogus visas'' to the
United States.
   It said the investigation started several weeks ago and that
police believed the false visas were being produced with stamps and
documents stolen from the embassy.
   ``There are apparently dozens involved in the affair, some acting
as middlemen between visa seekers and the counterfeiting ring,''
Maariv reported.
   The paper said the people seeking the visas were Israelis with
criminal records or citizens who lacked the necessary documents to
qualify for legal visas.
