<DOCNO> AP890912-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 1304EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-TireFire     09-12 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tire Fire,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tire Pile Fire Knocked Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ADOLPHE V. BERNOTAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DANVILLE, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters today dumped truckloads of
dirt on a heap of 1.5 million tires and knocked down a smoky fire so
fierce that water just vaporized, but the pile of rubber could
smolder for weeks.
   The blaze, the second fire in four years at the used-tire dump,
now has townspeople asking: Where is Ernie Hunt?
   Hunt is the attention-loving guy who assembled the tires at the
seven-acre dump before it was taken away by the state over the 1985
blaze. Hunt began amassing the tires 15 years ago, charging gas
stations 50 cents a tire.
   ``Mr. Hunt remains at large,'' said Geoffrey Huntington, the
assistant attorney general who has been dealing with the dump. Hunt
is wanted on a perjury warrant accusing him of lying at hearings on
the seizure of the site.
   The stubborn fire broke out Sunday, sending flames 40 feet into
the air and billowing acrid, black smoke that could be seen 25 miles
away.
   About 250 firefighters from 45 communities in three states worked
to contain the fire. Sixty-five trucks and 10 loaders through the
night hauled tons of dirt from a sand and gravel pit.
   ``We switched from water because even at 2,500 gallons a minute,
the water was vaporizing,'' said David Tordoff of the Environmental
Protection Agency said. ``Instead, we will smother it.''
   About 50 residents were evacuated. Some began returning to their
homes late Monday.
   William Toland, state fire marshal, said the cause of the blaze
appeared suspicious. ``It was out of control right from the
beginning,'' he said. ``The fire just absolutely raged.''
   Six years ago, Hunt received a $22,000 down payment from a London
company that had planned to ship the tires to Africa. With the
money, Hunt bought a luxury automobile. But the tires were never
moved. In July, the state contracted with a Buffalo, N.Y., company
to shred the tires for shipment to Greece to fuel a cement plant.
The removal was to have begun shortly.
   ``It's not Ernie so much,'' said Danville resident Jackie McLean.
``I used to say to him, `Hey, Ernie, what are you going to do with
all those tires?' And he'd say, `Someday somebody will want them.'
He was just following the American dream. The towns knew what he was
doing. I blame the communities.''
   ``He was quite a character,'' said Tim Dube, past whose house
Hunt used to drive his car. ``He liked the attention.''
   But said Dube: ``The state and the communities should have done
something years ago.''
   Tordoff said his agency earmarked up to $1 million from the
Superfund for the effort. He said EPA scientists were monitoring
air, soil and ground water for harmful chemicals from the fire. The
1984 blaze smoldered for several weeks.
   Tordoff estimated that 2{ acres of tires 30 to 40 feet high were
on fire.
   Amy Juchatz, a state toxicologist, said the smoke could cause
respiratory problems and other irritation and that lead and zinc
fumes and other chemicals, possibly cancer-causing, could be inhaled
or could contaminate the soil.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
