<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 1329EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     09-12 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korea Proposes Negotiations to Make Korean Peninsula Nuclear
Free</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea on Tuesday proposed
negotiations to remove U.S. nuclear weapons allegedly in South Korea
and convert the Korean Peninsula into a nuclear-free zone.
   Army Maj. Gen. Choe Ui Ung, saying a U.S. nuclear arms buildup on
the penisula could start another Korean War, made the North Korean
proposal at the 451st meeting of the Military Armistice Commission
in this border truce village.
   U.S. Navy Rear Adm. Larry Vogt, speaking for the U.N. Command,
refused to discuss the communist request on grounds it was a
political issue and did not come under the jurisdiction of the
commission, which was formed after a 1953 armistice ended the
three-year Korean War.
   The U.N. Command, led by the United States, was formed in 1950
with 16 foreign countries that rushed troops to help South Korea
repel invaders from the North.
   North Korea has frequently demanded the United States remove
nuclear weapons it says are in South Korea and it proposed a
nuclear-free zone at a commission meeting May 9.
   U.S. forces have refused to confirm or deny the presence of
nuclear arms.
   Vogt charged the communist North with propaganda and misusing the
commission to ``rehash trumped-up charges.'' The meeting was called
by the North.
   Vogt suggested the meeting of the armistice commission discuss
proposals to ease tension along the Demilitarized Zone that
separates the two Koreas.
   Vogt said joint teams should investigate alleged armistice
violations and work to return remains of American soldiers who died
in the Korean War. North Korea has said it has the remains.
   Choe, chief communist delegate to the commission, contended the
United States has deployed ``a colossal amount of nuclear weapons
ranging from mini-nuclear shells and bombs to operational and
tactical nuclear missiles and constructed a number of storehouses
for nuclear weapons'' in at least six areas in the South.
   He said unless the nuclear arms are withdrawn and South Korea is
converted into a nuclear-free zone, ``confrontation and hostile
feelings cannot be removed, nor can confidence be built between both
sides forever.''
</TEXT>
