<FIRST>r w AM-HostageAwareness 320   09-12 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostage Awareness, 320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contest, `Awareness Day' Planned to Honor Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bipartisan resolution was introduced in
Congress on Tuesday to mark journalist Terry Anderson's birthday
next month with a national day of prayer for the eight Americans
held hostage in Lebanon.
   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, was kidnapped March 16, 1985, and is the longest held
American captive. The resolution, co-sponsored by 84 members of
Congress, would set aside Oct. 27 as National Hostage Awareness Day.
   ``It's ... an exercise in conscience for the American people, so
we can say we did what we could,'' Rep. Paul Henry, the Michigan
Republican who introduced the resolution, said at a news conference.
``This is something we want to have all Americans rally behind.''
   The resolution calls for church bells across the country to be
rung for one minute at noon Oct. 27, Anderson's 42nd birthday, and
asks the United Nations to declare a simultaneous International
Hostage Day.
   David Aikman, foreign affairs correspondent for Time magazine and
chairman of the Journalists' Committee to Free Terry Anderson, said
at the news conference that he believed publicity has helped keep
Anderson alive.
   Aikman said high school students are being asked to participate
in an essay contest, writing about ``How I would cope with being a
hostage.'' The winner will receive $1,000.
   The other Americans still held in Lebanon are: Thomas P.
Sutherland, dean of agriculture at American University in Beirut;
Frank H. Reed, American director of the Lebanese International
School; Joseph J. Cicippio, acting comptroller of the American
University; writer Edward A. Tracy; and J.J. Turner, Alan B. Steen
and Robert B. Polhill, professors at Beirut University College.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Editor's Note: Students may send their essays to Journalists'
Committee to Free Terry Anderson, P.O. Box 10404, McLean, Va.,
22102-0404. Essays must be 1,000 words or less. Entries must include
the student's name, address, grade, age, school's name, address and
phone number. The deadline is Oct. 27.
</TEXT>
