<FIRST>u p PM-PrimaryRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0525 09-12 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Primary Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0525,0749</SECOND>
<HEAD>Candidates Vie for Wright, Coelho Seats; Mayors Run in New York,
Detroit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 19th graf pvs, `Nine candidates ...' to CORRECT to nearly
14 sted 12 years in office; SUBS last graf to CORRECT that city is about
half white.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhotos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats in Texas and California today hope to reclaim two House
seats in special elections prompted by the resignation of Speaker
Jim Wright and Majority Whip Tony Coelho in a Capitol Hill
bloodletting over ethics.
   New York Mayor Edward Koch is looking for a come-from-behind
victory in the Democratic primary over David Dinkins, who could
become the city's first black mayor. And in Detroit, Mayor Coleman
Young is expected to brush back a swarm of primary challengers who
want to keep him from winning a record fifth term in November.
   Among other elections around the country today are mayoral
primaries in Buffalo, N.Y., New Haven, Conn., and Minneapolis and
St. Paul, Minn.
   In the congressional races, Democrats are basking in the support
of the leaders they are trying to succeed. Although Wright and
Coelho resigned because of alleged ethics violations, both remain
popular and have been central figures in the campaigns.
   Wright has campaigned for Democrat Pete Geren, a Fort Worth
lawyer and former aide to Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas. Geren faces
Republican Bob Lanier, a TV medical commentator, who has countered
with endorsements from President Bush and former Dallas Cowboys
coach Tom Landry.
   Lanier said he initially worried that Wright's endorsement would
be a major factor in the race but now believes ``it hasn't been
quite as much as we anticipated.''
   Still, he conceded that he's ``swimming upstream'' as a
Republican in a district with a long history of sending Democrats to
Congress.
   In California's San Joaquin Valley, Coelho has endorsed
Democratic state Assemblyman Gary Condit in a low-key race against
Republican Clare Berryhill, a former assemblyman and state
agriculture chief.
   Berryhill and Condit are considered the leading candidates among
the six running. Unless one candidate gets more than 50 percent of
the vote, there will be a runoff.
   The New York City race, once considered a lost cause for Koch,
has turned into a cliffhanger between the brash mayor and his
soft-spoken challenger.
   Koch sent out an SOS call to his supporters Monday, saying he
needed a big turnout to win his party's nomination for an
unprecedented fourth term.
   ``I'm saying to everybody who understands that expression: `I
need you. Come out tomorrow. Vote for me. Mayday! Mayday!,''' Koch
said at a lunchtime rally.
   At a school dedication, Koch pulled Dinkins aside to call for a
unity rally on Wednesday, no matter who wins.
   ``I think that's a nice gesture,'' said a smiling Dinkins, who is
the Manhattan borough president. ``I mean, he recognizes that the
likelihood is that I'm going to succeed, and he offers to help me, I
think that's fine.''
   Koch said it was important for his party to work on defeating
Republican Rudolph Giuliani, the former federal prosecutor who leads
cosmetic heir Ronald Lauder in the GOP race.
   In Detroit, Young faces a dozen challengers, including Rep. John
Conyers, a 13-term Democratic congressman who says Young has been
mayor too long.
   Conyers, who like Young is black, has benefited from the vocal
support of Jesse Jackson, who exhorted a crowd Monday to ``keep hope
alive'' by voting for Conyers.
   A poll released Sunday showed Young well in front, with Conyers
running neck-and-neck with accountant Tom Barrow for second place.
The top two finishers in the non-partisan primary advance to
November's general election.
   Nine candidates are battling to succeed St. Paul Mayor George
Latimer, who is quitting after nearly 14 years to become a law
school dean. Across the river in Minneapolis, Mayor Don Fraser faces
six challengers.
   The top two vote-getters in each city will advance to the Nov. 7
general election.
   Buffalo Mayor James Griffin, a maverick Democrat, faces two
challengers in his party's primary but is also running unopposed for
both the Republican and Conservative party nominations.
   In New Haven, Democratic state Sen. John Daniels is trying to
become the first black mayor of the Connecticut city, which is about
half white. His opposition for his party's nomination in the
overwhelmingly Democratic city comes from John DeStefano Jr., the
hand-picked candidate of Mayor Biagio DiLieto, who is retiring.
</TEXT>
