<FIRST>r i AM-Norway-Election     09-12 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Norway-Election,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rival Blocs Have Equal Chance to Form Government, Say Analysts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG MELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of voters ditched Norway's two
largest parties in general elections, and analysts Tuesday gave the
governing Labor Party coalition only a 50-50 chance to survive a
right-wing challenge.
   Neither grouping got a majority in parliament from Monday's
balloting, and conservatives must gain the support of an
increasingly popular far-right party if they hope to topple Prime
Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland.
   Mrs. Brundtland, whose party suffered its greatest postwar
defeat, said she will remain in office until opponents oust her
minority government. The non-socialist parties planned meetings next
week to discuss forming a coalition.
   Voters fed up with high unemployment, rising prices and little
perceived difference between the Labor and Conservative parties
streamed to the far-right Party of Progress and the Socialist Left,
the analysts said.
   ``This election was marked by enormous changes, and just the same
nothing changed,'' said political scientist Lars Svaasand of the
University of Bergen.
   Whichever side succeeds, it probably will control a minority with
limited ability to complete Norway's economic recovery, Svaasand
said.
   The VG newspaper called it ``the election that Norway lost.''
   ``There is a clear polarization in the system. Both the largest
parties suffered setbacks, but the Conservatives were the big
loser,'' said analyst Bernt Ole Aardal of the Institute for Social
Research.
   Analysts gave Mrs. Brundtland roughly equal chances of remaining
in government, with some suggesting she might be forced out
initially but regain power over the divisive non-socialist bloc.
   To gain power, the opposition bloc must come to terms with the
Progress party of Carl I. Hagen, who challenges the foundations of
Norway's social democracy. The party soared from two seats in the
1985 parliament to 22 in the new one.
   The non-socialist bloc won a slim majority of 84 seats to 80 for
Labor and the allied Socialist Left, which doubled its strength. The
single independent, Anders Aune, will probably support Labor, still
Norway's largest party.
   Hagen said he will support a vote to topple Mrs. Brundtland but
warned that if he is not included in a coalition his party will be
another opposition party.
   ``If they want the benefit of our support, it is at the cost of
our having influence,'' he said.
   ``The other non-socialist parties don't want anything to do with
the Progress party but they may be forced into cooperating,''
Svaasand said.
   Aardal said relations in the non-socialist bloc are tense and
that ``it will take a while until we see a solution for the whole
period.''
   ``My guess is that the government will operate on an
issue-by-issue basis. But that doesn't necessarity mean that it will
be inefficient and unstable. It has happened many times before in
Norwegian history,'' he said.
</TEXT>
