<FIRST>u a PM-Inmates'Infections     09-12 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Inmates' Infections,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Illness Kills Two in Jail; Inmates Seek Early Release</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for inmates at the county jail asked a
judge today to release up to 500 prisoners early because of a
bacterial infection that has killed two inmates and sickened as many
as 35 others.
   James Oitzinger also asked U.S. District Judge James DeAnda to
isolate inmates at risk of contracting the illness either because
they already are sick or have impaired immune systems.
   The hearing was expected to continue through the day.
   A bacterial infection known as pneumococcus bacteremia killed two
inmates Thursday, according to doctors. They said the two, ages 21
and 30, had had their spleens removed, leaving them more susceptible
to the infection.
   Since then, 18 more inmates have been admitted to Ben Taub
Hospital and at least 17 are in the jail infirmary, reporting
flu-like symptoms, authorities said. Cultures indicated pneumococcus
bacteria in five of the inmates at Ben Taub, one of whom is missing
his spleen and is in very critical condition, Dr. Stephen Greenberg,
an infectious disease expert at Baylor College of Medicine, said
Monday.
   ``We don't ever see five cases of pneumococcal bacteremia coming
from one place at one time,'' Greenberg said. Bacteremia is an
infection that attacks virtually all bodily systems.
   The cause of the other inmates' symptoms is not yet known, and
neither are the source of the outbreak and exactly how it spreads,
doctors said.
   Greenberg said outbreaks have been seen in the military and among
South African miners, groups that live in crowded conditions.
   The Harris County Jail, designed for 4,200 inmates, houses about
8,300. Although no specific measures were ordered by health
authorities, jail officials canceled religious services,
recreational activities and classes.
   Oitzinger, who represents inmates in a suit over jail
overcrowding, asked for early release of up to 500 inmates in jail
on misdemeanor charges.
   At the hearing, Sheriff Johnny Klevenhagen testified that medical
experts told him the outbreak was not caused by overcrowding. ``The
jail's not the breeding place and certainly not the environment''
for the illness, he said.
   Two doctors from the Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta
toured the jail Monday with state and local health officials but
declined to comment on their findings or plans to curb the spread of
the bacteria.
   Authorities were preparing to screen 3,200 inmates who indicated
they at risk of contracting the infection.
   Klevenhagen said he expects the number to be narrowed to about
500 once health officials question the group about any chronic
illnesses and immune-system problems.
</TEXT>
