<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     09-12 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former President's Sister-in-Law Among 16 Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen believed to be Sinhalese
radicals killed the sister-in-law of former president Junius
R.Jayewardene at a traffic intersection in downtown Colombo on
Tuesday, police said.
   Gladys Jayewardene, 72, was gunned down by two men on a
motorcycle, police said.
   No one claimed responsibility for the killing but police blamed
the People's Liberation Front, a Sinhalese extremist group that has
been trying to overthrow the government since 1987.
   Mrs. Jayewardene, the wife of the former president's younger
brother, Ronald, was the chairwoman of the State Pharmaceutical
Corp., a government-owned firm responsible for distributing medicine.
   Many of the drugs sold by the pharmaceutical corporation are
imported from neighboring India, which sent peacekeeping troops to
Sri Lanka two years ago. The deployment of the troops sparked a
violent protest by the People's Liberation Front, including a demand
to boycott Indian goods.
   Military officials blamed the radical group for 12 other deaths
in the country's south and center since Monday. At least three
people were killed in fighting between Indian soldiers and Tamils
rebels in the north.
   The officials, who cannot be identified under briefing rules,
said police found the bodies of 11 unidentified Sinhalese men on
Tuesday in Panadura town, 15 miles south of Colombo.
   On Monday, the director of a private supermarket chain was
abducted from his car at gunpoint and killed, the officials said.
They said R.S. Perera's body was found in Kahawita, a Colombo suburb.
   The killings occurred as the government prepared to meet leaders
of opposition parties Wednesday in a bid to end the ethnic violence.
   The violence was sparked by a Tamil movement for a separate
nation in the northeast. Tamils, who make up 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people, claim the Sinhalese-dominated government
deprives them of jobs and education.
   Junius Jayewardene's government attempted to end the insurgency
with an India-sponsored peace accord in July 1987, but it was
rejected by the largest rebel group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, who said it did not grant enough concessions to the Tamils.
   The Tigers turned their guns on Indian peacekeeping troops
deployed to monitor the accord.
   Besides the Tamil violence, the Sinhalese front's campaign has
claimed 5,000 lives since 1987. Most victims have been Sinhalese, a
community that makes up 75 percent of the population.
   The group protests the July accord, saying it gave too many
concessions to the Tamils and compromised the country's independence
by inviting Indian soldiers to Sri Lanka.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa has invited the Sinhalese front to
Wednesday's meeting but the guerrilla group has not responded. It
has rejected at least five calls from the government for cease-fires.
   Two Tamil Tiger representatives will attend the meeting as
observers, government officials said Tuesday. They said most of the
23 political parties have accepted Premadasa's invitation.
</TEXT>
