<FIRST>u w PM-Congress-Drugs 4thLd-Writethru a0612-a0614-a0583 09-12
0843</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Drugs, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0612-a0614-a0583,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Push to Expand Bush's Anti-Drug Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democrats today pushed for a $2.2
billion expansion of President Bush's anti-drug plan, but top
administration officials immediately said they would urge a veto if
the proposal reaches the White House.
   In a statement released by the Office of Management and Budget,
administration officials said Bush's $7.9 billion proposal ``made
the tough choices,'' while the Democratic alternative ``throws money
at the plan.''
   The clash came as Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., chairman of the
Appropriations Committee, formally proposed the legislation with the
backing of Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell.
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas also said the
Democratic proposal was too expansive, and legislative leaders met
off the Senate floor to discuss the measure, which Byrd sought to
add to the transportation appropriations bill.
   Secretary of Defense Richard Cheney, drug policy coordinator
William J. Bennett, Budget Director Richard Darman and other senior
advisers will recommend to the president that he veto the Democratic
plan, the OMB statement said.
   Meanwhile, Bennett told the House Foreign Affairs Committee
today, ``I don't think it's unreasonable to say that we are talking
about a $50 billion program over five years'' to fight drugs.
   But several members told him it would be unacceptable for the
administration to find those funds by shifting money out of other
vital domestic programs.
   Chairman Dante Fascell, D-Fla., told Bennett: ``I don't want to
see one dime diverted from from essential domestic purposes that are
in fact part of the drug problem; I think that would be a tragic
mistake.''
   Fascell said funds should not be shifted from such programs as
education, health, welfare, housing or from programs designed to
help communities deal with the impact of large-scale legal and
illegal immigration.
   ``That doesn't help communities win the drug fight,'' Fascell
said.
   Bennett suggested that a large percentage of the needed money may
come from drug users themselves in the form of heay fines imposed on
drug offenders.
   ``Substantially increased fines will come back into the
Treasury,'' he said.
   Byrd said Monday his plan would increase the government's
anti-drug budget by $3.9 billion above the level Congress would have
otherwise provided. To pay for the extra spending, Byrd proposed
across-the-board cuts in many domestic and defense programs of 0.575
percent.
   ``He may have the best solution on the funding side of the
equation,'' Dole said of Byrd's proposal before debate began. ``I'm
not certain of the amount, but perhaps that's something we can work
out.''
   Byrd said Monday he was seeking to transfer money to drug
spending from other programs because Bush has refused to consider
tax increases.
   ``The president says, `Read my lips,''' Byrd told reporters. ``He
says he won't support any increase in taxes. So I have to do what I
can do.''
   Byrd, whose panel oversees about half of all federal spending,
said he would introduce the proposal as an amendment to the $11.9
billion transportation appropriations bill for fiscal 1990. That
bill also contains language permanently banning cigarette smoking on
all domestic airline flights.
   Byrd not only topped the dollars Bush would spend, but said his
proposed across-the-board cuts were fairer than what the president
proposed.
   Last Tuesday, Bush asked Congress to increase anti-drug efforts
by $717 million. He said he would trim a handful of programs,
including immigration aid, rural development, housing and a Defense
Department radio system. The president has ruled out a tax increase
to pay for the new drug spending.
   ``The drug epidemic facing this country is a crisis that affects
us all,'' Byrd told reporters. ``In my view it is critical that we
look for solutions that will seek to spread not only the pain but
also the gain in a fair and even-handed manner.''
   The funds Byrd proposed spending include $1 billion for new
prisons, $200 million to help state and local law enforcement
agencies, $81 million for new federal attorneys, $97 million for the
FBI and $59 million for the Drug Enforcement Administration.
   He would also spend $1.1 billion for drug and alcohol treatment,
$289 million for education, $45 million for customs agents, $43
million for the Customs Service to buy new helicopters and
airplanes; $100 million to help drug-addicted veterans, and $100
million for public housing authorities to deal with drug problems.
   Of the extra spending, Byrd said 53 percent would go to law
enforcement and 47 percent to education, treatment and prevention
programs.
   Social Security and other benefit programs would be exempted from
his spending cuts, Byrd said.
   Because the Pentagon budget will be close to $300 billion next
year, the cut in defense spending would total more than $1.5 billion.
   Byrd said when he explained his amendment to Senate Majority
Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, ``He liked it.''
   He also said he had spoken to the Democratic chairmen of most of
the 13 Appropriations subcommittees and to the ranking Republican on
the committee, Mark Hatfield of Oregon.
   ``His reaction was positive,'' he said.
</TEXT>
