<FIRST>r a AM-AtticaArtifacts     09-12 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Attica Artifacts,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Archaeological Finds Will be Buried to Mark Attica Riot Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATTICA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Key chains, wallets and other objects that
inmates took from hostages during the 1971 Attica prison uprising
will be buried in a capsule Wednesday on the 18th anniversary of the
bloody riot.
   Inmates buried the incriminating objects shortly before the
prison was retaken by authorities in a hail of state police gunfire
on Sept. 13, 1971. Forty-three inmates and 11 guards were killed
during the riot and retaking of the prison 30 miles east of Buffalo.
   Guards using a metal detector during a routine sweep of a
prison's yard discovered the cache in 1986, but the find was not
publicized until now. They found enough corroded padlocks, keys to
prison gates and doors, personal car keys, key chains and empty
wallets to fill two and a half shopping bags.
   On Wednesday, officials plan to bury the objects in a capsule
near a monument to the prison guards killed during the riot.
   The items were discovered on Sept. 9, 1986 _ an anniversary of
the outbreak of the rebellion.
   ``They were found on the 15th anniversary, 15 minutes to the hour
that it started,'' said prison Sgt. Robert Kauffman. ``That's what
was so ironic about it. It was very somber at the jail after we
brought them in. A lot of the old-timers came down and saw them and
got very quiet.''
</TEXT>
