<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 1416EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Yeltsin 5thLd-Writethru a0623-a0595 09-12 0870</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yeltsin, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0623-a0595,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Tells Yeltsin Administration Has Positive Relationship with
Gorbachev</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs, editing to shorten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush told Soviet maverick Boris
Yeltsin his administration enjoys a ``very positive relationship''
with Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev, the White House said today.
   The president met with the Soviet official, an outspoken critic
of some of Gorbachev's policies, for about 15 minutes, according to
a statement by White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   The statement said Bush ``dropped by'' a meeting between Yeltsin
and National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft.
   Fitzwater earlier had suggested that the session would be little
more than a handshake between the president and the visiting Soviet
figure, saying: ``We don't want to do anything to foster internal
conflict that might be associated with this trip.''
   However, Fitzwater's later statement said the meeting included
discussion of overall U.S.-Soviet relations and of drugs.
   Yeltsin said in a speech prior to the meeting that he wanted to
tell Bush, ``We have to combine our efforts to rescue perestroika,
which is in a super-critical situation today.''
   ``The president said that there is much interest in Mr. Yeltsin's
visit. He expressed his view that the overall bilateral relationship
is in good shape,'' said Fitzwater's statement.
   ``In this connection, the president noted his very positive
relationship with General Secretary Gorbachev and reiterated his
support for perestroika,'' it continued.
   ``The president emphasized that the American people share his
hope for the success of the reform movement in the Soviet Union,''
the short statement added.
   Vice President Dan Quayle also ``dropped by'' to greet Yeltsin,
the statement said.
   Fitzwater said Bush met with Yeltsin shortly before his
nationally televised anti-drug speech to school children.
   The spokesman said the president mentioned the speech to the
Soviet official ``and the problem that drugs have created throughout
the world. The president and Mr. Yeltsin both agreed that drugs are
a major problem that touches on both American and Soviet societies.''
   The 58-year-old Yeltsin, ousted as Moscow's Communist Party chief
in 1987 but then elected to parliament with overwhelming popular
support in a contested election, arrived Saturday on a private tour.
He has been prodding Mikhail Gorbachev to step up the pace of reform
in the Soviet Union.
   ``We didn't want to indicate that we were trying to provide a
platform for dissent,'' Fitzwater said.
   Yeltsin also was to meet with Secretary of State James A. Baker
III and Sens. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., and Barbara Milkulski, D-Md.
   He announed Monday night that he would cut short his U.S. visit
to go home to attend meetings on pressure from various nationalities
for independence from the Kremlin.
   In his speech today at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore,
Yeltsin said perestroika had not improved the delivery of food and
other consumer goods to the Soviet people.
   He repeated earlier statements that unless Gorbachev improves the
consumer goods situation in the Soviet Union, he faces an upheaval
from below. He has said Gorbachev has six months to a year to
achieve progress.
   ``I have a lot to tell President Bush,'' Yeltsin said, but did
not spell out what requests he might make of the U.S. government.
   White House officials had said Monday the administration did not
want to send the wrong signal to Gorbachev by having Bush meet with
Yeltsin, who has been prodding the Soviet leader to speed reforms.
   In a question-and-answer session with reporters, Yeltsin said he
approved of the exodus of thousands of East Germans through Hungary
to West Germany, where they have been granted citizenship.
   ``It should be regulated by international agreements stating that
people have the right to live where they want,'' Yeltsin said.
   Speaking Monday evening at Columbia University, Yeltsin said the
Kremlin has suppressed numerous peoples in its power for too long.
   ``The feeling of national dignity was constantly being crushed in
our country,'' he said through an interpreter. ``If they even wanted
to build a school, they had to go hat in hand, so to speak, to
Moscow. It was very offensive.''
   Giving Soviet republics more power to govern themselves would
greatly reduce tensions, he said.
   The problem is serious enough, he said, that he was cutting his
two-week tour by a week to attend a special meeting in Moscow to
discuss the nationalities issue. If the problem is to be solved, the
ruling Politburo must be reinvigorated with progressive-thinking
leaders, Yeltsin said.
   ``We have so many odious and incompetent people in the
Politburo,'' he said. ``All they do is raise questions and never
answer them. They are hanging on to their positions with dear life.
We need to catapult them out like they do with ejection seats. But
the question is, who is willing to push the button?''
   He said the Soviet people should ``throw off our false pride and
take a lot from the American experience'' of running a country.
   In Moscow, Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov
said Yeltsin's views were his own and not necessarily the
government's.
   Yeltsin's visit is organized by the Esalen Institute
Soviet-American Exchange Program. He is receiving $25,000 per
speech, which will pay for the trip and contribute to AIDS research
in the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
