<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Thruelsen     09-12 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Thruelsen,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Saturday Evening Post Editor Dies at 81</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLD LYME, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard D. Thruelsen, who wrote about
science and aviation and covered World War II during a long career
as a writer and editor for the Saturday Evening Post, has died. He
was 81.
   Thruelsen died Sunday at home, a spokesman for the
Alderson-Prentis Funeral Service said. The cause of death was not
disclosed.
   Thruelsen joined the magazine as an associate editor in 1936,
became a senior editor in 1958 and retired in 1962.
   He learned to fly in the 1920s and came to the magazine as an
expert on science and aviation. He later served in World War II and
helped cover the war for the Post.
   Thruelsen served in intelligence and information units in the
war, but went on numerous bombing missions with the 8th Bomber
Command. Based on those experiences, he wrote ``Target, Germany,'' a
book depicting a day in the life of a crew member of a B-17 bomber.
   His other books included ``Men at Work,'' published in 1950;
``Voyage of the Vagabond,'' 1965, and ``The Grumman Story,'' 1976.
   He is survived by a son, two daughters and a granddaughter.
Funeral arrangments were private.
</TEXT>
