<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 1433EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TMIWater     09-12 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TMI Water,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>NRC Staff Approves Evaporation of Water at Three Mile Island</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Mile Island plant operators should
be allowed to boil away 2.3 million gallons of radioactive water
left over from the nation's worst nuclear accident, the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission staff says.
   The staff Monday amended the Unit 2 reactor license to allow the
process, concluding there would be no ``significant effect on the
quality of the human environment.''
   The full NRC will vote on evaporation procedures in six weeks.
   GPU Nuclear Corp. has said the water contains radioactive tritium
and trace amounts of cesium 137 and strontium 90. The three isotopes
cannot be completely removed from the water and will be released
into the atmosphere during evaporation.
   The plant operator has said it hopes to begin the two-year, $4
million process in November. The water has been stored since the
March 1979 accident, when the Unit 2 reactor lost cooling water and
half the radioactive core melted.
   Two citizens groups, Susquehanna Valley Alliance and Three Mile
Island Alert, contend that any further release of radiation would be
hazardous.
</TEXT>
