<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 1908EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BabySafety     09-12 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baby Safety,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deaths 75, Injuries Exceed 72,000 From Nursery Items</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 75 children under 5 die each year of
injuries involving nursery items, the Consumer Product Safety
Commission reported Tuesday.
   The commission also said about 72,300 children in the same age
group were injured last year in accidents involving those things.
   The figures were released in a statement announcing observance of
next week as Baby Safety Week by the commission and the Juvenile
Products Manufacturers Association.
   ``There is no substitute for adult supervision protecting
children from death and injury,'' said Anne Graham, acting chairman
of the commission.
   The commission said an average of 76.4 deaths per year related to
nursery products were reported from 1983 through 1987.
   Of these, an average of 54.4 were releated to cribs, many of them
older cribs such as those stored in attics or sold at garage and
yard sales. The commission said these cribs may have slats more than
2] inches apart, decorative cutouts or high corner posts. Such
features can result in strangulation.
   Other items of nursery equipment blamed in the deaths of children
included playpens, accounting for an average of 4.2 deaths, and high
chairs, an average of 2.4. On the average there was one death a year
connected with strollers and carriages and less than one from baby
walkers or jumpers, from changing tables and from baby gates and
enclosures.
   Other unspecified items accounted for an average of 13.2 deaths
per year.
   Baby walkers and jumpers, on the other hand, accounted for the
largest number of injuries, 17,700, followed by strollers and
carriages 13,300, cribs 12,800, high chairs 8,200, changing tables
2,300, playpens 1,700, baby gates and enclosures 400 and other items
15,800.
   The figures do not add up to the totals because of rounding.
   The commission urged parents to monitor the nursery equipment
used in child care facilities, as well as that in their own homes.
</TEXT>
