<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 1915EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NixonImpeachment     09-12 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nixon Impeachment,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Impeached Judge Tells Senators He Was `Wrongly Convicted'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. District Judge Walter Nixon told the
Senate on Tuesday that the trial that led to his imprisonment on
perjury charges was a ``miscarriage of justice'' and that he wants
to return as an active federal judge.
   Nixon, 60, has been in prison serving a five-year sentence since
March 1988 but will continue to collect his $89,500 annual judge's
salary until he resigns, dies or is convicted by the Senate on
impeachment charges.
   ``I was wrongly convicted,'' Nixon told a 12-member Senate panel
that will summarize the evidence against him for the full Senate,
which is trying the judge following his impeachment by the House
last year.
   The case revolves around Nixon's knowledge of a marijuana
smuggling case and whether he tried to influence its outcome. It
involved the son of a wealthy businessman in Hattiesburg, Miss., who
had sold Nixon lucrative oil properties.
   Nixon denied to federal investigators and a grand jury that he
ever discussed the case with anyone. That denial was the basis for
his later conviction on perjury charges.
   Nixon, who remains chief U.S. district judge for the southern
district of Mississippi, was appointed by President Johnson and is
the last remaining Democrat on the federal bench in that state.
   He told the Senate committee Tuesday the conversations that were
the central points of his impeachment were not ``discussions'' about
the narcotics case and were was so minor that he never thought to
mention them to federal investigators or the grand jury.
   Nixon said that in March 1983 he visited oilman Wiley Fairchild
because Fairchild had asked him to keep in touch with him after he
sold him oil property in 1980.
   Fairchild was ``mad as hell'' because his son, who'd been
arrested on narcotics charges, was causing the Fairchild name ``to
be dragged through the news media,'' Nixon said.
   Furthermore, Fairchild said he thought the local prosecutor, Paul
``Bud'' Holmes and another attorney, Carroll Ingram, were trying to
blackmail him into paying more legal fees by getting his son
indicted in state court, said Nixon.
   ``I was taken aback,'' said Nixon, who said he didn't believe
either lawyer, both friends of his, would be involved in blackmail.
   ``I thought it was a figment of his imagination,'' said Nixon.
   The case had already been handled federally and the son, Drew
Fairchild, had arranged a plea bargain that kept him out of jail.
   Holmes testified last week that at unbeknownst to the elder
Fairchild or Nixon, he also had arranged a plea bargain with the son.
   Nixon testified that at one point, he went to Holmes' house to
borrow some Hank Williams records. When he got there he mentioned to
Holmes what Fairchild had said about blackmail.
   Nixon said Holmes was on the phone most of the time he was there.
He said he was about 20 feet away from Holmes but could not hear
Holmes' phone conversations because of loud background music. But he
said at one point Holmes called him over and handed him the phone.
   On the other end of the line was Wiley Fairchild.
   ``He said, `I'm glad you talked to that fellow. I'm satisfied,'''
said Nixon. ``I said, `that's good' and handed the phone back to
Holmes.''
   Nixon said he went back to playing records and Holmes talked a
little longer to Fairchild.
   Nixon said he asked Holmes why he placed the call and the
prosecutor said it was because he wanted ``to get the damn thing
straightened out.''
   The judge testified that he thought Fairchild's remark about
being satisfied was a reference to the blackmail accusation and that
he never thought about the incident again.
   He said that when questioned by federal officials and during
grand jury proceedings about whether he had discussed Drew
Fairchild's case, he did not think about the phone conversation that
night at Holmes' house.
   He said at the time he did not consider it a ``discussion'' of
the case and to this day does not.
   The House, voting unanimously for impeachment, alleged:
   _Nixon lied when he told a grand jury he never discussed the case
against Drew Fairchild with Holmes.
   _Nixon lied when he told a grand jury he had nothing to do
officialy or unofficially with the Fairchild case and never
influenced anyone in the case.
   _Nixon undermined ``the integrity of the judiciary'' and
disobeyed the law by making 14 false or misleading statements during
an interview with the federal investigators and in his sworn grand
jury testimony.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
