<FIRST>r a AM-ChildVandals     09-12 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Vandals,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Say Children Vandalize School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMILLUS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five children ages 5 to 8 broke into a
school and stole calculators and crayons, toppled desks, smashed a
glass door and vandalized a dozen classrooms, police said.
   The two boys, ages 7 and 8, and three girls, ages 5, 6 and 7,
told police they used stones to smash a window to get into
Stonehedge Elementary School, according to police reports.
   The damage, estimated at more than $3,000, was discovered Monday
morning, although two of the children had been found in the school
Sunday afternoon when officers responded to an alarm, police said.
   Officer Thomas Marlin said money, calculators, pencils, books and
crayons were taken, and electronic equipment and hanging plants were
damaged. Desks and file cabinets were toppled, and a glass door was
smashed, he said.
   All five children are related and share a grandmother living in
Camillus. Three of them, a kindergartener and two first-graders,
live with the grandmother and attend Stonehedge. The others live in
Syracuse and were visiting the grandmother, police said.
   Donald Stebbins, principal at the 880-pupil school, said the
three Stonehedge pupils admitted vandalizing the classrooms. They
were suspended for a week, he said.
   ``They know they did something that was not correct, but I'm not
sure they understand the full impact of that,'' he said Tuesday.
   Police who went to the school Sunday said they found two children
but no sign of vandalism in the school.
   Later the same day, the grandmother reported the children
missing. When officers approached the children near the school, the
children threw a calculator, notebook, some change and school
supplies into the shrubs, police said.
   On Monday, a janitor reported finding 12 second-floor classrooms
vandalized.
   Police said they won't press charges because state law doesn't
hold children 7 and younger responsible for their actions.
   The police files, however, will be turned over to Onondaga County
Family Court for consideration of possible action regarding the
8-year-old.
   Principal Donald Stebbins said the three Stonehedge pupils had
been suspended for a week. The West Genesee School District will
seek restitution through Family Court, he said.
</TEXT>
