<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-ArmsTalks     09-12 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Arms Talks,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Puzzled by Soviet Criticism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration called ``somewhat
mystifying'' Tuesday a charge by the Soviet foreign minister that
the United States has been dragging its feet on nuclear arms
negotiations.
   ``We reject any suggestion of United States' foot-dragging in the
START talks, or that negotiations have been put on a back burner,''
White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters.
   He said the United States was still awaiting a Soviet reponse to
U.S. proposals made ``at the latest round of the START talks,
including new ideas on verification and stability measures.'' START
is an acronym for strategic arms reduction talks.
   Fitzwater called Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze's
criticism of the U.S. stance on arms control ``somewhat mystifying
in the sense that we have felt the negotiations were going ahead
rather well.''
   Shevardnadze, in an interview published Monday in the Soviet
government daily Izvestia, charged that talks in Geneva on a partial
nuclear test ban had been ``frozen'' because of the new Bush
administration's indecision.
   He contrasted the ``constraint and timidity'' of the Bush
approach with progress on arms reductions made during Ronald
Reagan's presidency.
   Shevardnadze said both countries and ``the entire world community
have lost a lot'' because of the Bush administration's ``restrained,
indecisive position.''
   Shevardnadze is scheduled to meet with Secretary of State James
A. Baker III in Wyoming on Sept. 22-23 for discussions on nuclear
testing and conventional arms reductions. The talks could be a
prelude to a later summit between Bush and Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev.
   Fitzwater, asked if he felt the Soviet minister was playing
politics with his criticism, said, ``I wouldn't want to characterize
his motives. I don't know.''
   But the White House went out of its way Tuesday not to antagonize
the Kremlin on another matter: the visit to Washington of Soviet
maverick Boris Yeltsin.
   Bush met with Yeltsin for about 15 minutes and ``emphasized that
the American people share his hope for the success of the reform
movement in the Soviet Union,'' the White House spokesman said
afterwards.
   Bush also ``noted his very positive relationship'' with Gorbachev
and reiterated his support for perestroika, Fitzwater said in a
written statement.
   Fitzwater said beforehand that Bush only planned to drop by
Yeltsin's meeting with national security adviser Brent Scowcroft to
shake hands.
   Fitzwater said Bush did not want to ``provide a platform for
dissent'' or ``do anything to foster internal conflict that might be
associated with this trip.''
   The meeting was closed to reporters, who usually are allowed to
observe the start of Bush's meetings with visiting dignitaries.
</TEXT>
