<SECOND>AM-Public Broadcasting,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texan, Californian Get CPB Posts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial circuits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ken Towery was re-elected chairman and Daniel
L. Brenner was elected vice chairman of the Corporation for Public
Broadcasting on Tuesday, the corporation said.
   Towery, a Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist and newspaper
publisher, first was elected chairman in February to fill the
vacancy created when former chairman Howard Gutin's term on the
board ended March 1.
   Towery was appointed to a five-year term on the board in November
1981 and was reappointed to a second five-year term in October 1986.
His terms expires in March 1991.
   A resident of Austin, Texas, Towery publishes three Texas
newspapers. In 1955 he won a Pulitzer for his series of stories
exposing fraud and corruption in the Texas Veterans Land Program,
the corporation said.
   Brenner is director of the communications law program and teaches
law at the University of California, Los Angeles. He also has served
as adviser to former Federal Communications Commission chairmen Mark
Fowler and Charles Ferris.
   Brenner was appointed to a five-year term on the board in October
1986. His term expires in March 1991. He currently is chairman of
the board's audit committee.
   The corporation is a private, non-profit organization chartered
by Congress in 1967 to support non-commercial U.S. radio and
television.
