<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 1626EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-PrimaryRdp Bjt   09-12 0947</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Primary Rdp, Bjt,0973</SECOND>
<HEAD>Election Stakes: Two House Seats, Mayors' Posts in New York, Detroit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Will be led with returns; first polls close in Texas at 8 p.m.
EDT. Matter below dash should stand. ^LaserPhotos DT1, NY12, NY17</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   California and Texas held special elections Tuesday to fill the
seats of two Democratic congressmen who resigned over alleged ethics
violations, while primary voters in New York and Detroit weighed
re-election bids by Mayors Edward Koch and Coleman Young.
   Democrats were hoping the popularity of former House Speaker Jim
Wright and former Majority Whip Tony Coelho would carry Democratic
candidates to victory in special elections to fill the two leaders'
seats in Texas and California. In Detroit, Young was expected to
coast into a general election runoff with one of two likely
challengers, but in New York, Koch faced the possibility of losing
the Democratic primary to Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins.
   Two other candidates _ Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin and former
transit chief Richard Ravitch _ also were on the Democratic ballot
in New York.
   Koch, voting in Greenwich Village, said he and Dinkins were so
close that the primary would be decided by the Hispanic vote,
amounting to about 10 percent of the expected turnout.
   ``I'm surging,'' said Koch, who was seeking an unprecedented
fourth term. ``That's the best place to be the day before and the
day of the primary.''
   Dinkins, hoping to become New York's first black mayor, also
voted early and said he hoped to win ``with a broad base'' that
would make it easier to govern.
   The winner of the Democratic primary will face the winner of a
Republican match between former prosecutor Rudolph Giuliani and
cosmetics heir Ronald Lauder. Giuliani has been well ahead in the
polls.
   Young was expected to lead a field of 13 candidates in his bid
for a record fifth term. The top two finishers will go head-to-head
in the runoff; Rep. John Conyers and accountant Tom Barrow were
considered the most likely prospects for the second spot on the
November ballot.
   In Fort Worth, Texas, voters in Wright's former district had a
choice of two political newcomers _ Democrat Pete Geren, an attorney
and former aide to Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, and Republican Bob Lanier, a
physician and television commentator.
   Wright campaigned for Geren, just as Coelho actively assisted the
campaign of Democratic Assemblyman Gary Condit, his would-be
successor in California's San Joaquin Valley. Seven other candidates
were on the ballot, including former Republican Assemblyman Clare
Berryhill. If no candidate won a majority of the vote, a runoff
would be held in November.
   Several cities besides New York and Detroit were holding mayoral
primaries.
   _ Buffalo, N.Y., Mayor James Griffin faced two challengers in the
Democratic primary, and was running unopposed on the Republican and
Conservative party ballots.
   _ In New Haven, Conn., where Mayor Biagio DeLieto is retiring,
state Sen. John Daniels ran against former city administrator John
DeStefano Jr. in the Democratic primary. Daniels hoped to become the
city's first black mayor.
   _ Minneapolis Mayor Don Fraser opposed six challengers in his bid
for re-election.
   _ In St. Paul. Minn., where Mayor George Latimer is retiring,
nine candidates were on the primary ballot. As in Minneapolis, the
top two vote-getters will advance to the Nov. 7 general election.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The New York City race was the liveliest there since 1977, when
Koch won his first term in office after a free-for-all primary and a
general election race against then-Lt. Gov. Mario Cuomo, now the
governor.
   Koch, 64, was all but counted out as a formidable candidate a few
months ago, his popularity badly damaged by corruption scandals and
his propensity for angering entire blocs of voters _ blacks and
Irish-Americans most prominently _ with his frequently outrageous
remarks.
   Early polls gave big leads to Dinkins, 62, whose quiet, dignified
manner contrasted sharply with that of the bombastic mayor.
   But Koch steadily ate away at Dinkins' lead in the weeks before
the election and the race was considered a toss-up by the last
weekend of the campaign.
   On Monday, Dinkins and Koch ran into each other at a high school
dedication and agreed to a ``display of unity'' on Wednesday,
regardless of which candidate won the primary.
   No such display is expected in Detroit, where Young has undergone
vigorous attacks by challengers who ran what were dubbed ``ABC''
campaigns _ ``Anybody But Coleman.''
   They said the 71-year-old mayor has been in office too long and
accused him of paying too much attention to downtown business
interests at the expense of the city's poorer neighborhoods.
   The two House vacancies were the outgrowth of one of the biggest
political shakeups in congressional history _ the resignations of
Wright and Coelho in the wake of investigations into alleged ethics
violations.
   In Texas, Republicans saw the Geren-Lanier race as a rare chance
to break into a district that has long sent Democrats to Congress.
   But Lanier, 44, a pediatric allergist who is featured on the
television program ``60-Second Housecall,'' called his race an
``upstream swim'' against Geren, 37. Geren raised nearly twice as
much campaign money and had the advantage of Wright's endorsement.
   In the California race, Condit stressed his ties to Coelho, and
Berryhill conceded that there was little point in attacking the
former congressman, who remains extremely popular in his old
district.
   The major issues in the race were abortion, highway congestion
and agricultural problems.
   Berryhill opposed abortion except in cases involving rape, incest
and a threat to the life of the mother. Condit opposed abortion but
said it was a ``personal decision that one needs to make for one's
self.''
</TEXT>
