<DOCNO> AP890912-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 2011EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-High-DefinitionTV     09-12 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-High-Definition TV,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Reprimands Mosbacher on HDTV, Source Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher won't
concentrate on promoting a high-definition television industry in
the United States after being reprimanded by the White House, a
congressional source said.
   ``Mosbacher in their eyes is a renegade promoting industial
policy and they thought it was absolutely necessary to reprimand
him,'' said the source, who also spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Mosbacher ``was made to stand in front of the class and made to
say `I believe in the free market 500 times,''' the source said.
   As a result, the Commerce Department will consider HDTV, the next
generation of television, only as part of a broad-based effort to
boost U.S. technological competitiveness, an administration source
said Monday.
   Mosbacher said for months that he was prepared to recommend that
the Bush administration loosen tax and antitrust laws to jump-start
private American industry efforts to compete with Europe and Japan
to build HDTV, which promises motion-picture clarity and compact
disc-quality sound.
   Commerce officials first promised Congress they would unveil the
government plans for HDTV by midsummer and, later, by the end of the
year.
   Now, the administration official said, the HDTV initiative is on
hold.
   ``There isn't necessarily going to be a single HDTV report as was
once envisioned,'' the official said, adding that the issue would be
viewed in a broader context.
   ``We're going to study it further and probably weave it into a
more extensive high-tech competiveness package. There's no
date-certain of when that will be ready,'' said the official, who
spoke only on condition of anonymity.
   ``It's something that we're working toward. But it's just a
bigger animal than we thought.''
   The congressional source said the White House had reined in
Mosbacher for talking in terms reminiscent of the ``industrial
policy'' program that Democratic presidential candidate Michael
Dukakis advocated in the 1988 campaign.
   The Wall Street Journal last month quoted sources who said
Mosbacher's HDTV initiative was soundly criticized by other
government agencies and was near death.
   Advocates of HDTV say it could revitalize a moribund U.S.
electronics industry and have important applications in medicine,
defense and other industries.
   It is envisioned as a $20 billion industry by 2000 and would be a
``technology driver'' for industries such as computer chips.
   The American Electronics Association has asked Congress for more
than a billion dollars in development money for HDTV, and several
bills are pending in Congress that would provide taxpayer money to
spur the industry.
   The Defense Department has allotted $30 million in seed money for
the U.S. HDTV industry.
   But a Congressional Budget Office report last month said HDTV
claims were ``very optimistic'' and that even under the rosiest of
scenarios, HDTV sales will be small relative to other electronic
equipment markets.
   The congressional official said nervous electronics industry
officials are beginning to back away from HDTV.
   Richard Wiley, chairman of a broadcast industry panel that will
advise the Federal Communications Commission on setting a
transmission standard for HDTV by 1992, said last week there are
only eight applicants _ down from 14 _ who will be ready to begin
testing next year.
   He said testing will begin in January in Alexandria, Va., by the
Advanced Television Test Center and Cable Labs.
</TEXT>
