<DOCNO> AP890912-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 2019EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-World     09-12 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-World,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Cites Progress, Problems in World Hotspots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
said in his annual report on the state of the world Tuesday that
there is a new international atmosphere of cooperation but that
grave problems remain in the Middle East.
   Perez de Cuellar also recommended that foreign ministers of the
15-member Security Council meet periodically to consider
international peace and security in different regions to avert
conflicts and defuse explosive situations. The idea is not new but
the secretary-general placed special emphasis on prevention of armed
conflicts, as well as peacekeeping operations to control them.
   The U.N. chief, in a 28-page survey of international problems and
progress, said the past year ``has brought little relief'' from
frequent, sometimes massive violations of human rights worldwide.
   But the world, he said, is witnessing ``the end of the era of
sterile confrontations'' between East and West. In the past year, he
said, the assistance of the United Nations was sought as never
before.
   A major U.N. accomplishment was implementation of an independence
plan for Namibia, formerly Southwest Africa, from South Africa, he
said.
   Despite U.N. successes in other areas, the situation in the
Middle East remains a source of grave concern, Perez de Cuellar said.
   Hopes for early progress because of the Palestinian National
Council's conciliatory statements toward Israel ``have sadly given
way to mistrust and doubt among the parties concerned,'' he said.
Efforts to pave the way to negotiations have proved ``frustratingly
inconclusive.''
   He said the situation in the Israeli-occupied territories has
worsened steadily since the Palestinian uprising began nearly two
years ago, and that Lebanon's government and society also are
disintegrating because of escalating violence between Christians and
Moslems there.
   Concerning the divided island of Cyprus, the secretary-general
said, ``We have now reached the critical juncture where an overall
settlement that will safeguard the legitimate interests and meet the
concerns of both communities seems possible.''
   He has been meeting with leaders of the Greek Cypriot and Turkish
Cypriot communities.
   Perez de Cuellar said one place where U.N. involvement had not
solved a problem was in Afghanistan, where Moslem rebels are
fighting a Soviet-backed government.
   Efforts to end the fighting have failed and U.N. humanitarian
assistance to Afghanistan has been ``severely impeded'' because of a
massive infusion of military aid from the United States, Pakistan
and the Soviet Union to the warring parties, he said.
   In addition, despite a year-old U.N.-supervised cease-fire in the
Iran-Iraq war, both sides remain far apart and a U.N. peace plan has
not been implemented, the secretary-general reported.
   Although the United Nations is at the forefront of international
efforts in peacekeeping and other areas, the secretary-general said
the organization is short of funds and greater demands are being
made for more U.N. operations.
   ``The present financial position is not reassuring,'' he said.
   As of Aug. 31, outstanding contributions to the regular budget
exceeded $688 million, including $347 million for the current year,
the U.N. chief reported. For peacekeeping operations, the arrears
were $661 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
