<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 2004EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Freighter-Cocaine     09-12 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Freighter-Cocaine,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Agents Make Biggest Bust Since Bush Crackdown</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILL LESTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents who hauled in 2,700 pounds of
cocaine, 17 defendants and five boats described the bust Tuesday as
a ``textbook case'' of how U.S. agencies can choke off the cocaine
pipeline from Colombia.
   The seizure of the freighter Nerma, allegedly used as a smuggling
``mother ship,'' as well as three speedboats and a trawler used to
haul the cocaine to land was described by agents as the largest
since President Bush announced his battle plan against drug
trafficking.
   Videotape provided by the Coast Guard showed a chase in which the
speedboats tried to evade a persistent, but slower Coast Guard
craft, which fired 43 warning shots near the speedboats. A fourth
speedboat escaped.
   The drug organization supervising the cocaine smuggling was based
in Miami and had been under investigation for several months, said
Drug Enforcement Administration agent Tom Cash. More arrests were
expected.
   Federal agents moved in early Sunday while cocaine was being
unloaded from the Nerma in Bahamian water, the document said.
   The cocaine was believed to have originated in Medellin,
Colombia, home of the enormous Medellin cartel of cocaine
traffickers, and was loaded onto the freighter on the island of
Aruba, off the northern coast of Venezuela.
   The cocaine had left Colombia before the Aug. 18 assassination of
Colombian presidential candidate Luis Carlos Galan set off a new
crackdown in Colombia and was already ``in the pipeline'' to the
United States, the DEA estimated.
   Cash said the bust ``is indicative of the magnitude of the
pipeline.''
   ``This is a textbook case of what taxpayers get for their money''
in drug enforcement,'' he said.
   The DEA, Coast Guard, Customs and local police were involved,
officials said.
   A Coast Guard cutter had been sent to intercept the Nerma,
registered in the South Pacific island nation of Vanuatu, after the
ship was detected on radar Saturday, officials said.
   Coast Guardsmen boarded the Nerma early the next day after seeing
bales of cocaine, each weighing about 70 pounds, floating alongside,
court documents said. Each bale consisted of plastic packages
bundled around flotation devices.
   Seven Danish crew members aboard the freighter were arrested and
ordered held without bond Monday.
   Six more men were arrested aboard the three speedboats. And four
were arrested late Monday in Miami in the vicinity of the trawler,
which apparently picked up a load from the Nerma before the Coast
Guard reached the freighter and had sailed into the Miami River.
   The defendants face federal charges of possession of cocaine with
intent to distribute.
   Authorities seized 1,100 pounds of cocaine bobbing near the
freighter Nerma. An additional 70 pounds was seized inside the
freighter and 1,540 pounds was seized aboard the trawler, the J.J.
Lorick, DEA spokesman John Fernandes said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
