<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 2032EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AbortionPolitics     09-12 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Politics,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Pivotal Issue in New Jersey and Virginia Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abortion will prove an important and perhaps
decisive issue in the two governor's elections this fall in Virginia
and New Jersey, Democratic consultants and analysts said Tuesday.
   But the analysts, in a discussion of abortion politics sponsored
by a liberal think tank, differed on whether Democratic candidates
are smart to promote positions in favor of abortion rights in other
races around the country.
   Democratic candidates for governor in both states holding
gubernatorial elections this year have staked out positions
generally in favor of abortion rights.
   A consultant to the Virginia Democratic candidate, Lt. Gov. L.
Douglas Wilder, suggested Wilder plans to use the issue in
television advertising in his race. He faces Republican nominee J.
Marshall Coleman, who has softened his opposition to abortion but
remains perceived as the anti-abortion candidate, the analysts said.
   Frank Greer, a Washington-based media consultant to the Wilder
campaign, said: ``Until this year, we always said this is an issue
you don't want to ... pay to put on TV.''
   ``This year, people are going to be paying ... and I think that
will make it a cutting issue,'' Greer said. ``Everyone will face the
question of deciding it's an important issue in how you vote, and it
will be a determining issue, I think, in the Virginia race, in terms
of how people vote.''
   Greer commented at a luncheon sponsored by the Center for
National Policy.
   Celinda Lake, a Democratic pollster, described both Virginia and
New Jersey as ``pro-choice states.'' She said that there and
elsewhere, the Supreme Court's recent decision permitting states
more leeway in regulating abortion has presented a political
opportunity for Democratic candidates supporting abortion rights.
   In New Jersey, Rep. James Florio, a Democrat, faces Republican
Rep. James Courter.
   Lake said polls show that about 20 percent of voters are
influenced by the abortion issue, and that Democrats can be aided by
a feeling among many moderate voters ``that we shouldn't go back''
to a time when abortions were illegal.
   But Charles Cook, editor of The Cook Political Report newsletter
and a political analyst, said much of the polling showing voters in
favor of abortion are meaningless because voters will decide their
votes on other issues.
   He said it was ``very, very dangerous'' for the Democratic Party
to allow itself to become identified as the pro-abortion party, and
that candidates who push pro-abortion positions risk alienating
older Democratic voters, less educated voters and, in many states,
black voters.
   ``Where the American people are now is, they're mildly
pro-choice,'' Cook said.
   ``Any candidate that decides to go full out on abortion, one way
or the other, runs a very real risk of damaging their party base,''
Cook said. ``You risk offending your whole partisan base. ... I'd be
very leery before I crawled out on that limb.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
