<FIRST>u a AM-Nielsens     09-12 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nielsens,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBS' `Paradise' Jumps from Bottom to Top of Ratings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The CBS Western series ``Paradise'' stampeded
into the Top 10 of the Nielsen ratings with a special two-hour
Sunday premiere rounding up a number of Western stars from the past.
   The show, which stars Lee Horsley, leaped to ninth place for the
week ended Sept. 10 from a tie for 66th place the week before.
   NBC's ``Cheers'' was first and ``The Cosby Show'' was second as
ABC's ``Roseanne'' dropped from first the previous week to third.
NBC won the week for the 64th consecutive week.
   ``Paradise'' was lifted out of its usual place at the bottom of
the ratings by a special season opener featuring Hugh O'Brian
reprising his role as Wyatt Earp and Gene Barry in his former role
as Bat Masterson. Other Western actors also appeared. The show's
regular appearance Saturday will also feature several former Western
actors.
   CBS' ``Rescue: 911,'' the only other premiere of the week, was in
a three-way tie for 20th place. William Shatner is host of the show,
which features real-life emergency rescue situations.
   The week also saw Fox Broadcasting's Sunday-night ``Married ...
With Children'' return to the Top 20. It was in 17th place for the
second time this summer, the highest a Fox show has ever finished.
   Fox's ``Totally Hidden Video'' was tied for 33rd, ``America's
Most Wanted'' was tied for 42nd place and ``Open House'' was tied
for 51st place. The Fox shows had taken a slight dip the week before
after their summer surge.
   Here are the Top 10: NBC's ``Cheers,'' NBC's ``The Cosby Show,''
ABC's ``Roseanne,'' NBC's ``The Golden Girls,'' NBC's ``Dear John,''
NBC's ``Empty Nest,'' NBC's ``A Different World,'' ABC's ``The
Wonder Years,'' CBS' ``Paradise'' and CBS' ``60 Minutes.''
   The finish of ``Paradise'' and ``60 Minutes'' marked the first
time since July that CBS had a show in the Top 10. CBS's prime-time
programming Sunday was delayed because of the runover of its
coverage of the U.S. Open Tennis Tournament.
   NBC was first in the A.C. Nielsen Co. survey with an average of
11.3. ABC was second with 9.9 and CBS was third with 9.1.
   ABC had the highest rated evening news show with 8.7. CBS was
second with 8.6 and NBC was third with 8.2.
   The lowest rated network show was NBC's ``Saturday Morning
Preview.'' Here are the five bottom shows: NBC's ``Saved By the
Bell'' preview, CBS' ``Tour of Duty,'' CBS' ``3 Star Comedy
Edition,'' CBS' ``Woodstock Special'' and NBC's ``Saturday Morning
Preview.''
</TEXT>
