<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 1717EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-SovietRefugees     09-12 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Refugees,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>US To Propose Funds For 40,000 Soviet Refugees Next Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration plans to propose to
Congress that the United States next year accept 50,000 Soviet
refugees plus 6,500 more from Eastern Europe, a U.S. official and
sources in the American Jewish community said Tuesday.
   Worldwide, 125,000 refugees would be admitted, an increase of
slightly less than 8 percent from this year.
   The 50,000 Soviet refugees, at least half of whom are expected to
be Jews, are a fraction of the 250,000 Soviet citizens the State
Department estimated last week would apply for entry to the United
States in 1990.
   Of the 50,000, the sources said, 40,000 would have their
transportation and settlement costs paid by the United States. The
10,000 others would have to depend on private organizations, friends
and relatives.
   This year's combined quota for refugees from the Soviet Union and
Eastern Europe is 50,000. The new plan would allocate 50,000 slots
to the Soviet Union and set up a separate category of 6,500 for
Eastern Europe.
   Last year, as emigration from the Soviet Union began to climb,
the combined quota for the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe was
15,000.
   Jewel S. Lafontant, the State Department's refugee affairs
coordinator, is scheduled to testify to a House Judiciary
subcommittee Wednesday about the administration proposal.
   An estimated 40,000 Soviet Jews are expected to leave the Soviet
Union this year. Currently there is a backlog of an estimated 30,000
to 40,000 Jews with exit permits for Israel who have not left the
Soviet Union or are in Vienna and Rome, seeking entry to the United
States.
   Most Soviet Jews who obtain exit permits say they want to live in
Israel. All but a fraction, however, then apply for admission to the
United States once they have left their country.
   According to the Jewish sources, who demanded anonymity, the Bush
administration will also drastically revise its processing
procedures. Tentatively, refugees who apply before Oct. 1, the
beginning of the 1990 fiscal year, will be processed in Rome and
Vienna.
   Thereafter, applications will be handled by a beefed-up U.S.
Embassy staff in Moscow and by a new office to be set up outside
Washington.
   The U.S. official, who also asked not to be named, said that the
Oct. 1 cutoff date was very likely but that it might be set back a
few months.
   While the Soviets seeking admission remain in their country,
their applications would be considered both in Moscow and in the
Washington area office.
   Israel has expressed concern that Jewish refugees from the Soviet
Union were increasingly choosing to head for the United States once
out of their homeland, depriving the Jewish state of needed settlers.
   It was not clear whether the change in U.S. procedure would
increase the flow of refugees to Israel.
   The rising exodus from the Soviet Union, which results from U.S.
pressure as well as reforms undertaken by President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, poses administrative and financial problems for the Bush
administration.
   Eager to reinforce the right of Soviet citizens to travel freely,
U.S. officials stress they will keep the door to immigrants open.
But beyond the 50,000 slots allotted for the Soviet Union,
prospective Jewish emigres will be encouraged to apply for parole
status. This requires private support for the immigrants.
   Also, the sources said, in admitting 50,000 refugees from the
Soviet Union preference will be given to those with close relatives
here. But no applicant will be declared ineligble on the grounds he
has no relative here, the officials said.
   Rep. Bruce Morrison, D-Conn., who heads the House subcommittee on
immigration, said as hearings opened that the administration's
proposal provides financing for 84,000 of the 125,000 refugees
overall.
   ``Where do we get the money for the rest?'' he asked a panel of
private witnesses.
   Morrison also expressed concern about the backlog of emigres in
Rome and Vienna awaiting U.S. decisions on their eligibility to
enter the United States. He said the administration had wasted money
through this processing method and changes would have to be
considered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890912-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 2037EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-GunSafety     09-12 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gun Safety,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Creates Penalties for Unsafely Storing Guns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two lawmakers on Tuesday introduced a bill
that would allow judges to send adults to prison when children
injure or kill someone with a firearm that was not safely stored.
   ``We require childproof caps on aspirin bottles, yet we allow
loaded guns to be left in the kids' playroom,'' said Rep. David
Clarenbach. ``This bill is a small step toward sanity and a giant
leap for safety.''
   The measure would set maximum penalties of two years in prison
and $10,000 fines for adults who leave loaded guns or weapons
accessible to children under 16, resulting in an injury or death.
   The bill, endorsed by the Wisconsin arm of the National Rifle
Association and Handgun Control Inc., was touted as an effort to
reduce childhood injuries through education.
   ``This is not a gun control bill, it's a gun safety bill,''
Clarenbach said.
   He and Sen. John Plewa said the measure was in response to a
number of accidental shootings involving children this summer in
Madison and Milwaukee.
   Ir would require the Department of Natural Resources to expand
its hunter safety program to promote gun safety, public awareness
and safe use and storage of weapons. The bill also would require gun
retailers to post information about the penalties for failing to
secure loaded firearms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890912-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 2039EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TireFire     09-12 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tire Fire,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massive Tire Pile Catches Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ADOLPHE V. BERNOTAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crews finished burying an enormous pile of
burning tires under a layer of soil Tuesday after two days of work,
but the now-underground fire was expected to smolder for some time.
   State Fire Marshal William Toland said the cause of the fire
appeared suspicious.
   About 35 people living within a half-mile of the dump who were
evacuated from their homes and took shelter Sunday night at a church
were home Tuesday. Several roads in the area were reopened.
   Meanwhile, the fire means the state and a New York firm may have
to renegotiate a $1.1 million contract to get rid of the tires, a
state official said.
   The abandoned dump caught fire Sunday, the second time since
1984, sending flames 40 feet into the air and releasing billowing
smoke that could be seen 25 miles away for the next two days.
   David Tordoff of the federal Environmental Protection Agency said
EPA scientists monitored the air, soil and ground water for harmful
chemicals stemming from the fire that is expected to smolder for
some time. The 1984 fire at the dump hung on for several weeks.
   Tordoff estimated that about 2{ acres of tires stacked 30 to 40
feet high was on fire. The dump holds an estimated 1.5 millions
covering about seven acres. He said his agency earmarked up to $1
million from the hazardous waste Superfund for the effort.
   About 250 firefighters from 45 communities in three states worked
to contain the fire, using 65 trucks and 10 loaders to haul tons of
dirt onto the fire, which burned so hotly that even 2,500 gallons of
water a minute just vaporized.
   In July, the state contracted with Integrated Waste Systems Inc.
of Buffalo, N.Y., to shred the tires at the dump for shipment to
Greece to fuel a cement plant. The removal was to begin shortly.
   William Evans, of the Department of Environmental Services' Waste
Management Division, said the fire's effects would need to be
assessed and the contract possibly renegotiated.
   Charles Laubisch, a vice president of the company, walked the
site Monday with Evans. Laubisch, while not commenting on possible
renegotiations, said equipment for the cleanup is already in town.
</TEXT>
