<FIRST>r a AM-TragicReunion     09-12 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tragic Reunion,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Son Dies Day After Moving in With Long-Estranged Father</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DIXON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who dreamed for years of a reunion with
his father died in a fire at his father's home one day after moving
in.
   Perry Eade, 28, of Rockford, hadn't seen his father, Jerry Ragan
of Dixon, since he was a child.
   During seven years in the Navy, he tried several times to contact
his father without success. In a chance meeting with Eade's cousin
earlier this year, Ragan learned his son was looking for him.
   Ragan called and invited Eade to a birthday celebration Aug. 19.
   ``We had this longing feeling that he needed me, and I needed to
see him,'' Ragan said. ``I gave him a big hug and a kiss. It was
really great.''
   Eade moved into his father's home Thursday, and the two went out
to celebrate.
   Hours later, Eade died, authorities said. The fire broke out at
3:20 a.m. Friday, said Fire Lt. Neil Freil.
   Ragan said he was awakened by smoke and ran to his son's bedroom
to try to to save him. He suffered numerous burns and cuts and was
taken to Katherine Shaw Bethea Hospital in Dixon, where he was in
stable condition.
   A week before the fire, Ragan said his son had complained about
chest pains. Eade went Thursday for a checkup but never learned the
results.
   Relatives speculated that Eade may have had a heart attack while
smoking, and dropped the cigarette that started the blaze.
   A complete autopsy report will not be available for three or four
weeks.
   Eade dreamed and talked of meeting his father for years, said
family friend Goldie Stiff.
   Eade's parents had been childhood sweethearts, but his mother's
family refused to let them marry, said Ragan, 46.
   ``We sort of drifted apart, but she never denied me seeing him,''
Ragan said of his son.
   Ragan said he believes Eade didn't try to find him when he was
younger because the boy didn't want to cause problems for his
mother's husband, who helped raise him in Rockford.
</TEXT>
