<SECOND>AM-Brites,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brite and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Darla Schardein was born during a
rush to the hospital, but not in the back seat of a car. The
impatient newborn chose the cargo bay of a helicopter as her
delivery room.
   Dawn Schardein, 28, gave birth to 5-pound, 9{-ounce Darla early
Monday after sudden labor during a visit with friends in Sun City, a
remote Riverside County city served by a hospital lacking a
maternity ward.
   Her husband, Mike, 29, rushed her to Menifee Valley Medical
Center in Sun City, about 70 miles southeast of downtown Los
Angeles, where quick thinking by emergency room workers resulted in
the calling of an air ambulance to take Mrs. Schardein to San
Bernardino, about 30 miles away.
   The baby was delivered just as the helicopter set down near Saint
Bernardine Medical Center, said flight nurse Russel West.
   ``Just as we went down, we were actually landing, she was born,''
West said. ``It was a very smooth, rapid delivery ... A nice,
healthy baby girl.''
   Mother, baby and flight crew were all doing fine.
