<FIRST>r a AM-NursingHomesDeaths     09-12 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nursing Homes Deaths,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Seated in Nursing Home Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury was seated Tuesday in the
murder trial of a former nurse's aide charged with smothering five
nursing home patients with her lesbian lover.
   Although defense attorney James Piazza had sought to move the
trial out of the county due to pretrial publicity, a jury was seated
in less than two days. Opening arguments are to begin Wednesday.
   Gwendolyn Graham, 25, is charged with five counts of first-degree
murder and one count of conspiracy to commit murder in the deaths of
female patients at Alpine Manor Nursing Home in suburban Walker.
   The key witness for the prosecution will be Graham's alleged
accomplice and former live-in companion, Catherine Wood of Grand
Rapids.
   Wood also was charged with two counts of first-degree murder. But
prosecutors allowed her to plead guilty to second-degree murder and
conspiracy to commit murder in exchange for her testimony against
Graham. First-degree murder carries a mandatory life sentence
without parole, while Wood has a chance of parole in 10 years on the
lesser charges.
   At Graham's preliminary examination, Wood described how Graham,
of Tyler, Texas, chose frail patients who would not be able to
struggle and therefore would leave no signs of suffocation.
   Wood testified that Graham told her killing the patients helped
her ``relieve tension.''
   Piazza has called Wood a pathological liar.
   When the five patients died in 1987, their deaths were listed as
natural and no autopsies were performed. Police only began
investigating late last year after Wood's former husband told them
his former wife confessed to her part in the slayings.
</TEXT>
