<FIRST>u i AM-NorthernIreland     09-12 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northern Ireland,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Meets Militia Force Accused of Slayings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
praised a locally recruited army unit Tuesday and sidestepped
questions about murder charges lodged a day earlier against two of
its members.
   Mrs. Thatcher expressed confidence in the 6,500-member Ulster
Defense Regiment, which she said had ``suffered greatly'' in the
Irish Republican Army uprising against British rule.
   ``I have just been looking at the figures _ 179 UDR (members)
have been murdered in the last 20 years. They are a very, very brave
group of men,'' said the prime minister during a visit to Northern
Ireland.
   On Monday, two members of the mainly Protestant regiment and a
taxi driver were accused in court of killing a Roman Catholic,
Loughlin Maginn, 38.
   Maginn allegedly was targeted after security documents
identifying him as an IRA suspect were leaked to an outlawed
Protestant group, the Ulster Freedom Fighters.
   One of the two soldiers was also charged in the slaying of
another Catholic, Liam McKee, 36.
   During a full day of talks with businessmen, soldiers and police,
Mrs. Thatcher met an eight-man defense regiment patrol at the
Lissanelly army barracks in Omagh, in the center of the province.
   A member of the regiment who spoke to Mrs. Thatcher said she did
not mention the allegations of leaked documents, which authorities
are investigating.
   The soldier, who was not allowed to be identified, told
reporters: ``She assured us she was being supportive. We talked
about personal security. Nothing was mentioned about intelligence
files. Nothing dramatic was said.''
   Mrs. Thatcher told reporters that claims of collusion between
some soldiers and extremists were matters for the courts.
   As for the murder charges, she told reporters: ``It is not a
matter for me. If a person is charged, they are not guilty until
they are found guilty by the courts.''
   As is usual with visits by British leaders to the province,
nothing was announced about Mrs. Thatcher's trip until after she
arrived at a Royal Air Force base near Belfast.
   Roadblocks were set up wherever she went, and police
sharpshooters were on rooftops.
   The security measures have been set up to prevent attacks by the
mainly Catholic IRA, which is fighting to unite the
Protestant-dominated province with the Catholic majority Irish
Republic.
