<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 1754EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Pentagon-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru   09-12 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0711,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon: U.S. Training Role Expanded</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to restore first name and title to Williams.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Drugs, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon said Tuesday the United States is
prepared ``to expand the training role'' of U.S. troops sent to
assist the Andean drug battle but insisted those forces will not
take part in any local anti-drug operations.
   Giving the latest update on the U.S. effort to battle the
international drug war, Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams also
defended the Defense Department against criticism from the chief of
Colombia's national police force, who complained the Pentagon is
sending the wrong equipment for the fight.
   ``There's a great deal more to go,'' said Williams, noting that
some $10.4 million in equipment has been sent to Columbia as part of
President Bush's emergency $65 million aid package to that nation.
   Williams said there are ``less than 50'' U.S. military officers
in Colombia, Peru and Bolivia, but he refused to specify where their
locations.
   Controversy arose about the role of U.S. troops in the
president's new strategy following a published report that Bush had
signed a secret directive authorizing U.S. Special Forces to
accompany local forces on some patrols.
   Asked to clarify the role of U.S. advisers in the current
situation, Williams stressed _ as Bush and White House officials
have done as well _ that the troops are not there to enter combat
but to provide training, equipment and support for the local police
and military in the anti-narcotics fight.
   ``The critical point to bear in mind _ no U.S. forces, no U.S.
military personnel will accompany host government forces on actual
field operations,'' Williams said. ``But we are prepared to expand
the training role. ... It's clearly an expansion of our training
role.''
   Although Williams refused to discuss the details of Bush's secret
directive, he said U.S. forces now will be allowed to go ``beyond
the boundaries of secured garrison training areas'' in their
training missions.
   He was also asled about published comments by Colombia's Maj.
Gen. Gomez Padilla that the U.S. equipment being sent to that nation
was more suitable for conventional warfare than operations against
narcotic traffickers.
   ``This is not something where ... you fill out your Eastern
Mountains Sports catalog and mail it in. It's not that simple,''
Williams said.
   He said the items sent to Colombia have been derived as ``the
result of continuing discussions between the United States and the
Colombians. It's their request, and we match it with what we can
provide.''
   The spokesman noted that under the emergency program, the
Pentagon must send materiel gleaned from existing stocks and cannot
purchase new items.
   So far, he said, that aid has included 15 aircraft, 23 jeeps and
ambulances, medical supplies, bullet-proof vests, radios, machine
guns and grenade launchers
   The Colombian police have recieved 5 UH-1 ``Huey'' helicopters,
small arms, machine guns, grenade launchers and ammunition. The
Colombian army has been sent vehicles, radios, medical equipment,
grenade launchers and ammunition while the air force has been sent
two C-130 transport planes and spare parts, eight OA-37
reconnaisance jets and spare parts, he said.
   The judiciary has been provided 500 bullet-proof vests, Williams
said.
   ``We are undergoing extensive and continuing negotiations with
the government of Colombia, both civil and military officials, to
develop the maximum amount of benefit of our available military
equipment,'' Williams said. ``It may not be a perfect match, but the
equipment and its schedule has received a great deal of attention at
the Pentagon.''
   The spokesman said that the Pentagon believes ``that the aid that
we have offered is appropriate to the circumstance.''
</TEXT>
