<FIRST>r w AM-DisasterRelief 320   09-12 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disaster Relief, 320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeutter Agrees to Examine Disaster Payment Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Name Cotton Fanning is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter agreed
Tuesday to consider boosting disaster payments to farmers who
harvested a second crop after severe weather destroyed their winter
wheat and cotton.
   Farm state lawmakers contend the Agriculture Department's formula
for calculating relief payments is inflexible and unfair to farmers
who planted a replacement crop after drought, hail and extreme cold
battered the Great Plains earlier this year.
   Under the current formula, some farmers who ``did nothing'' after
the drought are better off than those who planted a second crop,
said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas.
   ``You can't treat the guys who are trying to help themselves
worse than the guys who are waiting around for the government to
help them,'' Gramm said.
   Gramm and Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole of Kansas predicted
USDA would modify its second crop formula, under which 75 percent of
the gross value of a second crop would be deducted when calculating
disaster payments for losses on the first crop.
   ``That's tantamount to saying the cost of production was 25
percent,'' said Cotton Fanning, executive assistant at the High
Plains Cotton Growers Inc. in Lubbock, Texas.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, said he was encouraged by Yeutter's
response to lawmakers' concerns during a meeting Tuesday in Dole's
office.
   ``The secretary recognized that changes are needed, although he
stopped short of a firm commitment,'' Bentsen said after the session.
   Gramm, who also attended the meeting, said the USDA's forumula is
``totally arbitrary'' and that farmers' costs vary. He said he asked
Yeutter to ``come up with a practical way of calculating the real
costs.''
   Bentsen has proposed that only the net value of the second crop
be deducted.
   Yeutter spokeswoman Kelly Shipp said the secretary would respond
after evaluating the suggestions.
</TEXT>
