<FIRST>u i AM-SouthAfrica     09-12 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0709</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Not to Block Protest March Led by Tutu</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a highly unusual move, the
government Tuesday said it would allow a mass march condemning
alleged brutality by police riot squads. Protest marches in South
Africa normally are outlawed.
   Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu and other organizers of
Wednesday's demonstration had refused to seek authorization from the
government. But Acting President F.W. de Klerk told reporters the
protest would be allowed nonetheless because of assurances that it
would be peaceful.
   ``I hope tomorrow will prove that a new spirit can arise in our
beautiful country, a spirit in which all Christians and all people
who say that they believe in peace will reach out and really start
talking to each other,'' de Klerk said.
   The march through downtown Cape Town is to coincide with the
opening of Parliament, where the National Party-controlled electoral
college is expected to elect de Klerk to a five-year term Thursday.
He has offered to negotiate a new constitution that would give some
form of political rights to the now-voteless black majority.
   Tutu and other activists allege that at least 23 people in Cape
Town's black and mixed-race townships were killed on the night of
the Sept. 6 parliamentary elections by police. Police say 15 people
were killed, 10 in black-on-black faction fighting.
   De Klerk said police were forced to act because militants were
forcefully preventing people from voting. He said ``remedial steps''
would be taken on any policemen found to have used excessive force.
   ``This is not the time to aggravate the differences that exist in
our society,'' said de Klerk. ``This is the time for finding common
ground.''
   One government source, speaking on condition of anonymity,
indicated the decision to allow the march came after an appeal from
officials of the white Dutch Reformed Church, who contacted the
government after meeting Tutu and other protest leaders.
   Tutu is to be joined at the head of the march by Cape Town's
white mayor, Gordon Oliver.
   They and two other activists issued a statement inviting all Cape
Town residents to join in a ``dignified, peaceful procession ...
under the theme `Peace in Our City.'''
   The statement said the marchers would demand removal of riot
police from the townships, a halt to detentions, release of police
records to lawyers and negotiations aimed at ending apartheid.
   The government announced Tuesday that Maj. Gen. Jaap Joubert, a
senior police investigator, had been appointed to lead a probe into
the allegations of police violence.
   However, Lt. Gregory Rockman, a mixed-race policeman who has
created a furor by accusing riot squad members of brutality, said he
was not satisfied and proposed a judge be appointed to oversee a
public inquiry.
   ``This just doesn't satisfy me,'' Rockman said of Joubert's
appointment. ``They are just trying to cool us off.''
   Rockman spoke after he and about 40 other mixed-race officers met
with Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok and police commanders from
the Cape Town area, where riot squads and protesters have clashed
almost daily since early August.
   Tutu, among others, has hailed Rockman as a hero for going public
with his allegations that police behaved like ``wild dogs'' when
they beat schoolchildren and bystanders during an anti-election
protest on Sept. 5.
   The top-ranking mixed-race policeman, Col. John Manuel, was among
those who met with Vlok. Afterward, Manuel said Rockman has ``full
support from his colleagues and from me.''
   In another development, a former newspaper photographer told a
news conference he had been a police spy for the past two years,
providing information about anti-apartheid journalists and
organizations.
   Gregory Flatt, 21, said he was coerced into becoming an informer
while in detention in early 1987.
   He said he decided to confess his role because of the election
night violence and because he was impressed by Rockman's courage.
Both Flatt and Rockman are from the mixed-race township of
Mitchell's Plain.
   Flatt formerly worked for South, an anti-apartheid weekly
newspaper published in Cape Town.
   ``I betrayed the cause of my people and helped to maintain an
unjust system,'' Flatt said.
</TEXT>
