<FIRST>r i AM-EasternEurope-Glance     09-12 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern Europe-Glance,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Developments in Eastern Bloc</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland Bjt, AM-Refugees Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of developments Tuesday in Eastern Europe:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>POLAND</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Polish Parliament overwhelmingly approved the first Cabinet
in the East bloc not led by Communists, but reserved key ministries
controlling defense and police for the Communists.
   The new Cabinet includes Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki of
Solidarity, 11 Solidarity members, and a foreign minister
independent but sympathetic to Solidarity. The Communists have four
seats, and two parties aligned with Solidarity hold seven seats.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EAST GERMAN REFUGEES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of East Germans crowded refugee camps in West Germany
after crossing the border from Hungary. Bavarian border police said
over 10,000 had arrived in the past two days.
   In the border city of Passau, the new arrivals were greeted with
offers of jobs and shelter. Tent camps and a reception area were set
up for the emigres.
   East Germans camping outside the West German Embassy in Prague,
Czechoslovakia, gave up their vigil after East German authorities
promised they would not be punished if they returned home.
   Officials said thousands more East Germans were arriving in
Hungary, which opened its doors to the West Sunday.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EAST GERMANY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany issued a sharp formal protest to Hungary for
permitting the exodus and demanded the flood be stopped. The state
ADN news agency also said Soviet Politburo hard-liner Yegor Ligachev
and East German government officials issued a joint statement
harshly criticizing West Germany.
   Neues Deutschland, the Communist Party's official newspaper,
called the exodus a ``provocation organized at high levels,'' and an
``illegal action to lure away East German citizens in Hungary.''
   The Communist Party youth newspaper Junge Welt called the exodus
an ``anti-socialist action ... by Bonn.''
   Sources said many requests for tourist visas for trips to Hungary
are being refused, indicating that East Berlin has begun clamping
down.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SOVIET REACTION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   In Moscow, Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov,
indicating Soviet uneasiness over the exodus, said Hungary had taken
``an unusual and unexpected step'' in allowing Germans to cross the
border.
</TEXT>
