<FIRST>r w AM-OffshoreDrilling     09-12 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Offshore Drilling,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Backers Defend Expansion of Outer Shelf Oil Drilling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Backers of expanded drilling for oil on the
outer continental shelf contended Tuesday that the huge spill from
the Exxon Valdez tanker is impossible with an offshore rig.
   A greater risk comes from foreign tankers carrying foreign oil,
representatives of the petroleum industry and Interior Department
told a House Merchant Marine and Fisheries subcommittee.
   ``OCS (outer continental shelf) oil and gas development is
inherently safer,'' than importing oil on tankers, said Barry A.
Williamson, director of the Minerals Management Service at the
Interior Department. He noted that two of three oil spills in U.S.
waterways shortly after the March 24 Exxon Valdez accident involved
foreign vessels.
   ``Every barrel we don't produce from OCS is another barrel'' that
must be imported, he added.
   ``If we don't move forward with a domestic OCS program, our
country is going to suffer in the future,'' said Rep. Jack Fields,
R-Texas.
   The National Audubon Society contended, however, that the
pollution from offshore rigs consists of more than the spillage.
``Contrary to popular thinking, a significant amount of OCS oil and
gas activities takes place on coastal landfall areas and in
nearshore waters,'' said Dorene Bolze, an analyst for the group.
   For example, there are the residues of drilling _ muds and
cuttings _ and the liquids brought to the floor by drilling, all of
which may contain contaminants, including toxic materials.
   Additionally, there is the problem of air and noise pollution,
spills from ships used to transport the oil, and damage to wetlands
from pollution, pipeline digging and other construction, the group
says.
   Most of the oil produced in the Gulf of Mexico is brought to land
by pipeline.
   As a result of major offshore oil rig disasters in 1969 and 1970
_ one off Santa Barbara, Calif., and two involving fires in the Gulf
of Mexico _ federal regulation of the industry intensified.
   There have been no well blowouts spilling more than 200 barrels
into federal waters since 1970, according to Interior Department
figures cited in the hearing.
   A 1985 report by the National Academy of Sciences, quoted freely
in the hearing, estimated that the oil spilled from offshore oil
production accounted for only 2 percent of the total marine oil
spillage worldwide.
   The Valdez accident, by contrast, resulted in the release of more
than 250,000 barrels, or 11 million gallons.
   Drilling advocates say that kind of release is impossible not
only because of the regulations and safety measures that have been
put in place, but also because the offshore wells produce oil at
only eight barrels an hour.
   Tuesday's hearing of the Panama Canal and Outer Continental Shelf
subcommittee was not to consider any legislation, but occurred
against a backdrop of responses to the Valdez incident. Several
subcommittees were making last-minute adjustments to oil spill
cleanup legislation resulting from the Valdez accident before
committee and House action later this week.
   Most outer continental shelf production is in the Gulf of Mexico
and Pacific Ocean off California. An administration task force is
studying some of the more controversial lease sales off Florida and
the Gulf coast of Florida and is expected to make recommendations to
President Bush in December.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
