<FIRST>u i AM-TyphoonSarah     09-12 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Typhoon Sarah,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Typhoon Lashes Taiwan, 20 Dead or Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Typhoon Sarah lashed Taiwan with heavy
rains and high winds for a second day on Tuesday, killing at least
11 people and leaving nine missing, officials said.
   They said the typhoon set off landslides, immobilized
transportation, flooded crops and broke a Panamanian freighter in
two.
   The 12,000-ton Lung Hao with 26 Turkish and Indian crew broke
apart Monday off Hualien, 110 miles southeast of Taipei, and
rescuers still are looking for five crew members believed stranded
on the vessel.
   Four sailors swam ashore Monday and 17 were rescued Tuesday.
   Hualien was the hardest-hit area, with four people reported dead.
   An Australian teacher, Jonathan B. Watts, 26, died Monday when
swept into the sea while touring the harbor there with other
instructors from a nearby English-language center, police said.
   In addition, a woman was electrocuted, a boy drowned in
floodwaters and a man was hit by falling rocks.
   Police said four people were killed in southern Pingtung county
when strong winds made them lose control of their car.
   Officers said three people died elsewhere in Taiwan and four were
missing.
   They said the typhoon, sitting nearly 50 miles off eastern
Taipei, moved northward at 9 mph in a sweep across the island, but
weathermen said its peak winds were down from 108 mph to 72 mph.
   In Manila, government and Red Cross officials said Sarah caused
floods and landslides in the northern Philippines Sunday and Monday,
leaving 21 people dead and up to 70,000 homeless.
</TEXT>
