<FIRST>u w AM-Budget-PostOffice     09-12 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget-Post Office,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Votes To Remove Postal Receipts From Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House voted Tuesday to reverse a 1985
Reagan administration decision to include the U.S. Postal Service's
revenues and expenditures in the federal budget, a move designed in
part to stave off a rate increase.
   The bill, approved 405-11, would insulate the Postal Service from
deficit-reduction efforts, giving it the same ``off-budget'' status
accorded Social Security.
   It is designed ``to enable the Postal Service to operate in a
more businesslike manner and to relieve some of the pressure for
increased postal rates,'' a spokesman for the Post Office and Civil
Service Committee said. The bill now goes to the Senate.
   In 1985, Budget Director David Stockman included Postal Service
receipts and expenditures in the next year's federal budget _ a
practice that continues, said Rep. William D. Ford, D-Mich., the
committee chairman.
   ``Those receipts and disbursements now, at least on paper, affect
the federal deficit,'' Ford said.
   When Congress ordered government agencies to reduce spending in
1987, the Postal Service had to absorb a $1.2 billion cut, he said.
As a result, more than 700 post office construction projects were
delayed or cancelled, offices were closed on Saturdays, window hours
were reduced and Sunday mail processing was curtailed.
   ``This year, some budgeteers want to take another bite out of the
Postal Service,'' Ford said in a floor speech. The Bush
administration contends that a budget agreement with congressional
leaders reached earlier this year requires shifting $400 million in
postal revenues to the Treasury, he said.
   Ford said his committee rejects the idea. ``It's not good policy
and it will accelerate the next rate increase,'' he said.
   Most of the Postal Service's 1990 budget will be generated by the
mail system, he said.
   ``Today, no money is appropriated (from the federal treasury) to
pay for the costs of delivering the mail,'' Ford said. ``Those costs
are paid by postal ratepayers. And the Postal Service, as required
by law, is breaking even over the long haul.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
