<FIRST>r w AM-JeffersonLecturer     09-12 0123</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jefferson Lecturer,110</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scholar on Mideast Named 1990 Jefferson Lecturer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bernard Lewis, a Middle Eastern scholar and
professor emeritus at Princeton University, will give the 1990
Jefferson Lecture, the National Endowment for the Humanities
announced Tuesday.
   Lewis is the author of more than 20 books on Middle Eastern
history and has been a co-editor of The Encyclopedia of Islam.
   He receives a $10,000 stipend for the lecture, which is to be
delivered in Washington next May 2, the organization's statement
said.
   The National Endowment for the Humanities is a federal agency
promoting research and education in the humanities. Lewis is the
19th person to be named a Jefferson lecturer by the agency. The 1989
lecturer was novelist Walker Percy.
</TEXT>
