<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 2106EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-MiddleEast     09-12 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Middle East,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>UN Cites Occupied Territories, Lebanon as Biggest Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
on Tuesday painted a bleak picture of events in the Israeli-occupied
territories and Lebanon, saying they were his biggest problems.
   ``The situation in the Middle East remains a profound and intense
concern,'' he wrote in his annual report, ``not only because of the
political principles at stake, but also because of the widespread
human suffering caused by failure to resolve those issues.''
   Hopes for early progress in the peace process ``have sadly given
way to mistrust and doubt among the parties concerned,'' he said.
   Perez de Cuellar referred to a November resolution by the
Palestinian National Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile, that
implicitly recognized Israel's right to exist and renounced
terrorism.
   But efforts to promote a dialogue between Israelis and
Palestinians have been unsuccessful, the secretary-general said. He
said his own attempts to start negotiations have been
``frustratingly inconclusive.''
   Meanwhile, he said, the situation in the Israeli-occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip grows steadily worse.
   At least 567 Palestinians have been killed by Israelis in the
21-month-old uprising against Israeli rule of the territories. Forty
Israelis also have been killed.
   He said the Security Council repeatedly has called on Israel to
observe international conventions on protecting civilians in time of
war. Despite appeals by the international community, however,
widespread violation of human rights persist, he said.
   Perez de Cuellar called for negotiations, ``taking fully into
account the legitimate rights of the Palestinian people, including
those of self-determination.
   ``The longer such a process is delayed,'' Perez de Cuellar said,
``the greater will be the difficulties in intiating it and the more
explosive the situation can become.''
   The secretary-general also said the world is appalled by the
steady disintegration of government and society in Lebanon and by
the unprecedented violence in that country's 14-year-old civil war.
   On Aug. 15, the secretary-general requested an urgent meeting of
the Security Council on Lebanon. The Council appealed to the
Christians and Syrian-Moslem alliance to lay down their weapons.
   The secretary-general said he was pursuing contacts in liaison
with a tripartite Arab League committee to achieve a cease-fire.
   Perez de Cuellar said the international community bears a
responsibility to ensure restoration of the unity, sovereignty,
territorial integrity and independence of Lebanon, as a member state
of the United Nations.
   At least 847 people have died and 2,528 have been wounded since
March 8, when the most recent fighting in the sectarian civil war
broke out between Christian army units under Gen. Michel Aoun and
Syrian troops based in Lebanon.
   Syrian troops entered Lebanon in 1976 on an Arab League
peacekeeping mandate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
