<FIRST>u w AM-Yeltsin 1stLd-Writethru a0637 09-12 0969</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yeltsin, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0637,870</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeltsin Urges U.S. Help to Salvage Perestroika</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 14 grafs new with details of Yeltsin meeting, picking up
graf 4 pvs: ``Yelstin's White;'' minor editing and trimming.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet political maverick Boris N. Yeltsin met
briefly with President Bush on Tuesday and urged the administration
and U.S. business executives to help salvage the political and
economic reforms being pushed by Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   Bush ``emphasized that the American people share his hope for the
success of the reform movement in the Soviet Union,'' the White
House said in a short statement after the 15-minute meeting.
   Bush told Yeltsin his administration enjoys a ``very positive
relationship'' with Gorbachev and reiterated support for
perestroika, or the restructuring of Soviet economic and political
life, the White House said.
   The 58-year-old Yeltsin, ousted as Moscow's Communist Party chief
in late 1987 and then dumped from the ruling Politburo, was elected
to parliament with overwhelming popular support in a contested
election. He arrived in the United States on a private tour Saturday.
   After meeting for nearly an hour with Secretary of State James A.
Baker III, Yeltsin said he did not expect the United States to loan
money to the Kremlin, but that he wanted American companies to
invest in the Soviet Union.
   In a statement, the State Department said that Yeltsin ``offered
his views on the kinds of changes that are taking place in the
Soviet Union, his assessment of where the reform process stood, and
of what would be needed for the reform process to move forward and
succeed. Examples:
   _ ``Acceptance of existence of private property.
   _``Importance of a mixed economy.
   _``Enticing external investment in the Soviet Union.
   ``Mr. Yelstin made it very clear he would welcome U.S. support
for perestroika. He does not want and is not seeking American
grants. Rather he sees great virtue in private American investment
in the Soviet Union.''
   Yeltsin, rushing from his meeting to catch an airplane to
Chicago, told reporters that ``in my discussion with the president
and vice president, I made a list of 10 issues that could be
discussed between us that could serve rescue perestroika.''
   He declined to give specifics, but said ``the president supported
the proposals that I suggested.''
   The State Department said Baker told Yeltsin that ``in order to
make the Soviet Union an attractive place for Americans to invest,
the Soviet Union needs to address price reform and convertibility of
the ruble.''
   The ruble, the Soviet currency, is not generally traded on world
currency exchanges. A dollar buys many more rubles on the black
market than it does in official transactions in Soviet state banks,
a sign of an ailing economy. The Soviet government is sponsoring a
world-wide competition among economists with a $25,000 prize for the
best plan to make the ruble convertible _ freely traded for dollars,
marks, francs and other currencies.
   Yeltsin's low-key White House reception reflected Bush's desire
to avoid offending Gorbachev. Presidential spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said the president didn't want to ``provide a platform for
dissent.''
   In a speech at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore before going
to Washington, Yeltsin said Gorbachev had made mistakes in his
policy of social and economic reforms.
   ``The situation in our country, after 4{ years of perestroika, is
very dangerous. We have to combine our efforts to rescue
perestroika, which is in a super-critical situation today,'' Yeltsin
said, but he did not spell out what he thinks the Kremlin needs from
Washington.
   In Moscow, Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov
said Yeltsin's views were his own and not necessarily the
government's.
   Yeltsin's White House visit included a private meeting with
National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft, during which Bush and
Vice President Dan Quayle dropped by, Fitzwater said.
   Defending a White House decision to bar the media and to limit
Yeltsin's time with the president, Fitzwater said ``we don't want to
do anything to foster internal conflict that might be associated
with this trip.''
   ``We view him as one of the first elected representatives in the
Soviet Union, an important spokesman for his point of view,''
Fitzwater said about Yeltsin.
   Yeltsin, a critic of Gorbachev, has emerged as the leader of a
small but vocal group of reformers within the newly constituted
Soviet parliament.
   The group, which includes Nobel Prize winner Andrei D. Sakharov,
has stopped short of illegally forming a separate party or a
splinter group within the Communist Party but is widely viewed as an
opposition movement.
   ``Perestroika should not have been conducted on such a broad
front. We should have concentrated ourselves on such things as
consumer goods and food,'' Yeltsin said in Baltimore, arguing that
would have improved Soviet life and won greater support.
   Yeltsin told reporters in Baltimore that he approved of the
exodus of thousands of East Germans through Hungary to West Germany,
where they have been granted citizenship.
   ``It should be regulated by international agreements stating that
people have the right to live where they want,'' Yeltsin said.
   He said he was not opposed to unification of Germany, but said it
was not practical now. Leaders of communist East Germany oppose
unification.
   Gorbachev could face an upheaval from below if Soviet life is not
improved within a year, Yeltsin said, repeating past assertions.
   In Washington, Yeltsin also met with nine senators in the office
of Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., but failed to appear at a luncheon
where he was to address about 50 people including Sen. Barbara
Mikulski, D-Md., Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md., and former national
security adviser Zbigniew Brzezinski.
   Yeltsin, whose visit was organized by the Esalen Institute
Soviet-American Exchange Program, is receiving $25,000 per speech.
The money will pay for the trip and contribute to AIDS research in
the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
