<FIRST>r a AM-List-Cooper     09-12 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-List-Cooper,0387</SECOND>
<UNK>Investigator Discounts Arrestee as Skyjacker `D.B. Cooper'</UNK>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators have rejected the theory that
John E. List, accused of killing his family in 1971, is the
mysterious skyjacker ``D.B. Cooper.''
   A man who bought a ticket in the name Dan Cooper parachuted from
a Boeing 727 over southwest Washington state on Thanksgiving eve 15
days after the killings in Westfield, N.J.
   ``Cooper'' commandeered the Northwest Airlines flight by
threatening to detonate a bomb, and took $200,000 ransom for the
passengers and most of the crew. He has never been located and his
body was never found.
   From the time of the hijacking, some investigators have
speculated that List was Cooper, because the men's descriptions are
similar and because of List's disappearance after the New Jersey
killings.
   The story surfaced anew after a man police said was List was
arrested June 1 in Richmond, Va.
   ``There's nothing to indicate to us to that he's D.B. Cooper,''
said Capt. Frank Marranca, head of the homicide squad at the Union
County prosecutor's office. The FBI has reached a similar
conclusion, he said.
   There are a ``couple of other facts that would tend to not put
him as D.B. Cooper,'' said Marranca, who refused to reveal the
evidence, saying it would be relevant to List's trial.
   Jon Eyer, FBI assistant agent in charge in Seattle, said there is
nothing at this point that conclusively points to List being Cooper
or not being Cooper.
   He said the FBI has been investigating ``a whole slew of leads
and circumstances'' in the case, but they're not focusing
necessarily on List and they never were. He's only one of many
possibilities, Eyer said.
   Marranca said investigation showed List had no paratroop
experience in service during World War II and the Korean War,
Marranca said.
   No date has been set for the trial, which could lay the issue to
rest once and for all if prosecutors prove List's whereabouts two
weeks after the killings.
   List's wife, three children and mother were found murdered in
their home in December 1971.
   A man who identified himself as Robert B. Clark was arrested in
Richmond and accused of being List following a tip by the viewer of
a crime recreation television program.
</TEXT>
