<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-12 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow in Colorado; Summer in The Southwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Unseasonably cool air hovered over the nation's midsection
Tuesday, producing afternoon temperatures as much as 30 degrees
below normal in some areas and dumping up to 8 inches of snow in
Colorado.
   Summer continued in the Southwest, however, with temperatures
rising into the lower 90s.
   Scattered thunderstorms developed from the southern Appalachians
across the central Gulf Coast states to the Texas coast. Florida
also had scattered thunderstorms.
   Thunderstorms over the southern High Plains brought 2.78 inches
of rain to Canyon, Texas, flooding streets and stalling cars
throughout the city. Nickel-sized hail fell in Panhandle, Texas.
   Snow fell in much of the Denver area, with up to an inch in
northern and western sections. Up to 8 inches was reported in the
foothills west of Fort Collins, Colo., and Sidney, Neb., got a
dusting of snow.
   Afternoon temperatures were in the 30s over parts of southwest
Nebraska, northeast Colorado and southeast Wyoming. Much of Kansas
had readings in the 40s. The Kansas City, Mo., area was around 50
degrees, about 30 degrees below normal for this time of the year.
   It was warmer west of the Rockies, with Grand Junction, Colo.,
reporting 64 degrees and Gunnison, Colo., 59 degrees.
   Temperatures reached the 70s across the Pacific Northwest and in
the mid to upper 90s over the desert Southwest and in southern Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 34
degrees at Denver and Cheyenne, Wyo., to 96 degrees at Palm Springs,
Calif., as well as Brownsville, Harlingen, Beeville and Kingsville,
Texas.
   The nation's low Tuesday was 13 degrees at West Yellowstone, Mont.
   Wednesday's forecast called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the middle and south Atlantic Coast across the
Tennessee Valley and Gulf Coast states to the southern Plains; and
rain from Oklahoma across the middle Mississippi and Ohio valleys to
the southern Great Lakes.
   Highs were expected in the 50s and 60s from the central Rockies
across the Great Plains states and the upper Mississippi Valley to
the Great Lakes region; 80s and 90s from the middle and south
Atlantic coastal states across the Tennessee Valley and Gulf Coast
states to most of Texas; 80s and 90s over the Pacific Northwest and
interior valleys of California; near 100 degrees in the desert
Southwest; and in the 70s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
