<FIRST>u a AM-DrugWars-Glance     09-12 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Wars-Glance,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summary of Developments in Drug Wars</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Drugs Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of developments Tuesday on the drug-fighting
front:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>BUSH-SCHOOLCHILDREN</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   In an address televised to schools, President Bush told students
to refuse drugs and urged them to help others stay away from
narcotics.
   ``Saying `no' won't make you a nerd. It won't make you a loser.
In fact, it will make you more friends than drugs ever will,'' Bush
said.
   Bush added, ``I'm asking you to find someone who needs you. And
offer to help. I'll say it again: If you're not in trouble, help
someone who is.''
   Many students who watched Bush's speech wondered if anything the
president said would make a difference.
   ``I don't think what he said is going to stop it. It needs a lot
more to stop it,'' said 10-year old Amos Dunn, a student at an
inner-city Boston elementary school.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CONGRESS-DRUGS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., proposed legislation to boost
anti-drug spending to $10.1 billion, $2.2 billion more than Bush's
program.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the proposal
``throws money at the problem rather than providing a plan.''
Administration officials said they would recommend Bush veto the
Democratic plan.
   Democrats said they would raise the extra money for law
enforcement, education, and prevention and treatment programs
through across-the-board cuts in hundreds of federal programs.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>STATE-LOCAL REACTION to BUSH PLAN</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   State and municipal officials told the Senate Judiciary Committee
that aid to state and local governments envisioned under Bush's drug
strategy would be a fraction of what already is being spent. Several
expressed dismay at contemplated cuts in existing programs to pay
for the new initiative.
   ``It is inconceivable that we would go out to fight a war with $8
billion to solve a problem that we conservatively estimate at $120
billion,'' said John Gustafson, president of the National
Association of State Alcohol and Drug Abuse Directors.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MILITARY-DRUGS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon said the U.S. is prepared ``to expand the training
role'' of U.S. troops sent to assist the Andean drug battle but
insisted those forces will not take part in any local anti-drug
operations.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>COLOMBIA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   A judge in Barranquilla, Colombia, said he had released suspected
drug traffickers Bernardo Londono Quintero and Alberto Orlandez
Gamboa. The government had said the two could be extradited to the
United States, but the judge said he released them for lack of
evidence.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DRUG TRIAL</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   A jury was chosen in Jacksonville, Fla., to hear the cocaine
conspiracy case against five Americans accused of helping Colombian
drug lord Carlos Lehder Rivas create a smuggling ring. Opening
arguments in the trial were scheduled for Wednesday morning.
</TEXT>
