<DOCNO> AP890912-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 1935EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-O'HareCrash-Landing     09-12 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-O'Hare Crash-Landing,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jetliner Skids off O'Hare Runway, No Injuries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Airlines jetliner's nose gear
collapsed on landing at O'Hare International Airport on Tuesday,
sending the craft skidding off the runway, officials said.
   No one was injured in the crash-landing, according to early
reports, but airport police said one passenger was given
precautionary treatment for a pre-existing medical problem.
   The jetliner was American Airlines Flight 1271, which was bound
for Chicago from Rochester, N.Y., said Federal Aviation
Administration spokesman Mort Edelstein. He said the plane was a
two-engine MD-80 and was carrying 115 passengers and crew members.
   ``The pilot reported hydraulic system problems as he was coming
in on approach,'' Edelstein said. ``He was asked if he wanted
emergency vehicles on standby, and he said `yes.'''
   Edelstein said the nose gear collapsed as the plane touched down
at 5:46 CDT. ``It went off the runway and kept on skidding,'' he
said.
   There was no fire in the crash landing, but the crew deployed the
emergency chutes so passengers could make a quick exit from the
crippled plane, authorities said.
   Officer Mal Gunther of the O'Hare police unit said the one
passenger requiring treatment suffered hyperventilation.
   The MD-80 is a Stage 3 jetliner which is essentially a DC-9
redesigned for noise reduction, Edelstein said.
</TEXT>
