<DOCNO> AP890912-0188 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 1941EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-AdamsMuseum     09-12 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Adams Museum,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Creative Photography Museum Named For Ansel Adams</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new museum named for the late photographer
Ansel Adams opens Sunday, and promises to become one of the world's
leading centers for creative photography, supporters said during a
preview Tuesday.
   ``If he were here right now, I think he would be absolutely
elated,'' said Ron Egherman, executive director of the Ansel Adams
Center.
   Adams, whose black-and-white landscapes influenced generations of
photographers and helped elevate the medium to the level of art,
died five years ago.
   ``He would be thrilled, not only at the fact that his long-term
dream of always supporting fine-arts photography was achieved, but
also to have his work shown in contrast to the work of other
artists,'' Egherman said.
   One of the $1 million museum's five galleries will be devoted to
Adams. The other galleries will exhibit works by local
photographers, other contemporary artists, traditional and
historical photographers and ``people who are challenging the
frontiers of what is photography, what is art,'' Egherman said.
   The museum has 6,000 square feet of exhibition space, additional
space for workshops and offices for publishing works by contemporary
photographers, and room for expansion. The Adams Center expects
75,000 to 100,000 visitors its first year, Egherman said.
   The museum is across the street from the Moscone Convention
Center, in an area that is expected to eventually include the San
Francisco Museum of Modern Art, a visual arts center, a theater and
a cinema arts complex.
   The Adams Center is run by The Friends of Photography, a
10,000-member group started 22 years ago by Adams and other top
photographers.
   The Friends' original museum was in Carmel, but the group,
seeking a larger space and hoping to attract more attention, decided
several years ago to move it to San Francisco, Adams' birthplace.
   Most of the cost of building the Adams Center came from member
donations. A black-tie fund raiser Friday will be attended by Adams'
widow, Virginia, historian-photographer Beaumont Newhall and other
leading photographers.
   Newhall, former curator of photography at New York's Museum of
Modern Art and a founding member of the Friends, said the Adams
Center should soon become a leading center for photography, along
with the George Eastman House in Rochester, N.Y., and New York's
International Center of Photography.
   Newhall said the Adams Center also will add to the growing
acceptance of photography as an art form.
   ``There is a minority who won't accept photography as an art
form, but there's been a great acceptance by curators and the
public,'' he said. ``This center will only increase that perception.
It's a tremendous memorial to a man who meant so much to us, and a
great new center for photography.''

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890912-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 1951EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-SovietRefugees     09-12 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet Refugees,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0703 with changed keyword line to avoid duplicating
keyword line of a0664</HEAD>
<HEAD>US To Propose Funds For 40,000 Soviet Refugees Next Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration plans to propose to
Congress that the United States next year accept 50,000 Soviet
refugees plus 6,500 more from Eastern Europe, a U.S. official and
sources in the American Jewish community said Tuesday.
   Worldwide, 125,000 refugees would be admitted, an increase of
slightly less than 8 percent from this year.
   The 50,000 Soviet refugees, at least half of whom are expected to
be Jews, are a fraction of the 250,000 Soviet citizens the State
Department estimated last week would apply for entry to the United
States in 1990.
   Of the 50,000, the sources said, 40,000 would have their
transportation and settlement costs paid by the United States. The
10,000 others would have to depend on private organizations, friends
and relatives.
   This year's combined quota for refugees from the Soviet Union and
Eastern Europe is 50,000. The new plan would allocate 50,000 slots
to the Soviet Union and set up a separate category of 6,500 for
Eastern Europe.
   Last year, as emigration from the Soviet Union began to climb,
the combined quota for the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe was
15,000.
   Jewel S. Lafontant, the State Department's refugee affairs
coordinator, is scheduled to testify to a House Judiciary
subcommittee Wednesday about the administration proposal.
   An estimated 40,000 Soviet Jews are expected to leave the Soviet
Union this year. Currently there is a backlog of an estimated 30,000
to 40,000 Jews with exit permits for Israel who have not left the
Soviet Union or are in Vienna and Rome, seeking entry to the United
States.
   Most Soviet Jews who obtain exit permits say they want to live in
Israel. All but a fraction, however, then apply for admission to the
United States once they have left their country.
   According to the Jewish sources, who demanded anonymity, the Bush
administration will also drastically revise its processing
procedures. Tentatively, refugees who apply before Oct. 1, the
beginning of the 1990 fiscal year, will be processed in Rome and
Vienna.
   Thereafter, applications will be handled by a beefed-up U.S.
Embassy staff in Moscow and by a new office to be set up outside
Washington.
   The U.S. official, who also asked not to be named, said that the
Oct. 1 cutoff date was very likely but that it might be set back a
few months.
   While the Soviets seeking admission remain in their country,
their applications would be considered both in Moscow and in the
Washington area office.
   Israel has expressed concern that Jewish refugees from the Soviet
Union were increasingly choosing to head for the United States once
out of their homeland, depriving the Jewish state of needed settlers.
   It was not clear whether the change in U.S. procedure would
increase the flow of refugees to Israel.
   The rising exodus from the Soviet Union, which results from U.S.
pressure as well as reforms undertaken by President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, poses administrative and financial problems for the Bush
administration.
   Eager to reinforce the right of Soviet citizens to travel freely,
U.S. officials stress they will keep the door to immigrants open.
But beyond the 50,000 slots allotted for the Soviet Union,
prospective Jewish emigres will be encouraged to apply for parole
status. This requires private support for the immigrants.
   Also, the sources said, in admitting 50,000 refugees from the
Soviet Union preference will be given to those with close relatives
here. But no applicant will be declared ineligble on the grounds he
has no relative here, the officials said.
   Rep. Bruce Morrison, D-Conn., who heads the House subcommittee on
immigration, said as hearings opened that the administration's
proposal provides financing for 84,000 of the 125,000 refugees
overall.
   ``Where do we get the money for the rest?'' he asked a panel of
private witnesses.
   Morrison also expressed concern about the backlog of emigres in
Rome and Vienna awaiting U.S. decisions on their eligibility to
enter the United States. He said the administration had wasted money
through this processing method and changes would have to be
considered.
</TEXT>
