<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0731 09-12 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0731,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Chief Cautions Against Excess Force, Peres Seeks Cabinet Decision</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with army chief of staff cautioning
against violence by troops, details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army chief of staff sent a letter to the
soldiers in the occupied territories cautioning against the use of
excess force when suppressing riots or arresting Palestinians, a
spokesman said Tuesday.
   Also Tuesday, Finance Minister Shimon Peres, head of the
left-leaning Labor Party, said he would demand a Cabinet decision on
Egypt's Middle East peace proposal if Palestinians accept the plan.
   The army gave excerpts from the letter from Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron
to the Itim news agency. The army spokesman said the letter was sent
in the last few days.
   Shomron warned soldiers not to use brutality or to take
unreasonable measures. He gave specific examples such as beating
prisoners in army custody or disrupting ambulances that are
evacuating wounded.
   ``Violence may not be used after a mission has concluded, for
example, or after a demonstration has been dispersed, or after a man
is already in our hands and there is no resistance,'' Shomron wrote.
``In any incident, the passage of ambulances and medical services
must not be prevented.''
   Israel radio said the Justice Ministry recommended that Shomron
send the letter after four soldiers were convicted of brutally
beating an Arab and contributing to his death.
   Shomron said soldiers may use force to disperse violent
demonstrations and to make arrests, ``according to army orders and
the law, from which there can be no deviations.''
   ``In all instances where force is used, one must be strict and
use reasonable force,'' he wrote.
   Meanwhile, officials of Peres' Labor Party intended to bring up
the Egyptian plan for discussion at a meeting Wednesday of the
12-member inner Cabinet, Israel's army radio reported.
   Such a move was likely to increase divisions in the coalition
government over Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's peace plan, which
calls for elections in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip of
Palestinian representatives for talks with Israel.
   The 10-point plan proposed by Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
includes Israeli acceptance of the U.S.-backed concept of trading
land for peace. It also calls for allowing the 140,000 Arabs in
annexed east Jerusalem to vote.
   Those points are acceptable to Labor but not to Likud. The
Israeli proposal worked out by the two parties deliberately leaves
these issues open.
   Shamir, leader of the rightist Likud bloc, has refused to discuss
Mubarak's proposals.
   Peres, speaking on Israel army radio, said he supports most of
Mubarak's plan.
   Peres was asked about Shamir's refusal to discuss the proposals
and replied: ``If it becomes clear that a Palestinian delegation is
ready to come equipped with the 10 points as their position ... the
way to decide is a government meeting. Government discussions are
not somebody's monopoly. If we demand, there is going to be a
meeting.''
   In the occupied territories Tuesday, soldiers shot and wounded 12
Palestinians during clashes with stone-throwing youths, Arab
hospital officials said.
   The army confirmed one injury, saying soldiers shot a teen-ager
in the head when they were met with a hail of stones in the West
Bank village of Sabastiya. Hospital officials said the victim was in
serious condition.
   During the 21-month-old uprising, 567 Palestinians have been
killed in clashes with the army and Israeli civilians. Forty
Israelis also have been slain in the violence.
   The army meanwhile was reported planning a new system of
color-coded identity cards to increase control over Palestinians in
the West Bank. Officials of the military government refused to
confirm or deny the report.
   The daily Yediot Ahronot said the cards would have different
colors or markings to show from which areas residents came and
whether they were suspected of security offenss or crimes.
</TEXT>
