<FIRST>r a AM-LakeLevelDispute 1stLd-Writethru a0723 09-12 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lake Level Dispute, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0723,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Dakota Governor Irate Over Plunging Lake Levels</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `But the ..., to CORRECT total ramps to 39,
sted 30.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALE WETZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An angry Gov. George Sinner took federal
officials on a tour of the Missouri River's largest reservoir
Tuesday, hoping to persuade them to limit the amount of water
released to aid navigation downstream.
   Lake Sakakawea, which pumps $40 million into the North Dakota
economy through tourism, is at historic lows after two
drought-ridden summers and skimpy snow runoff upstream, state and
federal officials say.
   Two planeloads of officials, including Sinner, an assistant Army
secretary and the commander of the Army Corps of Engineers Missouri
River division, toured the giant lake, which has fallen 20 feet
below its normal level for this time of year.
   A public forum was scheduled for early evening.
   The Corps, which has broad authority over water projects, has
been releasing water from Lake Sakakawea and other reservoirs to
keep the Missouri deep enough for boats and barges to navigate in
states downstream. Commercial river traffic is negligible in North
Dakota.
   ``I don't think anything has angered me as much as this
project,'' Sinner said earlier. ``I am literally at my wit's end,
and so are a lot of other people. We have become the fall guys for
the downstream states.''
   Sinner and South Dakota Gov. George Mickelson are pressing for a
change in Corps policy that would emphasize the recreational
benefits of the Missouri system over its navigation _ a change the
Corps says will be difficult to accomplish.
   ``Everybody that's impacted would have to become a party to
agreeing upon such a change,'' said Duane Sveum, chief of the Corps'
Reservoir control center in Omaha, Neb.
   Many businesses, including four big resorts, have grown up around
Lake Sakakawea, which is 178 miles long and has 1,300 miles of
recreational shoreline.
   But the receding lake has left less than half of the lake's 39
boat ramps in the water, and publicity about the situation has
scared away tourists, state officials say.
   The lake's elevation was measured Tuesday at 1,823 feet above sea
level. Corps statistics dating back to 1967 show an average
elevation of 1,843.1 feet at September's end, said Larry Murphy, an
engineer in the Corps' reservoir control center in Omaha, Neb.
   Murphy said the lake had 14.1 million acre-feet of stored water
Tuesday, compared to a record September low of 14.8 million
acre-feet recorded last year.
   Tracy Potter, assistant tourism director for the state Economic
Development Commission, said Lake Sakakawea's elevation needed to be
at 1,830 feet ``to keep everybody in the water and happy.''
   But Sveum said the lake was expected to drop as much as six
additional feet by February.
   A resort owner on the lake's southern Little Missouri arm, Mark
Slater, called on Sinner to declare the region a disaster area, even
though Sinner said that suggestion was impractical.
   Slater closed his own resort Aug. 15, six weeks earlier than
normal, at an estimated loss of $100,000 in revenue.
   ``Since we are selling the lake, it's hard to sell a lake when
you don't have any water,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890912-0196 </DOCNO>
