<FIRST>r i AM-Dominican-Boat     09-12 0135</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dominican-Boat,0139</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Charged With Murder in Capsize of Illegal Emigrants' Boat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two people accused of
organizing a boat voyage of illegal emigrants bound for Puerto Rico
that killed at least 12 passengers were arrested on murder charges
Tuesday, the Dominican navy said.
   The navy said the two, whose identities were not disclosed,
charged their 70 passengers a total of $20,000 for the crossing.
   The 25-foot motorboat capsized in the Mona Passage on Sept. 5
soon after leaving Higuey on the Dominican Republic's east coast,
and the navy said 12 people were known dead, nine survivors were
found and 49 people were missing.
   Hundreds of Dominicans attempt the perilous 110-mile journey each
month in search of jobs in Puerto Rico, a Spanish-speaking U.S.
commonwealth of 3.2 million people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
