<DOCNO> AP890912-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 2058EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia     09-12 0862</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0890</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Suspects Freed; Council Approves Secret Measures to Battle Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, COLOMBIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Security Council has taken
secret measures to stop violence in Medellin, and the government
released two suspected drug traffickers because of lack of evidence,
officials said today.
   Judge Sostenes Zabarain D'Arce of the Public Order Court in
Barranquilla said by telophone that he had no legal reasons for
keeping Bernardo Londono Quintero, 47, and Alberto Orlandez Gamboa,
37, in jail.
   ``There was nothing solid against them _ not in Colombia and not
from the United States,'' the judge said.
   Londono and Orlandez were among hundreds of people seized during
a massive anti-narcotics sweep that began last month. During the
weekend, Colombia's National Drugs Council said the two were being
held for extradition to the United States.
   However, the judge said one suspect was freed Aug. 31 and another
on Sept. 4. The reason for the discrepancy was unclear, and justice
ministry and president's office officials said they were unaware of
the releases.
   U.S. Justice Department spokesman David Runkel said Monday there
was ``no evidence indicating U.S. criminal charges'' against Londono
and Orlandez.
   Meanwhile, the government's National Security Council took
undisclosed measures to stem violence in Medellin, home of the
cartels believed to supply most of the cocaine to the United States.
   The governor's office in Antioquia or state, of which Medellin is
the capital, said the council Monday night extended anti-terrorism
measures to the entire state. But a spokesman, who declined to be
named, said the measures were secret ``for obvious security
reasons.''
   ``We are in total anguish over events in Medellin,'' Helena
Herran de Montoya, the governor of Antioquia said before the meeting.
   Officials fear the crackdown launched against the cocaine cartels
by President Virgilio Barco three weeks ago is turning Medellin into
a war zone.
   Pablo Pelaez Gonzalez, a popular former mayor of Medellin, was
shot and killed Monday when five or six attackers opened fire as he
was driven to work.
   His driver also was killed and a bodyguard wounded. The killers
fled, police said.
   Pelaez was mayor from 1984 through 1986 and founded a local
movement called ``Love for Medellin,'' designed to rid the city of
drug traffickers.
   Near Medellin, attackers on Monday set fire to a farm owned by
the head of the government oil company. A similar attack Sunday
targeted the ranch of a government official who supports turning
over drug traffickers' property to the poor.
   ``The traffickers warned us: government officials,
industrialists, businessmen, journalists, their families and homes
would suffer the consequences of the government's drug war,'' said
Carlos Ossa Escobar, whose ranch was set on fire Sunday by hooded
assailants.
   ``But we have to stand by the president,'' he said in a
television interview.
   About 4,000 soldiers and police already patrol Medellin, where an
11 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew has been in force for two weeks.
   Hundreds have been injured and more than 20 killed as terrorists
retaliate for the crackdown, launched on Aug. 18 when narcotics
gangs killed Sen. Luis Carlos Galan and the police chief of
Medellin. Galan was the leading presidential candidate and an avowed
anti-drug crusader.
   In Vienna, Austria, a U.S. drug enforcement officer hailed
Colombia for its offensive against the Medellin cartel. John C. Lawn
was speaking with colleagues from nearly 100 countries, gathered at
a United Nations conference on anti-drug measures.
   ``The worldwide epidemic of drugs is a war that cannot be won
independent of one another. It requires that we work together,''
Lawn told the conference today. ``The United States applauds the
recent actions taken by the government of Colombia.''
   In an opening speech Monday, Margaret J. Anstee, director general
of the U.N. Office in Vienna, said: ``If Colombia were to lose this
war, we should all be lost,'' she told the conference.''
   Colombia was to be represented at the meeting by a delegation
headed by Miguel A. Gomez Padilla, director general of national
police, but conference sources said the Colombian officials have
failed to show up.
   In Colombia, Justice Minister Monica de Greiff returned from
Washington on Sunday night after meetings with Bush Administration
officials. She met Monday with President Barco, her office said.
   Mrs. de Greiff, whose office handles extraditions, has been
threatened with death by cartel bosses and Monday was flanked by
bodyguards. She eluded journalists by entering and exiting the
ministry through back doors.
   In Atlanta, Eduardo Martinez Romero, the first reputed cartel
member extradited to the United States in more than two years,
pleaded innocent to money laundering charges.
   The government reportedly has signed the extradition orders for
three other alleged traffickers, who are in Colombian jails.
   In Washington, Chief U.S. Justice Department spokesman David
Runkel said the United States wants the extradition of Ana Rodriguez
de Tamayo, 37, who was indicted in Miami in 1983 on federal cocaine
charges.
   A government official said on condition of anonymity that de
Tamayo, Bernardo Londono Quintana and Alberto Orlando Gamboa would
be extradited.
   The three are not, however, in the top echelons of the drug
cartels. The top drug traffickers wanted in the United States remain
at large.
</TEXT>
