<FIRST>r i AM-Angola     09-12 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angola Reports 66 Soldiers Die in Clashes with Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUANDA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military said 66 soldiers died in
clashes with UNITA rebels in the last week, with most of the
fighting in central and south Angola.
   An armed forces statement, released Tuesday in Luanda, said
government forces killed 51 rebels of UNITA _ the National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola _ who attacked the town of Mungo in
central Huambo province.
   It gave no exact date for last week's ``large-scale'' attack but
said eight soldiers were killed and 19 wounded.
   On Sept. 7, government troops also clashed with UNITA 19 miles
southwest of Umpulu in central Bie province, killing seven rebels
and capturing weapons and ammunition, the statement said.
   Military sources said recent rebel attacks were mainly
concentrated in central provinces and southern Huila and Cunene,
where the United Nations Development Program is operating an
economic recovery project.
   But the sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, added that
government troops reinforced their positions in northern provinces
bordering Zaire over the past week.
   The Western-backed rebels have fought to force the
Cuban-supported government to share power since shortly after Angola
gained independence from Portugal in 1975.
</TEXT>
