<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 2203EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Mine     09-12 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Mine,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico Declares Copper Union Contract Void</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TALLI NAUMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities canceled the union contract of
3,000 mineworkers left without jobs after Mexico's largest copper
company went into bankruptcy last month, the government newspaper El
National said Tuesday.
   The former employees of the Cananea Mining Co., 30 miles south of
the Arizona border, will be eligible for severance pay under
national labor laws, the federal labor arbitration board decreed.
That will amount to one-sixth of what they would have received under
liquidation terms of their labor contract.
   Soldiers forced workers from the mine on Aug. 20 after Cananea _
90 percent government-owned _ declared bankruptcy during contract
negotiations.
   Mineworkers appealed the bankruptcy to the arbitration board.
   Cananea is considered the birthplace of trade unionism in Mexico.
The army crushed a labor movement at the mine in 1906. Four years
later, miners rose to the leadership of the Mexican Revolution.
   The bankruptcy administrator, Financiera Nacional Azucarera,
announced the board's decision in a news release, El National said.
   About 1,000 non-union workers will be eligible for severance pay
at the same rate as union members, the administrator said.
   On Monday, President Salinas de Gortari's pledged in a speech to
the Mexican Labor Federation that workers will be allowed to become
part-owners of the mine and mill, which account for 45 percent of
Mexico's copper output.
   He also promised that the mine will not be sold to foreign
investors.
   The government has been trying to sell the copper company as part
of its plan to return nationalized industries to the private sector.
   The mine is expected to be ready to reopen within two months,
when bankruptcy administrators settle accounts, authorities say.
   Local union leaders fear hundreds of members will be refused
employment and will lose rights they established in their contract,
now void.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
