<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia 1stLd-Writethru a0685 09-12 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0685,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reinforcements Sent to Drug Regions; Judge Frees Drug Suspects</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Cocaine and Coffee, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with reinforcements sent to drug regions,
details. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE HANDLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Tuesday beefed up
Colombia's embattled cocaine regions with hundreds of security
forces and said it might appoint military advisers to help mayors of
cities convulsed by violence.
   Also Tuesday, the former mayor of Medellin, Pablo Pelaez
Gonzalez, was buried after a tearful funeral and Mass at City Hall.
Pelaez, 45, was gunned down Monday by gangs believed backed by the
drug cartels.
   Gen. Oscar Botero Estrepo, the minister of defense, said 450
police and hundreds of soldiers were sent to Antioquia state, where
the Medellin drug cartel has waged a war against the government for
its anti-drug crackdown.
   ``The army is paying great attention to the area, especially
Medellin,'' the minister told reporters Tuesday evening.
   More than 4,000 security forces from the army and police have
been patrolling the region since President Virgilio Barco three
weeks ago began confiscating the properties of drug traffickers and
arresting members of the violent cartels.
   Botero said the government is studying measures to send military
advisers to cities terrorized by daily bombings, shootings and arson.
   A judge said Tuesday two suspected drug traffickers the
government earlier said might be extradited to the United States
were released because there was no evidence they were involved in
drug trafficking.
   Judge Sostenes Zabarain D'Arce of the Public Order Court in
Barranquilla, on Colombia's Caribbean coast, said by phone he had no
further reason to hold Bernardo Londono Quintero, 47, or Alberto
Orlandez Gamboa, 37.
   ``There was nothing solid against them _ not in Colombia and not
from the United States,'' the judge said.
   Over the weekend Colombia's National Drugs Council said the two
were being held for extradition to the United States, seemingly to
follow Eduardo Martinez Romero, who was flown last week to Atlanta
to face trial in the United States in connection with drug
money-laundering charges.
   However, the magistrate said he released Orlandez on Aug. 31 and
Londono on Sept. 4.
   The reason for the discrepancy was unclear, and Justice Ministry
and president's office officials said they were unaware of the
releases, which came to light after a Bogota newspaper article
Tuesday.
   Zabarain D'Arce said local authorities failed to press charges
against Londono or Orlandez after the eight-day holding period
permitted in Colombia under special anti-drug emergency measures
decreed last month by Barco.
   U.S. Justice Department spokesman David Runkel said Monday there
was ``no evidence indicating U.S. criminal charges'' against the two.
   Still in custody and possibly facing U.S. extradition, according
to the government, was Ana Rodriguez de Tamayo, 37, indicted on
federal drug charges in 1983 in Florida.
   The governor's office in Antioquia state, of which Medellin is
the capital, said Tuesday the National Security Council, meeting
behind closed doors Monday night, had extended anti-terrorism
measures.
   But a spokesman, who declined to be identified, said the measures
were secret. Medellin and surrounding suburbs are under an 11 p.m.-5
a.m. curfew, with army and police patrols able to enter buildings
and search people at will.
   Meanwhile, more than 400 mourners crammed Medellin's City Hall on
Tuesday to view the flag-draped coffin of Gonzalez, an anti-drug
crusader assassinated on the streets of the cocaine-producing center.
   His assassination came amid an almost daily series of bombings,
shootings and arson by drug traffickers since Barco announced an
unprecedented crackdown on drugs Aug. 18.
   At the funeral, the crowds watched as Pelaez's widow and daughter
placed a cross on the body before the casket _ draped in a green and
white Antioquia state flag _ was closed.
   A military helicopter and armed soldiers in trucks followed the
funeral procession to the burial. Mourners waving white
handkerchiefs lined the streets to the Campos de Paz cemetery.
   Pelaez, mayor of Medellin from 1984-86, had formed a civic group
that urged tough action on drugs and crime in the northwestern city
of 2 million, the headquarters of a cocaine cartel believed
responsible for much of the cocaine entering the United States.
</TEXT>
