<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Hispanics     09-12 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Hispanics,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Salutes New Hispanic Congresswoman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush planted a kiss on the cheek of
the first Cuban-American congresswoman Tuesday night and said her
recent election is just another sign that Hispanic Americans ``have
made it into the mainstream.''
   ``I am so proud of Ileana Ros-Lehtinen for her victory down there
in Florida,'' Bush told nearly 1,000 people who filled a hotel
ballroom for the National Hispanic Heritage Presidential Tribute.
   He said the new Republican congresswoman from Miami, elected Aug.
29 to fill the seat left vacant by the death of Rep. Claude Pepper,
``is going to be a tiger. She is going to be a force to be reckoned
with on Capitol Hill, and boy, do we need her up there for good
common sense.''
   Bush added that he views her election ``as just one more
indication of the fact that Hispanic Americans have made it into the
mainstream, and that more and more are choosing the Republican
Party.''
   Her campaign was run by Bush's son, Jeb, whose Mexican-American
wife, Columba, was also honored at the dinner.
   Bush said Republican National Committee Chairman Lee Atwater, who
emceed the event, ``is driving the Democrat Party right up a wall
the way he is reaching out and bringing people in, opening doors
that have been regrettably closed.
   ``What he's trying to do ... is build it on mainstream values,
and I want all Hispanic Americans to know that they have a home in
the Republican Party,'' said the president.
   Bush himself was credited with helping create during his own days
as GOP chairman in the early 1970s the Republican National Hispanic
Assembly.
</TEXT>
