<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 2219EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Inmates'Infections     09-12 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inmates' Infections,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sheriff Says Overcrowding Not Cause of ``Jail Disease''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Overcrowding at the Harris County jail is not to
blame for a mysterious, flu-like bacterial infection that has killed
two inmates and sickened at least 35, the sheriff testified Tuesday.
   Medical experts have said the illnesses have ``not been caused by
overcrowding in the jail,'' Ssheriff Johnny sKlevenhagen told U.S.
District Judge James DeAnda in opposing a lawsuit attempting to free
as many as 500 misdemeanor prisoners.
   The jail, designed for 4,200 inmates, currently holds 8,300.
Tuesday's hearing was on a motion by attorney James Oitzinger, who
represents inmates in a continuing lawsuit against crowding at the
jail.
   Oitzinger sought the mass release on grounds that crowding may
have contributed to the outbreak of infections by the pneumococcus
bacteria. He also asked the judge to isolate those at risk of
contracting the infection.
   Jail officials say they have yet to identify a common source for
the bacteria.
   Two doctors from the federal Centers for Disease Control in
Atlanta toured the jail Monday with other health officials, but have
yet to comment on their findings.
   Late last week, the bacterial infection killed inmates Ricky
LaBreck, 30, and Rene Antonio Fuentes, 21. Both had previously had
their spleens removed for reasons unrelated to the outbreak, and
doctors said that left them more susceptible to the infection.
   Eighteen more inmates since have been admitted to Ben Taub
Hospital, and the pneumococcus bacteria has been found in five of
them, hospital spokeswoman Nora Shire said Tuesday.
   The others have various flu-like symptoms that may be early signs
of the infection, she said. They also may be sick with the flu or
some other type of mild infection.
   In addition 20 to 30 were being evaluated at the jail infirmary
for flu-like symptoms, said Mark Canfield, chief of epidemiology
with the Harris County Health Department.
   ``We're taking blood to test for various types of viruses for
weakening the immune symptoms,'' Canfield said at an afternoon news
conference. He said there is little data on a vaccine for
pneuococcal disease, but officials are looking into the availability
and use of the vaccine.
   Klevenhagen said medical staff members at the jail were
continuing to screen about 3,200 inmates who said their medical
histories include ailments, like immune system problems, that make
them more susceptible to the infection.
   Although no specific measures were ordered by health authorities,
jail officials voluntarily canceled religious services, recreational
activities and classes Monday.
</TEXT>
