<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 2222EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AmocoCadizDamages     09-12 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amoco Cadiz Damages,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Decreases Awards to French Oyster Growers From 1978 Oil Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired federal judge has decreased the amount
of damages recommended for French oyster growers who lost shellfish
in the 1978 oil spill from the supertanker Amoco Cadiz, attorneys
said Tuesday.
   The adjustment in damages by former U.S. District Court Judge
Frank McGarr may hasten a final judgement in the case and pave the
way for appeals, said New York attorney Barry Kingham, who
represents the oyster growers and other plaintiffs along France's
Brittany coast.
   Denver attorney Frank Cicero, who represents Amoco Corp., the
defendant, said McGarr's action would cut about $11 million, plus
interest, from the total recommended damages, which he now estimated
at $100 million.
   Cicero said McGarr, at Amoco's request, re-examined the testimony
of a shellfish expert and determined that the expert failed to
include include the fact that the French government had already
awarded substantial compensation to the two groups of oystermen
affected by the oil spill.
   McGarr then reduced the possible damages against Amoco by the
amount already paid by the French.
   ``Basically, he's gone back to his original damage estimate,''
Kingham said in a telephone interview. ``He's adjusted it several
times since first delivering it in 1988.''
   McGarr has served as ``special master'' in the case since his
retirement in 1984, shortly after he ruled that Amoco was liable.
His recommendations on damages are being passed on to U.S. District
Judge Charles Norgle, who is expected to rule on the amount of
damages some time before the end of the year.
   ``We intend to appeal all of the damages, including those to the
oyster growers,'' said Kingham, who also represents some 100 French
towns, two counties, hotel keepers and fishermen affected by the oil
spill.
   The Amoco Cadiz struck rocks two miles off the Britanny coast on
March 16, 1978. The huge tanker had lost the use of its rudder and
was under tow through the English Channel by a German-owned tug when
the towlines snapped in hurricane-force winds.
   The resulting 68 million gallon oil slick was 18 miles wide and
80 miles long. It fouled 100 miles of Brittany beaches with tar,
killing thousands of birds and millions of sea creatures.
   By comparison, the Exxon Valdez spill in Alaska's Prince William
Sound was 11 million gallons.
</TEXT>
