<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 2239EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Rather     09-12 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rather,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBS' Rather Says His White House Access Was Affected After Bush Flap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS anchorman Dan Rather says his access to the
White House for news was affected by his famous, combative interview
with President Bush when Bush was the Republican candidate for
President.
   He also said he wasn't sure if the access of other CBS News
staffers had been affected by the incident.
   Rather's comments Monday night on CNN's ``Larry King Live''
didn't make clear how he felt his relations with the Bush White
House had been affected since the headline-making interview.
   The White House has no comment on Rather's remarks, a spokesman
said Tuesday. At CBS, the anchorman was reported busy and
unavailable for comment.
   Rather interviewed Bush without incident several times after
their verbal clash that aired live on Jan. 25 last year on the ``CBS
Evening News.'' But he also was turned down once in requesting an
interview a month after the incident.
   The anchorman was asked by a caller if the flap had affected his
access to the White House for news.
   ``Does it affect my personal access to the White House for news?
The answer is yes,'' Rather said. ``Does it affect CBS News overall
in their access to the White House? I think that is not yet clear.''
   He added that he hoped there had been no affect on access by
other CBS News staffers.
   King asked him if he'd attend a White House state dinner if he
were invited to one.
   ``Well, I haven't been invited,'' Rather replied. ``I'm not in
the habit of turning down invitations I don't have, but the more
important thing is whether you have access to news.''
</TEXT>
