<FIRST>r i AM-Guatemala     09-12 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guatemala,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human Rights Group Says Another Student Kidnapped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A human rights organization said Tuesday
that another student has been kidnapped, the 10th such disappearance
in nearly two months.
   The Mutual Support Group, comprising relatives of missing people,
said in a statement that Eduardo Antonio Lopez Palencia, 24, a
student of chemistry and pharmacology from San Carlos University,
was kidnapped Sunday.
   Palencia's girlfriend contacted them to report the abduction, the
statement said.
   Five other students are missing and presumed kidnapped. Three
students and one professor kidnapped in recent weeks were found dead
on Sunday. They had been shot repeatedly.
   The Association of University Students at San Carlos blamed the
government for the recent violence.
   But the government has said it does not know who is behind the
attacks, which began July 19 with an explosion that destroyed
transmitters belonging to a major television network.
   Neither leftist guerrillas who have been fighting for power for
four decades or rightist death squads notorious for hunting down
suspected leftists have claimed responsibility for the slayings or
the 28 bombings.
   The bomb blasts have killed two people and wounded more than 25.
   President Vinicio Cerezo Arevalo said Tuesday he will raise the
issue at the United Nations. He travels to New York later this month
to address the U.N. General Assembly.
   ``We are the object of aggression to break the continuity of the
democratic process,'' Cerezo told reporters.
   He blamed ``extremists'' but did not elaborate on which groups or
who might be involved.
   The Mutual Support Group said there were about 800 political
murders in Guatemala last year.
   In July, Amnesty International said the military and police keep
operating death, torture and abduction squads.
   The London-based human rights organization said it has reports of
222 people who have disappeared since Cerezo came to power in 1986
after 20 years of military rule.
</TEXT>
