<FIRST>r a AM-ZsaZsaTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0714 09-12 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zsa Zsa Trial, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0714,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Day In Court Draws Smaller Crowd</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to CORRECT writethru sequence; SUBS grafs 9-12,
`Defense attorney ..., with 5 grafs to UPDATE with details of jury selection,
prosecutor comment about Gabor's attire; pick up 10th graf pvs: `A reporter
... </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zsa Zsa Gabor glided into court
Tuesday wearing a leopard-patterned dress, her eighth husband at her
side, for a second day of jury selection in her trial for alleging
slapping a cop.
   ``I feel wonderful, dahlink,'' she told reporters covering her
misdemeanor criminal trial.
   But the audience was far smaller than on opening day.
   Miss Gabor, who appeared in ``Moulin Rouge'' and ``Picture Mommy
Dead,'' drew a crowd of only about 20 when she arrived.
   She was mobbed by about 100 reporters at the courthouse Monday
when jury selection began. Only six reporters were allowed inside,
leaving the rest to chase interviews with fans and bystanders.
   Miss Gabor's leopard-patterned dress was another Donna Karan
creation, as was Monday's black outfit.
   ``Leopard is coming back in,'' she said.
   She was accompanied Monday by her hairdresser, daughter and
eighth husband, Prince Frederick von Anhalt, Germany's Duke of
Saxony. The duke returned Tuesday, but the hairdresser did not.
   Defense attorney William Graysen ended his screening of potential
jurors after a day and a half, asking them if they believe older
people should be treated differently than younger people when
arrested and whether insubordination or profanity should be
considered.
   Graysen said he expected to finish his case early next week. ``Oh
my goodness, I can't make the Pat Sajak show now,'' Miss Gabor
blurted.
   Miss Gabor was asked how deep in her closet she would have to dig
if there were a long trial. ``I have enough clothes for at least a
year,'' she said.
   Prosecutor Elden Fox groused that his closet only held two weeks'
worth of suits. ``If this case runs two weeks I may run out of
suits, but Miss Gabor may not run out of dresses. Will that
influence you?'' he asked prospective jurors.
   At that point, Municipal Court Judge Charles G. Rubin told
ordered prospective jurors to ignore the adversaries' clothing.
   A reporter asked if Miss Gabor had been offered a plea bargain
involving her performing community service and Graysen said it would
be inappropriate to comment. But Miss Gabor said: ``How can I be
punished? I didn't do nothin'.''
   Municipal Judge Charles G. Rubin had imposed a gag order on the
case, attempting to silence the outspoken Miss Gabor and her
supporters.
   She was arrested June 14 after an officer stopped her for having
expired registration on her $215,000 Rolls-Royce Corniche
convertible. She drove off as the officer was checking for other
infractions and then allegedly slapped him when he stopped her again
two blocks later.
   Miss Gabor maintains she was verbally and physically abused by
the officer who she contends has a history of harassing celebrities.
   Miss Gabor pleaded innocent July 12 to charges of misdemeanor
battery on a police officer, disobeying a police officer's orders,
driving with an expired license, having an open bottle of liquor in
her car and having an expired car registration.
   The judge's first question to the prospective jurors Monday
focused on their familiarity with an obscene directive Miss Gabor
claims the officer told her and which she allegedly took as an order
to leave the scene.
   If convicted, she faces a maximum jail term of two years and a
$4,000 fine.
   It wasn't Miss Gabor's first run-in with law enforcement.
   In January, authorities said, she spouted profanities when she
was taken off an airliner in Atlanta because her two dogs were loose
in the plane. A similar incident occurred in 1968 when she illegally
took a dog with her to Spain.
   The Hungarian-born actress Gabor is secretive about her age, but
court documents indicated she was born June 6, 1923, making her 66.
She was a Miss Hungary and her first marriage was to Burhan Belge,
the Turkish ambassador to Hungary.
</TEXT>
