<FIRST>r p AM-NewHavenMayor     09-12 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Haven Mayor,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black State Senator Wins New Haven Democratic Primary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Primary Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Sen. John Daniels soundly defeated
former City Administrator John Stefano Jr. in the Democratic mayoral
primary Tuesday, making it all but certain he would become the
city's first black mayor.
   With all 30 wards reporting, Daniels had 16,018 votes, or 59
percent, to 11,082, or 41 percent, for DeStefano, who had been
endorsed by both the Democratic Party and retiring Democratic Mayor
Biagio DiLieto.
   ``Well, my friends, we did it!'' Daniels, 53, told supporters in
his victory speech, setting off a long round of cheers. ``I accept
this nomination with pride as an African-American ...''
   DeStefano, 34, called Daniels around 8:30 p.m. to concede defeat,
and urged supporters to support him in the general election Nov. 7.
   In the Republican primary, Alderwoman Robie Pooley, 48, defeated
Tobin Hitt, 28, an attorney and political newcomer. Pooley had 1,131
votes and Hitt 709.
   Because Democrats outnumber Republicans 10-to-1, the Democratic
primary winner is all but assured of victory in November. New Haven,
which is home to Yale University, has not had a Republican mayor in
36 years.
   Election officials said 53 percent of the city's 50,963
registered Democrats voted in the primary, the highest turnout since
a 1979 primary.
   DeStefano and Daniels sought to keep the issue of race out of the
campaign, and both sought multi-ethnic support. Blacks represent
about 35 percent and Hispanics about 12 percent of the city's
population of 127,000.
</TEXT>
