<FIRST>r a AM-Penobscots-Recall     09-12 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Penobscots-Recall,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maine Indians Recall Tribal Governor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIAN ISLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Penobscot Indian tribe
voted to remove tribal Gov. Francis Mitchell on Tuesday in an
unprecedented recall election.
   The vote was 241-206, according to a tribe official who spoke on
condition of anonymity. A date for an election to fill the vacancy
would be set within 60 days by the tribal council, the official said.
   Mitchell and Lt. Gov. Philip Guimond, one of Mitchell's harshest
critics, have said they would run in the next election.
   The recall climaxed a months-old power struggle between Mitchell
and the 12-member tribal council over past and future strategies for
investing the Penobscots' share of the $81.5-million Indian
land-claims settlement of 1980.
   A majority of tribal members signed a petition in July demanding
Mitchell's removal.
   The petition includes allegations that Mitchell has failed to
comply with directives from the tribal council, spent tribal funds
and filled certain positions without authorization, intimidated and
harassed employees, and taken actions that jeopardized a business
owned by the tribe.
   Mitchell has said some people dislike his policies of fiscal
austerity, and that he has inherited about $7 million dollars of
debt and an operating deficit that now exceeds $1 million, which he
cites as evidence of past mismanagement.
   Other tribal leaders maintain that there was an operating surplus
when Mitchell took over and that outside audits of tribal finances
have turned up no evidence of any wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
