<FIRST>r f PM-ShuttleAds     09-12 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle Ads,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Pan Am Shuttle Ads Tweak Trump</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan Am Corp.'s new advertising campaign for its
Northeast shuttle service tweaks the owner of its competitor, real
estate tycoon Donald Trump.
   ``On which shuttle will you find the world's most famous investor
in real estate, hotels and transportation?'' the ads ask. They
feature a drawing of the investor, Milburne Pennybags, the
top-hatted, mustachioed character from the Monopoly board game.
   The ads are a gentle swipe at the flamboyant Trump, head of the
rival Trump Shuttle, who also owns the Plaza Hotel, several casinos
in Atlantic City, N.J., and other assets.
   ``This is the second phase of the Pan Am Shuttle `Corporate Jet'
advertising, and it's more aggressive, given the heated-up shuttle
wars,'' Pan Am Shuttle President Harris Herman said in a statement.
``The Monopoly character is a lighthearted portrayal of the
successful business people who are our target market.''
   Pan Am launched its ``Corporate Jet'' ads last last February, in
anticipation of Trump's debut as a competitor. In June, Trump bought
the Eastern Airlines shuttle from Texas Air Corp. for $365 million.
   Both shuttles, which operate hourly flights linking New York to
Boston and Washington, cater mainly to business travelers. One-way
shuttle fares are $99 during peak hours.
   Trump claims his share of the lucrative shuttle market has
doubled since he took over from around 25 percent in early June to
about 50 percent currently. But Pan Am says its shuttle's share, at
around 75 percent when Trump started up, is now holding at roughly
60 percent.
   In the intensifying battle for customers, Pan Am recently
introduced business clubs with computer terminals, facsimile
machines and other equipment for all its shuttle passengers in New
York and Washington.
   Trump Shuttle, meanwhile, said Sunday it plans to give its
weekday passengers $25 American Express Co. gift certificates for
use in restaurants as part of a two-week promotion.
</TEXT>
