<FIRST>r f PM-JunkBonds     09-12 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Junk Bonds,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contradicting Harard Report, Study Says Return on Junk Bonds Good</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new University of Pennsylvania study paints
a fairly optimistic picture for investors in junk bonds,
contradicting a Harvard University report released in April.
   Marshall E. Blume, who conducted the study along with Donald B.
Keim for Penn's Wharton School of Business, acknowledged that from
1977 to 1988 many junk bonds defaulted, the basis of the Harvard
study's conclusions, but he said Monday they still provided adequate
compensation for investors.
   The Harvard study, conducted by Paul Asquith, now a professor at
Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Sloan School of Business,
studied all junk bonds issued in 1977 and 1978. It found that by
Nov. 1, 1988, more than 34 percent of these high-risk, high-yield
bonds defaulted.
   Blume called the Harvard report a catalyst for conducting the
Penn study on the same bonds, which is scheduled for release
Tuesday, but he said he and Keim were not directly challenging
Asquith's findings.
   He said the way researchers approached the investments may have
resulted in the different conclusions on the safety of junk bonds,
which have a rating below investment grade and often are used to
finance corporate takeovers.
   Blume said the Penn study ``states the Harvard study did not
really look at the relevant variables.''
   Blume said he concentrated on the rates of return to investors
rather than the default rate.
   According to Blume, the yield on the junk bonds, which averaged
8.51 percent a year during the period studied, was higher than that
of several other types of investments considered much safer, such as
triple A-rated corporate bonds, which yielded 8.43 percent, and
intermediate-term Treasury issues, which yielded 7.6 percent.
   ``If a bond defaults, that doesn't necessarily mean you lose your
shirt,'' Blume said.
   Exchanged bonds were counted in Asquith's study as defaulted
bonds, Blume said. In some cases, the company may have become a
better credit risk and offered to exchange its junk bonds for
investment-grade bonds to eliminate restrictions often contained in
junk bonds, Blume said.
   However, Blume said, the exchange factor may have affected
Asquith's findings by only 3 percent or 4 percent.
   Asquith was unable to be reached for comment late Monday
afternoon. His office was closed and directory assistance did not
have a listing for him in Boston or Cambridge, Mass.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
