<HEAD>Report: Mall Developer to Offer $1 Billion-Plus for Bloomingdale's</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crown American Corp., the nation's fifth-largest
shopping mall developer, is considering a bid of more than $1
billion for the Bloomingdale's department store chain, a published
report said today.
   Frank J. Pasquerilla, Crown American's chairman and chief
executive, said that the company would make the bid ``if the
operating numbers we are asking for hold up,'' The New York Times
reported.
   Bloomingdale's parent, Toronto-based Campeau Corp., said Friday
it was putting the famous retailer on the block to help ease its
problems in making debt payments.
   Crown American's bid would be made in conjunction with Hess's
Inc., its 76-unit department store chain in the East.
   Campeau's board of directors is scheduled to meet formally today
to consider the proposal from Campeau management to sell New
York-based Bloomingdale's.
   Pasquerilla said he had contaced First Boston Corp., the
investment house, to obtain operating data on Bloomingdale's. He
said he was concerned primarily with the cash flow generated by the
upscale chain. He said any bid would not involve junk bonds, ``which
we don't like.''
   Limited Inc., the nation's largest operator of women's specialty
stores, also is said to be interested acquiring Bloomingdale's, the
Times reported.
   Maus Freres, the Swiss family that owns P.A. Bergner Co., the
Milwaukee retail chain, and Carson Pirie Scott Inc., the Chicago
department store company, also has expressed interest in
Bloomingdale's.
   In addition, Marvin S. Traub, Bloomingdale's chairman, has said
he will try to lead an investor group to buy the chain.
   Crown American owns 33 shopping malls, 19 hotels and other
properties.
</TEXT>
