<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 0757EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UAL     09-12 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot Leaders Confident of Rank-and-File Support for UAL Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the United Airlines pilots union say
they are confident members will divert at least $200 million from a
retirement fund to buy stock in UAL Corp. as part of a $6.75 billion
buyout of the airline's parent company.
   ``Knowing these pilots as I do and knowing the history of this
thing, I think you're going to be oversubscribed in spades,'' said
James Damron, a spokesman for the United chapter of the Air Line
Pilots Association.
   Whether to commit retirement funds to the plan is a personal
choice each of the approximately 6,300 United pilots ALPA represents
will be asked to make, Damron said Monday.
   But rank-and-file approval would not be needed for the new
seven-year pilots contract that is also part of the
employee-management buyout plan, a contract that includes lower pay,
longer hours, shorter vacations and reduced medical benefits.
   ALPA outlined the proposed pilots contract in a 35-page document
mailed or distributed to members of the United chapter on Monday.
   Meanwhile, representatives of California investor Marvin Davis
began an examination of UAL's books to determine whether the Los
Angeles billionaire should raise his competing $6.19 billion offer
for the Chicago-based company.
   United's pilots are spearheading a buyout bid that also includes
UAL management, led by Chairman Stephen Wolf, and British Airways
PLC. Under the proposal, employees would own 75 percent of UAL,
British Airways would own 15 percent and management would own 10
percent.
   United's pilots have been seeking an ownership role in the
nation's second-largest airline since 1987, when union members
contributed $14 million to fund a study of an employee stock
ownership program, Damron said.
   The new pilots contract, replacing one that expired in April
1988, would be a seven-year pact with a no-strike clause.
   About two-thirds of United's pilots _ the senior pilots who
receive higher wages under the so-called A scale _ would have their
pay cut 10 percent.
   The more recently hired B-scale pilots, who earn only 55 percent
as much, would have their pay raised to 70 percent of the A scale
and gain higher pay for flying larger aircraft. They would then take
10 percent cuts as well.
   Pilots would have to work 85 hours a month instead of 80 as
currently required, but they wouldn't be paid for four of the
additional five hours.
   Some pilots would also have their medical benefits reduced via an
increased deductible. The mailing contained no details on the
cutback in vacation time.
   Damron said the pilots would like all of United's employees to
participate in the bid. But the Machinists, the airline's largest
unionized group with 25,000 workers, have expressed skepticism about
the proposed buyout, citing the enormous debt that would be incurred.
   United's 12,700 flight attendants are considering joining the
pilots and were to hear management's proposal today, said Pat
Friend, spokeswoman for the Association of Flight Attendants.
   Asked if the attendants would accept concessions similar to those
the pilot leaders agreed to, she said: ``As far as I know, the
flight attendants are not willing to give up anything. We haven't
for two years.''
   The flight attendants have been without a contract since November
1987.
   Davis and UAL signed a confidentiality agreement Friday giving
Davis access to the company's financial records in exchange for his
promise not to attempt a hostile takeover of the company for one
year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
