<FIRST>r f PM-Stroh-Investor     09-12 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stroh-Investor,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Milwaukee Investor Interested In Share Of Stroh's</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company controlled by a Milwaukee investor is
interested in obtaining a share of Stroh Brewery Co., which holds
the No. 3 ranking among U.S. brewers but has seen its standing erode.
   Christiana Companies Inc., of San Diego, has had discussions with
Stroh for about six weeks, said Sheldon Lubar, who heads Lubar &amp;
Co., a Milwaukee venture capital firm that owns a controlling stake
in Christiana.
   ``That's all it is, discussions,'' Lubar said Monday.
   Lubar, a former director of the Pabst Brewing Co., said
Christiana considered Stroh ``a worthwhile opportunity.''
   ``We are knowledgeable in the industry,'' he said. ``We have had
extensive conversations on the subject. I really can't say anymore.''
   Christiana, primarily a real estate company, has broadened its
holdings in recent months. In July, it bought a controlling interest
in Prideco Inc., a Houston-based supplier to the oil and gas
industry.
   John Collopy, president of the Milwaukee investment firm of
Cleary Gull Reiland McDevitt &amp; Collopy Inc., said he guessed that if
Christiana were successful, it would run Stroh primarily for cash.
   ``I don't think their intent in getting involved there was to
turn it around,'' Collopy said.
   Lacey Logan, a spokeswoman for Detroit-based Stroh, said she
could not confirm whether Stroh had talked with Christiana.
   ``Any negotiations are confidential,'' Ms. Logan said. ``But we
are continuing our search for a minority investment.''
   Stroh has seen its market share drop to 10.7 percent in 1988 from
13 percent in 1983. The company earlier this month cut 300 jobs.
   Stroh announced this year that it was seeking a minority partner
to broaden its scope in the international beer market.
   Among those initially expressing interest was Bond Corp. Holdings
Ltd., a Perth, Australia, company that owns the G. Heileman Brewing
Co.
   More recently, Stroh reportedly has discussed deals with domestic
bidders, including Lubar, the Adolph Coors Brewing Co., and S&amp;P Co.,
owner of Pabst.
   Beer Marketer's Insights, an industry newsletter, said Monday
that Stroh rejected a $500 million bid in August from some of its
top management.
   Some analysts trace Stroh's current woes to its 1982 purchase of
Jos. Schlitz Brewing Co.
   ``The continued decline in the Schlitz brand, combined with the
large amount of overhead (Stroh) bought _ I'm sure that is having a
deleterious effect on (Stroh's) bottom line,'' Collopy said.
</TEXT>
