<FIRST>r f PM-GM-UAW-Cancer     09-12 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GM-UAW-Cancer,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM, UAW Look Into 1 Plant's Cancer Rates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study will begin this week into whether United
Auto Workers union members at a General Motors Corp. plant west of
Detroit have an unusually high brain cancer rate, the union and the
company say.
   The investigation will focus on employee exposure to chemicals at
the plant, which makes car and truck transmissions, GM and UAW
officials said Monday. The study will focus on GM's Hydra-Matic
plant in Ypsilanti, where about 7,300 hourly workers are employed.
   The study will be part of an ongoing investigation by Harvard
University into hazards caused by machine cutting fluids. Earlier
studies in the United States and Europe have linked the fluids to
increased risks of stomach, intestinal and lung cancers, but not
brain cancer.
   The company and the union said the study was prompted by concern
among employees about instances of brain cancer. It isn't known how
many Hydra-Matic workers have had the disease.
   Preliminary results are expected in about six months.
</TEXT>
