<FIRST>u f PM-Manufacturers-Dai-Ichi 1stLd-Writethru   09-12 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Manufacturers-Dai-Ichi, 1st Ld-Writethru,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports: Manufacturers Hanover To Sell Leasing Unit To Big Japanese
Bank</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, Telephone calls ..., with one graf to UPDATE
with Dai-Ichi comment. Picks up 9th graf pvs, Bank analysts ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manufacturers Hanover Corp. said it is discussing
the sale of part of its CIT Group financial services unit to
Japanese banking giant Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd., but the New York
company refused to comment on overseas reports that a deal had been
struck for sale of the entire division.
   Nikkei Telecom, a Japanese financial newswire, and the Japanese
financial newspaper Nihon Keizai Shinbun reported Monday that
Dai-Ichi agreed to buy the CIT subsidiary for $1.5 billion. Both
reports said an announcement would come in a few days.
   The purchase would be the largest purchase of a U.S. company by a
Japanese bank, according to Nihon Keizai Shinbun. It also would be
the first significant U.S. purchase by Dai-Ichi, the world's largest
bank.
   CIT provides loans and leases to medium-sized businesses from
offices nationwide.
   In a terse statement issued a half hour before the stock market
closed Monday, Manufacturers Hanover confirmed ``serious
discussions'' with Dai-Ichi but referred to the proposal as a
``joint ownership of its wholly owned subsidiary, The CIT Group.''
   Manufactuers' stock closed up $2.87{ to $42.50 in composite
trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   John Meyers, a Manufacturers Hanover spokesman, said the bank
would have no further comment on the form the deal might take. ``I
think the statement pretty much speaks for itself,'' he said.
   Dai-Ichi spokesman Yasutoshi Tonegawa said the two sides were
negotiating ``the possibility of capital participation'' in the CIT
group, but he said it was premature to say whether the result would
be a Dai-Ichi buyout or joint ownership.
   Banking analysts said such a deal would come as no surprise.
   ``The bank has indicated that it is in the throes of a
recapitalization plan that could amount to $1.5 to $2 billion, and
as part of that it could sell some of its assets,'' said James J.
McDermott Jr. of Keefe Bruyette &amp; Woods in New York.
   He said there had been speculation the company might increase its
reserves against Third World debt to an average 50 percent from the
current average 32 percent, and therefore need more capital.
   As of June 30, Manufacturers Hanover total loan-loss reserves was
$2.06 billion, down from $2.53 billion a year earlier.
   Manufacturers, the nation's seventh-largest banking company with
assets of $70 billion, purchased CIT from RCA Corp. in 1984 for $1.5
billion. CIT's assets totaled $9.3 billion at the end of last year
and earnings of $120.3 million.
   Dai-Ichi has assets of about $370 billion.
</TEXT>
