<SECOND>PM-Dow-United Technologies,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow, United Technologies Form Joint Venture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Chemical Co. and United Technologies
Corp. today announced a joint venture to make plastics for the
aerospace, defense and automotive industries.
   Terms of the agreement were withheld. The companies said in a
joint statement the venture will focus on making materials for
United Technologies' Sikorsky Aircraft division.
   The new company, Dow-United Technologies Composite Products, will
employ about 500 people at its headquarters in Stratford, Conn., and
others at existing Dow facilities in Midland and the Sikorsky plant
in Tallassee, Ala.
   The companies said worldwide sales for advanced composite parts
were about $1 billion last year and would double by 1993. They
projected first-year sales of the new company of about $75 million,
growing to $600 million by the late 1990s.
   Final papers are to be signed in December with manufacturing to
begin shortly after that, the companies said.
