<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 1056EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-MiniScribe     09-12 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MiniScribe,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Internal Investigation Reveals `Massive Fraud' At MiniScribe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONGMONT, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An internal report released by MiniScribe
Corp. says former senior managers of the computer disk-drive maker
have ``perpetrated a massive fraud'' on the company over the past
three years.
   The report released Monday by MiniScribe, a manufacturer of
computer disk drives, paints a picture of a company run amok under
the direction of then Chief Executive Officer Q.T. Wiles, once known
as the Dr. Fix It of the high-tech industry.
   MiniScribe stock closed Monday at $2.06\ per share in
over-the-counter trading, down 18} cents from Friday and down from
its 1988 high of nearly $14 per share.
   ``It appears that MiniScribe's senior management perpetrated a
massive fraud on the company, its directors, its outside auditors
and the investing public,'' said the report written by an internal
evaluation committee.
   ``This fraud was all the more alarming in that it required the
active participation of many company personnel, and was apparently
common knowledge among a great many other employees.''
   Under pressure from investor lawsuits, MiniScribe initiated the
in-house investigation last March into possible misconduct under the
Wiles administration. A copy of the 1,500-page report that emerged
was given Monday to the enforcement division of the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
   Regulators there will determine if legal action is warranted and
the U.S. Justice Department could become involved if criminal
prosecution is pursued.
   According to the report, MiniScribe was so poorly managed at the
time that senior officials, including Wiles, fabricated company
financial statements with tactics that included shipping bricks and
scrap parts disguised as computer disk drives to confuse auditors.
   Wiles ran the company from April 1985 until his resignation in
February 1989. His entire management team also has departed.
   Wiles, 70, had led MiniScribe through a remarkable turnabout from
April 1985 through 1988. Using $20 million from the venture capital
firm of San Francisco-based Hambrecht &amp; Quist, Wiles brought the
company back from the verge of bankruptcy.
   By injecting MiniScribe with the $20 million and ruthlessly
slashing costs, Wiles boosted sales from $113.9 million in 1985 to a
now-disputed $603 million in 1988.
   MiniScribe reported a $14.6 million loss for the fourth quarter
of 1988. It was shortly thereafter that Wiles stepped down and
essentially disappeared.
   In May, MiniScribe announced that its financial reports for 1986,
1987 and the first three quarters of 1988 were not reliable. On
Monday, the compoany said its restated financial results will show
that the company has a negative net worth.
   Richard C. Rifenburgh, the new chief executive officer, said
Monday, ``It is now up to the company to move forward to solve the
remaining problems.
   ``At the same time, we must ensure that MiniScribe reaps the
benefits of the hard work and the dedication that employees have
exhibited during these difficult times.''
   Despite an anticipated $500 million in sales this year,
MiniScribe will likely post large losses, Rifenburgh said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
