<FIRST>r f PM-Tandy-Datatronic     09-12 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tandy-Datatronic,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tandy to Buy Swedish Computer Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tandy Corporation said today it has
signed a letter of intent to purchase the Victor and Micronic
computer subsidiaries of Datatronic AB of Sweden.
   Sales of Victor and Micronic products exceeded $200 million in
1988, placing Victor among the top personal computer companies in
Europe, Tandy said.
   Tandy will acquire the rights to the Victor and Micronic names
for microcomputers and hand-held computers in the transaction, which
is being made for an undisclosed price. Tandy expects to fund the
acquisition using internal funds and existing borrowing arrangements.
   Victor sells desktop and laptop computers through a network of
2,700 dealers and distributors in Europe. Its primary markets are
medium-size businesses and educational customers, said Philip M.
Bradtmiller, director of investor relations for Tandy.
   He said Victor's market channels will complement Tandy's European
sales through InterTan stores, which supply individual and small
business customers the way its Radio Shack subsidiary does in the
United States.
   Tandy Chairman John V. Roach said Tandy's GRiD division will be
augmented by Micronic's resources in the hand-held computer and
field automation business.
   Bradtmiller said the acquisition will help Tandy prepare for the
changes in Europe brought on by the common market agreement to begin
in 1992.
   The transaction is subject shareholder and regulator approval.
</TEXT>
