<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-BlueArrow     09-12 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Blue Arrow,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Southeastern Asset Management Buys Stake in Blue Arrow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blue Arrow PLC, the world's largest employment
services group, said Tuesday that the U.S. investment management
concern Southeastern Asset Management Inc. has acquired a
7.16-percent holding in the company.
   The announcement comes a week after Southeastern Asset Management
became the largest shareholder in Saatchi &amp; Saatchi PLC by buying a
9.4-percent stake in the advertising and communications giant.
   Blue Arrow Chairman Mitchell Fromstein said from his Milwaukee,
Wisc., office that the company welcomed the shareholding.
   ``They have a knack for spotting value in the service field more
so than many other people,'' Fromstein said.
   ``It doesn't surprise me that they've taken the stake,''
Fromstein said. ``If they took a bigger share, it wouldn't make me
uncomfortable. I'm certain it's a friendly investment.''
   Blue Arrow shares were unchanged at 108 pence, or $1.67, by
midafternoon on London's Stock Exchange.
   A number of recent events have depressed Blue Arrow's share
price. In April, Blue Arrow's former chairman, Tony Berry, was
ousted and replaced by Mitchell Fromstein, the head of employment
services concern Manpower Inc. which Blue Arrow acquired in 1987 in
a $1.34 billion takeover bid.
   The takeover of the Milwaukee-based employment agency tripled
Blue Arrow's size and had created an uneasy alliance between the two
companies' chairmen.
   Blue Arrow shares have lagged on disappointing earnings growth
and news of a government investigation into events surrounding a
controversial $39 million loan which Blue Arrow made last December
to a company controlled by British property developer and yachtsman
Peter de Savary.
</TEXT>
