<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 1527EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PostalATMs     09-12 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Postal ATMs,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Test of ATM Cards to Buy Stamps a Success</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You can buy gas and groceries with your
automated teller card these days, so why not stamps?
   The Postal Service decided to test that question at five offices,
and officials say the program has been a smash so far.
   Using Interlink systems provided by First Interstate Bank, three
Santa Ana post offices and two in Irvine have been accepting the
cards for about two months.
   The system works like this: The customer hands his ATM card to a
postal clerk, who passes the magnetic strip through a reader that
records the customer's name and account number. The customer enters
his secret code and the amount of purchase into a hand-held keyboard.
   ``We are very happy with it,'' said Florinda Bailey, manager of
commercial accounts at the Postal Service's Santa Ana division,
which encompasses most of Orange County and parts of Los Angeles
County.
   The average ATM card purchase is $33.69, up from $27.04 worth of
stamps when the program began and before a promotional program, Ms.
Bailey told The Orange County Register.
   Each system costs about $800, a price expected to drop if the
Postal Service goes ahead with the systems around the nation. The
trial program runs for another 10 months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
