<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 1514EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   09-12 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybean Futures Retreat On Lack Of Frost</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices fell moderately
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, pressured by a lack of
overnight frost in the Midwest and forecasts for improved crop
weather next week.
   Oat and wheat futures also retreated.
   Temperatures dropped into the upper 30s Monday night in parts of
Iowa and Minnesota, not cold enough to damage the maturing crops.
   A National Weather Service six-to-10-day forecast issued late
Monday predicted warmer, drier weather for the Midwest next week,
``and that's just what the crops need,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a
trader for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   After the close, the Agriculture Department issued a new crop
report revising downward its August estimates for 1989 U.S. corn and
soybean production.
   The USDA projected the corn crop at 7.32 billion bushels,
compared with its August estimate of 7.35 billion and last year's
harvest of 4.92 billion.
   The agency pegged 1989 soybean production at 1.89 billion
bushels, compared with last month's estimate of 1.91 billion and
last year's harvest of 1.54 billion.
   The soybean number was near expectations and should have little
market impact; the corn estimate was slightly higher than expected
and could prompt some selling of corn futures on Wednesday.
   At the close, wheat futures were unchanged to 2\ cents lower with
the contract for delivery in September at $3.93 a bushel; corn was
2{ cents to 4 cents lower with September at $2.36 a bushel; oats
were 1} cents to 4 cents lower with September at $1.36{ a bushel;
soybeans were 3 cents to 6\ cents lower with September at $6.03 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
