<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     09-12 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Flat To Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices headed lower in lackluster
trading Tuesday, reflecting continued concerns about overproduction
among some OPEC member nations.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the October contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, fell
6 cents to $19.70 a 42-gallon barrel. The contract had risen 1 cent
on Monday.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange,
wholesale unleaded gasoline for October delivery lost 0.18 cent at
56.89 cents a gallon, after falling 0.02 cent Monday.
   October heating oil, which slipped 0.73 cent the previous
session, ended down 0.64 cent at 55.37 cents a gallon.
   James Steel, an energy analyst at Refco Inc. in New York,
attributed Tuesday's market downturn to internal market influences
and continued concerned that several members of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries were exceeding cartel quotas.
   For instance, he quoted reports that Iran and Iraq were pumping
higher levels of crude oil after recently upgrading production
equipment.
   However, Steel said, strong domestic demand was keeping crude
prices from falling even further than they have in recent days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
