<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 1635EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Paramount     09-12 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Paramount,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profit Declines in 3rd-Qtr Due to Charge for Failed Time Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramount Communications Inc. said Tuesday its
third-quarter profit tumbled 20.1 percent as a hefty charge stemming
from its failed bid for Time Inc. more than offset a strong showing
in entertainment.
   The overall results fell largely within expectations although
some analysts said they were disappointed that Paramount's
publishing operations posted only a modest improvement from a year
ago.
   Paramount, which changed its name from Gulf &amp; Western Inc. in
June, said it earned $96.3 million, or 80 cents per share, for the
three months ended July 31, compared with $120.5 million, or $1 a
share, a year earlier.
   The earnings results reflected a $48.3 million after-tax charge
for costs incurred in Paramount's failed bid for Time. Time, which
had already agreed to merge with Warner Communications Inc.,
rejected the offer from Paramount.
   Analysts said Paramount's charge had been widely anticipated, and
focused on the company's operating income from continuing
operations, which rose 17.3 percent to $145.3 million from $123.9
million.
   Third-quarter revenue rose 19.6 percent to $950.6 million from
$795.1 million a year earlier.
   The revenue figures exclude revenue from The Associates, the
financial services company which Paramount has agreed to sell to
Ford Motor Co. for $3.35 billion in a deal expected to be completed
by Oct. 31. The company failed to provide revenue figures for The
Associates although its results were included in the earnings
figures.
   ``The results were fairly good, despite some weak spots in
publishing,'' said Andrew Wallach, who follows the entertainment
company stocks for Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Jack Kelly, who follows diversified companies for the investment
firm Goldman Sachs &amp; Co., agreed with that assessment, saying
``Publishing was disappointing but entertainment was above
expectations.''
   Paramount said it had record third-quarter operating income from
its entertainment operations as revenue rose substantially at its
motion picture, television and theater operations.
   Wallach said operating income in entertainment rose 48.7 percent
to $57.5 million while revenue rose 23.6 percent to $506.5 million.
   The strong results from motion picture operations reflected the
performances of movies such as ``Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade,
``Pet Sematary'' and ``Major League'' in U.S. markets and ``The
Accused'' and ``Naked Gun'' in foreign markets.
   The company said television operations reflected the success of
``The Arsenio Hall Show'' and ``Star Trek: The Next Generation'' and
that results from its theater operations were up, partly because of
attendance increases generated by a larger number of successful
motion picture releases.
   The Madison Square Garden unit had a loss of unspecified
magnitude, however, due to the closing of the facility for
renovations this summer.
   An increase in results from publishing reflected gains in
educational publishing that more than offset declines in consumer
publishing and professional information operations, the company said.
   Wallach said publishing revenue rose 15.2 percent to $444.1
million, while operating income rose 4.2 percent to $103.9 million.
   He said the Paramount consumer books segment is weak because
``they don't have a hit right now.'' Kelly said orders for old
titles were also sluggish.
   Wallach said the professional information operations, which
consist mainly of a tax information service, generated flat revenue
and increased costs.
   Kelly said the tax service's performance ``may trigger the sale
of the unit over the next few months.''
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Paramount said its
earned $231.1 million, or $1.93 a share, down 4 percent from $240.7
million, or $2 a share, a year earlier.
   Nine-month revenue rose 14.2 percent to $2.42 billion from $2.12
billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
