<FIRST>r f BC-Carolco     09-12 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Carolco,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Rambo' Producer in Joint Venture to Distribute Films for TV</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carolco Pictures Inc. took a big step Tuesday
into the fast-growing foreign market for TV programming, announcing
a joint venture to buy, sell and lease television distribution
rights for movies in markets outside the United States and Canada.
   Carolco, known for producing such action pictures as the
``Rambo'' movies, will team with Paravision International SA, a
subsidiary of L'Oreal SA, in the enterprise. The joint venture will
be called Carolco Paravision Television International V.O.F., with
offices in New York and London.
   Paravision controls TV and video rights for a library of 3,500
feature films, and will give the joint venture selections from that
huge library as well as the services of its worldwide facilities and
employees.
   Carolco International NV, a wholly owned subsidiary of Carolco
Pictures, will contribute all foreign TV rights currently owned by
Carolco and its affiliates, and also all future foreign TV rights
Carolco acquires and foreign TV rights to its own films.
   ``The foreign television marketplace is the fastest-growing
sector of the entertainment industry,'' Carolco co-chairman Mario
Kassar said.
   ``The combination of Carolco's product, the foreign television
expertise of Paravision's management and the opportunities to
acquire additional foreign rights, will establish the partnership as
one of the dominant players in this important market.''
   Carolco has been in turmoil in recent months. Andrew Vajna, who
co-founded the company with Kassar, has been negotiating for several
months to sell his 36 percent share in the company to Kassar.
   And Carolco's stock price has fallen about 10 percent since the
murder last month in Beverly Hills of the chairman of Live
Entertainment Inc. Carolco owns a 49 percent share in Live, a video
company which Carolco had said was expected to contribute
substantially to the Carolco's earnings.
</TEXT>
