<FIRST>u f AM-BerkshireHathaway     09-12 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Berkshire Hathaway,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Berkshire Hathaway Stock Keeps Rising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Berkshire Hathaway Inc. stock, already at
Everest-like heights, gained another $275 a share on Tuesday to
close at $8,575 on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Investors are flocking to Berkshire Hathaway because of the
stock-picking reputation of the holding company's chairman, Warren
Buffett, who is sometimes called the ``oracle of Omaha'' for his
success in choosing solid companies with good long-term prospects.
   The stock is up 80 percent since last Nov. 29, when it began
trading on the New York Stock Exchange at $4,750 a share. Before
that it had been listed over-the-counter.
   Most companies split their stock when it gets too high so that
round lots of 100 shares remain affordable to small investors. But
people familar with Buffett say he likes the special image that the
high price gives to Berkshire Hathaway.
   ``No plans to do anything,'' J. Verne McKenzie, the chief
financial officer, said in a five-word interview Tuesday when asked
whether the company was considering a split.
   The New York Stock Exchange changed its rules last year in a way
that permits Berkshire Hathaway stock to be traded in round lots of
10 shares instead of the usual 100. Extra commission is charged on
smaller, odd lots, but many investors nonetheless buy a single share.
   Berkshire Hathaway's high stock price is the result of having
relatively few shares outstanding. For example, if Exxon Corp. had
as few shares as Berkshire Hathaway, its price per share would be
$14,000 instead of about $45.
   The price of Bershire Hathaway shares is so large, many
newspapers have trouble squeezing the full price of Berkshire
Hathaway into their listings. At The Associated Press, a computer
program that processes stock prices had to be modified Tuesday when
it was discovered that the share price exceeded the program's
previous per-share ceiling of $8,192.
   Berkshire Hathaway has holdings in companies ranging from
Coca-Cola Co. to Gillette Co., Salomon Inc., Capital Cities-ABC
Inc., insurance companies, a candy maker and an encyclopedia
publisher. Buffett's family holding of 45 percent of Berkshire
Hathaway's stock makes him a billionaire.
</TEXT>
