<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-12 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Narrowly Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was narrowly mixed Tuesday, marking
time as traders awaited a batch of economic reports to be issued
later in the week.
   Gold prices also were mixed.
   Traders were reluctant to make significant adjustments to their
positions in advance of the reports due out of Washington on
Thursday and Friday, analysts said.
   The government will issue its August retail sales figures on
Thursday, and on Friday, reports on the July trade deficit and
August producer prices and industrial production will be released.
   The reports are expected to give some indication of how the
economy is faring, and consequently, clues on whether the Federal
Reserve will adjust its policy on interest rates. Dollar traders are
hoping the Fed will tighten credit, which moves interest rates
higher and is bullish for the U.S. currency.
   Analysts said the market was most concerned about the producer
price report, which will indicate whether inflation is accelerating.
If inflation is strengthening, the Fed would be expected to nudge
interest rates upward.
   In overseas trading, there were unconfirmed rumors that the Bank
of Japan intervened in Asian trading. No other central banks were
sighted in the markets during the day.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5470 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.5450 late Monday.
In later New York trading, the pound rose to $1.5485 from $1.5460.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday's
quotes, included: 1.9865 West German marks, unchanged; 1.7140 Swiss
francs, up from 1.7135; 6.6920 Swiss francs, up from 6.6910;
1,422.125 Italian lire, down from 1,425.875; and 1.8725 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.18715.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates
Monday, included: 1.9880 West German marks, up from 1.9875; 1.7160
Swiss francs, up from 1.7150; 6.6950 French francs, down from
6.6970; 2.2330 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2425; 1,421.75 Italian
lire, down from 1,424.75; and 1.1892 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1873.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 1.04 yen to close at 146.73 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 147.08 yen, and in New York, the dollar edged up to
146.905 yen from 146.70 late Monday.
   In New York gold trading, Republic National Bank quoted a late
bid of $385.50 for a troy ounce of gold, up 40 cents from late
Monday, and on the Commodity Exchange, gold edged up 30 cents to
close at $359.50.
   In earlier London trading, gold was unchanged at a late bid of
$358.75 a troy ounce.
   In Zurich, gold was lower, closing at a bid of $358.55 compared
with Friday's $360.00. Markets were closed Monday afternoon in
Zurich for a holiday.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose $1.03 an ounce to close at a bid of
$359.93.
   Silver bullion prices rose in New York after holding steady in
London. On the Commodity Exchange, silver rose 1.8 cents to close at
$5.069 a troy ounce, and in London, the metal was unchanged at a
late bid of $5.08 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
