<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-12 0777</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0803</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coffee Futures Tumble On Dimming Chances For Quota Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee futures prices plunged Tuesday on New York's Coffee, Sugar
&amp; Cocoa Exchange on indications the United States will not support a
return to international export quotas that would raise coffee prices.
   On other markets, sugar futures rose sharply; grains and soybeans
were lower; energy futures weakened; precious metals advanced; and
livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   All New York coffee futures except the contract for September
delivery plunged the permitted daily limit of 6 cents a pound. The
limitless September contract tumbled 6.68 cents to 81.48 cents a
pound, a 2{-week low.
   Analysts said prices plummeted amid panicked selling prompted by
a report that the Bush administration will reject Colombia's plea
for U.S. support in pushing for a resumption of export quotas among
producer members of the International Coffee Organization.
   The 74-nation cartel suspended the quotas in July amid discord
caused in part by U.S. demands for controls on sales of coffee at
cut-rate prices to Soviet-bloc nations that are not ICO members. The
United States is the organization's largest consumer member.
   Coffee prices had strengthened in the past two weeks on
speculation that the Bush administration would take a more
conciliatory stance in ICO talks as part of its war on drugs.
   A return to export quotas would lead to higher coffee prices and
help the economy of Colombia, which needs money to battle cocaine
cartels. Colombian President Virgilio Barco sent a letter to
President Bush lask week, saying the sharp drop in coffee prices
since July 3 was having ``devastating consequences'' on the
Colombian economy and urging Bush to support a return to the coffee
quota system.
   State Department officials would not confirm Tuesday's report
that Bush will reject Barco's plea.
   But in a related development, Sen. Richard Lugar, who sits on the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee, told reporters the United States
will not waver in its opposition to the existing International
Coffee Agreement.
   Sugar futures prices soared in New York after the United States
announced it had raised its 1989 sugar import quota by 860,000
metric tons to 1.99 million and had extended the import quota period
by nine months to Sept. 30, 1990.
   Sugar futures rose .37 cent to .54 cent with October at 13.95
cents a pound.
   Corn and soybean futures fell moderately on the Chicago Board of
Trade, pressured by a lack of overnight frost in the Midwest and
forecasts for improved crop weather next week. Oat and wheat futures
also retreated.
   After the close, the Agriculture Department issued a new crop
report revising downward its August estimates for 1989 U.S. corn and
soybean production and raising its wheat-crop estimate.
   The USDA projected the corn crop at 7.32 billion bushels compared
with its August estimate of 7.35 billion and last year's harvest of
4.92 billion.
   The agency pegged 1989 soybean production at 1.89 billion bushels
compared with last month's estimate of 1.91 billion and last year's
harvest of 1.54 billion.
   The USDA projected total 1989 U.S. wheat production at 2.06
billion bushels compared to last month's estimate of 2.04 billion
and last year's 1.81 billion.
   Analysts termed the soybean number neutral but said the
higher-than-expected corn and wheat estimates could cause futures
prices to drop Wednesday.
   Wheat futures settled 1{ cents lower to \ cent higher with
September at $3.93 a bushel; corn was 2 cents to 4 cents lower with
September at $2.36{ a bushel; oats were 1} cents to 3{ cents lower
with September at $1.36{ a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 6 cents
lower with September at $6.02 a bushel.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 6 cents to 7 cents
lower on the New York Mercantile Exchange with October at $19.70 a
barrel; heating oil was .64 cent lower to .15 cent higher with
October at 55.37 cents a gallon; and unleaded gasoline was .03 cent
to .28 cent lower with October at 56.89 cents a gallon.
   In precious-metals trading on New York's Commodity Exchange, gold
settled 20 cents to 30 cents lower with October at $361.10 a troy
ounce; silver was 1 cents to 1.8 cents lower with September at
$5.069 a troy ounce.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live cattle settled .02 cent
to .55 cent higher with October at 72.22 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .35 cent to .75 cent higher with September at 82.62
cents a pound; live hogs were .17 cent lower to .45 cent higher with
October at 39.20 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .30 cent to
.47 cents higher with February at 46.57 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
