<FIRST>r f AM-OxyPete     09-12 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oxy Pete,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Company Says Wyoming Court Reversed $412 Million Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has reversed a lower
court ruling that would have forced an Occidental Petroleum Corp.
subsidiary to pay more than $412 million in a dispute over the
purchase of natural gas, Occidental said Tuesday.
   The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed a 1986 district
court ruling under which Natural Gas Pipeline Co. of America, a
subsidiary of Occidental's Midcon Corp., would have owed the $412
million to Colorado Interstate Gas Co., a unit of Coastal Corp.,
Occidental said.
   An appeals court panel unanimously reversed the lower court's
ruling that Natural had breached a contract to buy gas from Colorado
Interstate and had attempted to monopolize the market for the
long-distance transportation of natural gas produced in Wyoming.
   The circuit court let stand a ruling under which Natural was
found liable for about $8 million, Occidental said.
   The court also rejected Colorado Interstate's claim that Natural
had attempted to create a monopoly for the Trailblazer Pipeline
system, a group of three pipelines that transport gas out of Wyoming.
   Coastal said in a statement it would appeal the reversal of the
lower court's ruling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
