<FIRST>r f AM-AT&amp;TSuit     09-12 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AT&amp;T Suit,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Computer Maker Sues AT&amp;T</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A maker of computers for government and
industry said Tuesday it had filed a fraud and breach-of-contract
suit against American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., alleging that AT&amp;T
knowingly supplied it with defective computer chips.
   The suit was filed Monday in Los Angeles federal court.
Microprojects Corp. also accuses AT&amp;T of conspiracy and attempt to
monopolize business by supplying the faulty parts to competitors.
   The lawsuit seeks compensatory damages in excess of $20 million,
which would be tripled under antitrust law if the monopoly
allegations are successful, plus $50 million in punitive damages.
   AT&amp;T spokeswoman Marylou Ambrus declined comment, saying the
company's lawyers had not seen the lawsuit.
   Marina del Rey-based Microproject and AT&amp;T agreed in 1986 to
develop Microproject's Unicorn B computer series, using AT&amp;T's Unix
operating system and the WE32100 Unix Microsystem Chip Set from AT&amp;T
as the computer's basic processor, according to Microproject lawyer
Allan Gabriel.
   Microproject began distributing the computers worldwide in 1987.
   The lawsuit alleges that AT&amp;T knew the chip set was defective. It
says AT&amp;T discontinued using that version in its own 3B2 Unix-based
computer line, which competes directly with the Unicorn systems, but
continued to sell the defective chip sets to outside parties.
  
</TEXT>
