<FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 2024EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Datapoint     09-12 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Datapoint,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Datapoint Stock Most Active on New York Stock Exchange</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Datapoint Corp. stock was the most actively
traded Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange, falling 50 cents a
share to $5.37{ as the company's chairman said he and his associates
bought 3 million shares in two days.
   Chairman Asher B. Edelman said the shares purchased Monday and
Tuesday give him and his associates slightly more than 4 million
shares or more than 40 percent of the computermaker's stock, a Dow
Jones &amp; Co. news wire reported.
   More than 2.6 million shares of Datapoint stock changed hands
Tuesday.
   The move comes days after shareholder Martin S. Ackerman launched
a bid to oust Edelman, a New York investor, as Datapoint's board
chairman and install his own slate of directors.
   Ackerman said he will challenge Edelman's stock purchase with
proxies, the Dow Jones Professional Investor Report said. Ackerman
also said he and his associates plan to proceed with their bid to
remove Edelman and his board.
   ``I'm certainly not going away and we intend to file suit in
Delaware soon,'' Ackerman said. The company is incorporated in that
state. ``We clearly intend to challenge the purchase of the share
with proxies. We clearly think it's illegal to disenfranchise
shareholders from their vote by buying shares at above-market
value.''
   Edelman was out of the country Tuesday and not immediately
available for further comment, said Ross Laughead, vice president
and general counsel for San Antonio-based Datapoint.
   Laughead said the company would not comment on Ackerman's
stockholder solicitation until Datapoint files documents pertaining
to it with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   When he initiated the ouster attempt, Ackerman, a New York
attorney who says he revives troubled companies, cited stock
declines and losses exceeding $126 million since Edelman took over
the company in 1985.
   The question should be put to the stockholders within 60 days, he
said.
   Datapoint has about $330 million in annual sales and employs
2,600 people.
</TEXT>
