<FIRST>u f AM-IMFCriticism     09-12 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IMF Criticism,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>IMF Criticizes US on Budget, Taxes, Trade</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: The material underlying this story was released by the IMF under
an embargo of 6 p.m. EDT Wednesday. The embargo has been broken. Also moving
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economic policies of the United States, the
leading member of the International Monetary Fund, were repeatedly
critized and sometimes praised in the fund's annual report Tuesday.
   The 22 banker-diplomats on the Executive Board singled out the
twin trade and budget deficits and the federal tax system for
``concern,'' one of the sharpest words the fund uses.
   ``Concern'' was also expressed, but less often, about policies of
West Germany, Britain and Italy. Japan was urged to speed some
changes.
   The fund uses contributions from its members to help out
countries in economic trouble, usually requiring changes in economic
policy in exchange for its loans. It makes regular appraisals of its
leading members but publishes only a short summary. The U.S.
government has the biggest voting strength in the fund, 19.14
percent.
   The report said brisk economic expansion in the United States
last year contributed to economic growth in the rest of the world.
But it noted ``concerns'' about inflation because the United States
was using its resources so close to capacity.
   Many U.S. experts have had the same worries but have been
reassured by the small size of recent increases in the major price
indexes.
   The report noted previous cuts in the federal deficit but added:
``Concern was expressed that further substantial reductions would
not be forthcoming soon.'' It said, ``The board emphasized the
importance of decisive action to reduce the fiscal deficit.''
   The federal tax system was criticized as discouraging private
saving and distorting investment. The heavy excess of U.S. imports
over exports was called a major source of vulnerability, and
``concern'' was mentioned again because pressures remain strong to
protect American business against foreign competition through trade
barriers.
   The board praised the Federal Reserve for making credit easily
available in response to the stock market crash of 1987, but said
rising interest rates caused ``concern.'' However, U.S. interest
rates have been falling since April, when the fund's fiscal year
ended.
   The word ``concern'' did not appear in the appraisal of Japan,
though it said the Japanese have much to do to speed up improvements
in land management, farming and the distribution system. The
directors said Japan should let in more foreign goods, especially
farm products.
   But they praised Japanese tax reform and what they called the
skillful monetary policy, sound financial policies and the continued
outlook for growth without inflation.
   In West Germany the board said it was ``concerned'' about high
unemployment, the large surplus of exports over imports and the
decision to raise taxes in 1989.
   ``Action on deregulation has been slow and disincentives in some
critical sectors continue to hamper economic activity,'' the report
said without elaboration.
   For Britain, ``concern'' was expressed that ``demand had grown
too rapidly and had begun to show up in higher inflation'' and a
larger trade deficit.
   For Italy, the board said it was ``concerned'' that ``slippages
in controlling public expenditure had set back'' efforts to control
inflation and stabilize interest and exchange rates.
   The report did not go into the issue that is expected to
preoccupy the fund for the next three month: the scheduled increase
in the member contributions, now the equivalent of $118.8 billion.
   Some U.S. officials have said they are yet to be convinced that
the increase is needed. Managing Director Michel Camdessus wants the
total doubled. Others want smaller increases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
