<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-NationalSemiconductor     09-12 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-National Semiconductor,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Semiconductor Posts Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Semiconductor Corp. on
Tuesday posted a $21.9 million loss for the quarter ended Aug. 27.
However, the Santa Clara company said it is still ``on target'' for
a return to profitability in the current quarter.
   The computer chip maker said the loss in the quarter, which is
the first quarter in its fiscal year 1990, represented a significant
improvement over the $98.3 million loss in the fourth quarter of its
fiscal 1989, which included a $45.1 million restructuring charge.
   The company said the most recent loss compares with a loss of
$30.5 million for the same period last year.
   First quarter revenue was $397.6 million, a decrease of 10.6
percent from $449.9 million during the same period a year ago.
   Charles Sporck, National Semiconductor's president, said the
company has slowed production, eliminated surplus inventory and
closed older manufacturing plants in an effort to return to
profitability.
   ``I am particularly encouraged by our continued improved
performance during a quarter which saw flat semiconductor business
conditions, along with pricing pressure, in certain areas,'' Sporck
said.
</TEXT>
